{"title_page": "Bob Gruen", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bob Gruen\n| image              = Bob Gruen.jpg\n| birth_date         = 1945\n| birth_place        = New York, New York, US\n| occupation         = Photographer\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse             = Nadya Beck\n| website            = {{website|http://www.bobgruen.com/|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Bob Gruen''' (born 1945) is an [[United States|American]] author and [[photographer]] known for his rock 'n' roll photographs. Gruen has also appeared in films. \n\nBy the mid 1970s Gruen was already regarded as one of the foremost photographers in music working with major artist such as [[John Lennon]], [[Tina Turner]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Elton John]], and [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]]. He also covered emerging New Wave and Punk bands including the [[New York Dolls]], [[The Clash]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[Ramones]], and [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]].\n\n== Career ==\nGruen was born in [[New York City]]. He credited Ike Turner with starting his career. He first saw [[Ike & Tina Turner]] open for [[Sam & Dave]] at New York's [[Hulu Theater|Felt Forum]] in 1969.<ref name=\":2\" /> He followed the Turners around to other gigs and took photos of them at the [[Honka Monka]] nightclub in [[Queens]] in 1970.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://pleasekillme.com/bob-gruen-ike-tina-turner/|title=Bob Gruen's Electric Photos of Ike & Tina Turner|last=Gruen|first=Bob|date=May 21, 2018|website=PleaseKillMe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gruen showed [[Ike Turner]] the photos and was invited to work with them. \"Ike introduced me to the publicist for their record company who took me to parties and introduced me to more people in the music business,\" he said.<ref name=\":1\" /> Gruen developed friendship with the Turners who invited him to photograph them in California.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tinaturnerblog.com/2012/11/13/the-tina-turner-blog-interview-bob-gruen/|title=Tina Turner Blog Interview: Bob Gruen|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2012|website=Tina Turner Blog|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gruen shot the cover of Ike & Tina Turner's 1971 album [['Nuff Said (Ike & Tina Turner album)|''<nowiki/>'Nuff Said'']].<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2012, Gruen released [[Ike & Tina on the Road: 1971\u201372|''Ike & Tina On The Road: 1971\u201372'']], a documentary he filmed of the Turners at their home in California and on tour across the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nodepression.com/dvd-review-ike-and-tina-on-the-road-1971-72/|title=DVD Review \u2013 Ike and Tina \u201cOn The Road 1971-72\u201d|last=Britt|first=Grant|date=December 20, 2012|website=No Depression|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/165612-ike-tina-on-the-road-1971-72-2495796323.html|title=Imagine This Power Duo Together Again: 'Ike & Tina: On the Road: 1971-72'|last=Butcher|first=Terrence|date=November 26, 2012|website=PopMatters|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2013/10/09/the-other-side-of-ike-and-tina-turner/|title=The other side of Ike and Tina Turner|date=October 9, 2013|website=Page Six|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> \n\nAfter meeting Ike & Tina Turner he began photographing [[Bob Dylan]] and served as [[John Lennon]]'s personal photographer during his time in New York City in 1971. Gruen is best known for his photograph of Lennon wearing a New York City T-shirt. Other notable celebrities and rock bands photographed by Gruen include the [[New York Dolls]], [[The Clash]], [[Ramones]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[Patti Smith Group]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[The Who]], [[David Bowie]], [[Elton John]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Courtney Love]] and [[Green Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2008/04/photographys-ro.html|title=Bob Gruen's Rock 'n' Roll Photo Opening|last=Sun|first=Feifei|date=April 25, 2008|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=February 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs a humanitarian, Gruen has worked with many local and international charities to raise money in support of their life-affirming missions. A partial list includes: [[World Hunger Year|WhyHunger]], Her Justice, [[Tibet House]], The Kristen Ann Carrr Fund, The Donaldson Adoption Institute, [[VH1|Save The Music]], [[MusiCares|MusicCares]], and [[Aperture Foundation]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lennontribute.org/gruen-real-love-award|title=39th Annual John Lennon Tribute|last=|first=|date=|website=39th Annual John Lennon Tribute|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = Bob's magical photos and brilliantly telling captions together present a kaleidoscope of John Lennon's New York Period. It is beautiful, clear, and truthful. I know. I was there.\n| source = \u2014Yoko Ono (John Lennon: The New York Years by Bob Gruen)\n| quoted = 1\n| style = padding:8px;\n| width = 21%\n}}\nIn June 2004, Gruen was presented with [[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo magazine]]'s prestigious Honours List Award for Classic Image in London.\n\nIn 2007, he received the International Society of Photographers Outstanding Achievement Award and the Great Neck Arts Center Artist of Distinction Award.\n\nIn 2010, Gruen was inducted into the [[Long Island Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.limusichalloffame.org/inductees/bob-gruen/|title=Bob Gruen|last=|first=|date=|website=Long Island Music Hall of Fame|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n''Ike & Tina On The Road: 1971\u201372'' won the 2014 ''[[Living Blues]]'' Award for Best [[Blues]] [[DVD]] of 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livingblues.com/lb-awards-2014/|title=2014 Living Blues Awards|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2014|website=Living Blues Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor his many charitable contributions, Gruen received the first ever John Lennon Real Love Award in December 2014 at the 32nd Annual John Lennon Tribute Concert.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Books ==\n* ''The Sex Pistols: Chaos'' (1990), {{ISBN|978-0711921214}}\n* ''The Rolling Stones '''\u2013''' Crossfire Hurricane''  (1997), Genesis Publications\n* ''The Clash'' (2004), {{ISBN|978-1903399347}}\n* ''John Lennon '''\u2013''' The New York Years'' (2005), {{ISBN|978-1584794325}}\n* ''Rockers: The Exhibit''(Cosac Naify, 2007)\n* ''New York Dolls Photographs by Bob Gruen'' (2008), {{ISBN|978-0810972711}}\n* ''Rock Seen'' '''''\u2013''''' Bob Gruen (2011), {{ISBN|978-0810997721}}\n\n== Films ==\n*''All Dolled Up '''\u2013''' A New York Dolls Story'' (2005)\n*''[[Joe Strummer: The Future Is Unwritten]]'' (2007)\n*''Rock 'N' Roll Exposed: The Photography of Bob Gruen'' (2011)\n*''[[LENNONYC]]'' (2010)\n*''New York Dolls '''\u2013''' Lookin' Fine on Television'' (2011)\n*''[[Ike & Tina on the Road: 1971\u201372]]'' (2012)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bobgruen.com Bob Gruen's website]\n* {{IMDb name|0344388}}\n* [http://punkcast.com/1679/index.html Who Shot Rock & Roll - Gail Buckland, Bob Gruen, and Justin Borucki] 2009 Brooklyn Museum panel includes extended presentation by Gruen of his photographs (Video)\n* [http://rockstore.com/Bob-Gruen-Original-Photographs_c10.htm Bob Gruen: Original Photographs]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Rockstore selection\n* [http://viralfashion.com/2013/09/spotlight-bob-gruen-photographer/ Spotlight On: Bob Gruen, Rock 'N' Roll Photographer] 2013 in-depth interview with Gruen on [http://viralfashion.com/ ViralFashion.com]\n* [http://imaginepeace.com/archives/10348 Bob Gruen Interview on imaginepeace.com] 2010 in-depth interview by Randy Patterson of boomerocity.com\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruen, Bob}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Portrait photographers]]\n\n\n{{US-photographer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bob Gruen\n| image              = Bob Gruen.jpg\n| birth_date         = 1945\n| birth_place        = New York, New York, US\n| occupation         = Photographer\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse             = Nadya Beck\n| website            = {{website|http://www.bobgruen.com/|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Bob Gruen''' (born 1945) is an [[United States|American]] author and [[photographer]] known for his rock 'n' roll photographs. Gruen has also appeared in films. \n\nBy the mid 1970s Gruen was already regarded as one of the foremost photographers in music working with major artist such as [[John Lennon]], [[Tina Turner]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Elton John]], and [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]]. He also covered emerging New Wave and Punk bands including the [[New York Dolls]], [[The Clash]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[Ramones]], and [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]].\n\n== Career ==\nGruen was born in [[New York City]]. He credited Ike Turner with starting his career. He first saw [[Ike & Tina Turner]] open for [[Sam & Dave]] at New York's [[Hulu Theater|Felt Forum]] in 1969.<ref name=\":2\" /> He followed the Turners around to other gigs and took photos of them at the [[Honka Monka]] nightclub in [[Queens]] in 1970.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://pleasekillme.com/bob-gruen-ike-tina-turner/|title=Bob Gruen's Electric Photos of Ike & Tina Turner|last=Gruen|first=Bob|date=May 21, 2018|website=PleaseKillMe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gruen showed [[Ike Turner]] the photos and was invited to work with them. \"Ike introduced me to the publicist for their record company who took me to parties and introduced me to more people in the music business,\" he said.<ref name=\":1\" /> Gruen developed friendship with the Turners who invited him to photograph them in California.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tinaturnerblog.com/2012/11/13/the-tina-turner-blog-interview-bob-gruen/|title=Tina Turner Blog Interview: Bob Gruen|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2012|website=Tina Turner Blog|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gruen shot the cover of Ike & Tina Turner's 1971 album [['Nuff Said (Ike & Tina Turner album)|''<nowiki/>'Nuff Said'']].<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2012, Gruen released [[Ike & Tina on the Road: 1971\u201372|''Ike & Tina On The Road: 1971\u201372'']], a documentary he filmed of the Turners at their home in California and on tour across the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nodepression.com/dvd-review-ike-and-tina-on-the-road-1971-72/|title=DVD Review \u2013 Ike and Tina \u201cOn The Road 1971-72\u201d|last=Britt|first=Grant|date=December 20, 2012|website=No Depression|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/165612-ike-tina-on-the-road-1971-72-2495796323.html|title=Imagine This Power Duo Together Again: 'Ike & Tina: On the Road: 1971-72'|last=Butcher|first=Terrence|date=November 26, 2012|website=PopMatters|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2013/10/09/the-other-side-of-ike-and-tina-turner/|title=The other side of Ike and Tina Turner|date=October 9, 2013|website=Page Six|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> \n\nAfter meeting Ike & Tina Turner he began photographing [[Bob Dylan]] and served as [[John Lennon]]'s personal photographer during his time in New York City in 1971. Gruen is best known for his photograph of Lennon wearing a New York City T-shirt. Other notable celebrities and rock bands photographed by Gruen include the [[New York Dolls]], [[The Clash]], [[Ramones]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[Patti Smith Group]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[The Who]], [[David Bowie]], [[Elton John]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Courtney Love]] and [[Green Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2008/04/photographys-ro.html|title=Bob Gruen's Rock 'n' Roll Photo Opening|last=Sun|first=Feifei|date=April 25, 2008|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=February 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs a humanitarian, Gruen has worked with many local and international charities to raise money in support of their life-affirming missions. A partial list includes: [[World Hunger Year|WhyHunger]], Her Justice, [[Tibet House]], The Kristen Ann Carrr Fund, The Donaldson Adoption Institute, [[VH1|Save The Music]], [[MusiCares|MusicCares]], and [[Aperture Foundation]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lennontribute.org/gruen-real-love-award|title=39th Annual John Lennon Tribute|last=|first=|date=|website=39th Annual John Lennon Tribute|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = Bob's magical photos and brilliantly telling captions together present a kaleidoscope of John Lennon's New York Period. It is beautiful, clear, and truthful. I know. I was there.\n| source = \u2014Yoko Ono (John Lennon: The New York Years by Bob Gruen)\n| quoted = 1\n| style = padding:8px;\n| width = 21%\n}}\nIn June 2004, Gruen was presented with [[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo magazine]]'s prestigious Honours List Award for Classic Image in London.\n\nIn 2007, he received the International Society of Photographers Outstanding Achievement Award and the Great Neck Arts Center Artist of Distinction Award.\n\nIn 2010, Gruen was inducted into the [[Long Island Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.limusichalloffame.org/inductees/bob-gruen/|title=Bob Gruen|last=|first=|date=|website=Long Island Music Hall of Fame|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n''[[Ike & Tina on the Road: 1971\u201372|Ike & Tina On The Road: 1971\u201372]]'' won the 2014 ''[[Living Blues]]'' Award for Best [[Blues]] [[DVD]] of 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livingblues.com/lb-awards-2014/|title=2014 Living Blues Awards|last=|first=|date=April 15, 2014|website=Living Blues Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor his many charitable contributions, Gruen received the first ever John Lennon Real Love Award in December 2014 at the 32nd Annual John Lennon Tribute Concert.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Books ==\n* ''The Sex Pistols: Chaos'' (1990), {{ISBN|978-0711921214}}\n* ''The Rolling Stones '''\u2013''' Crossfire Hurricane''  (1997), Genesis Publications\n* ''The Clash'' (2004), {{ISBN|978-1903399347}}\n* ''John Lennon '''\u2013''' The New York Years'' (2005), {{ISBN|978-1584794325}}\n* ''Rockers: The Exhibit''(Cosac Naify, 2007)\n* ''New York Dolls Photographs by Bob Gruen'' (2008), {{ISBN|978-0810972711}}\n* ''Rock Seen'' '''''\u2013''''' Bob Gruen (2011), {{ISBN|978-0810997721}}\n\n== Films ==\n*''All Dolled Up '''\u2013''' A New York Dolls Story'' (2005)\n*''[[Joe Strummer: The Future Is Unwritten]]'' (2007)\n*''Rock 'N' Roll Exposed: The Photography of Bob Gruen'' (2011)\n*''[[LENNONYC]]'' (2010)\n*''New York Dolls '''\u2013''' Lookin' Fine on Television'' (2011)\n*''[[Ike & Tina on the Road: 1971\u201372]]'' (2012)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bobgruen.com Bob Gruen's website]\n* {{IMDb name|0344388}}\n* [http://punkcast.com/1679/index.html Who Shot Rock & Roll - Gail Buckland, Bob Gruen, and Justin Borucki] 2009 Brooklyn Museum panel includes extended presentation by Gruen of his photographs (Video)\n* [http://rockstore.com/Bob-Gruen-Original-Photographs_c10.htm Bob Gruen: Original Photographs]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Rockstore selection\n* [http://viralfashion.com/2013/09/spotlight-bob-gruen-photographer/ Spotlight On: Bob Gruen, Rock 'N' Roll Photographer] 2013 in-depth interview with Gruen on [http://viralfashion.com/ ViralFashion.com]\n* [http://imaginepeace.com/archives/10348 Bob Gruen Interview on imaginepeace.com] 2010 in-depth interview by Randy Patterson of boomerocity.com\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruen, Bob}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Portrait photographers]]\n\n\n{{US-photographer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Twixister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccolades:removed link to avoid excess linking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Gruen"}
{"title_page": "Herb", "text_new": "{{short description|In general rather than botanical use, plant used for flavoring, food, medicine, or perfume}}\n{{about|[[culinary]], medicinal, and spiritual herbs|the botanical usage|herbaceous plant|other uses}}\n[[File:Garden of herbs.jpg|thumb|A variety of herbs are visible in this [[garden]]. Pictured is [[Mentha|mint]], along with some other herbs.]]\n\nGeneral Advice about herbs: Do not consume the glowing herbs or the herbs that defy gravity. If this does occur seek medical help immediately and bury 12 burnt sticks in your yard under a patch of clovers.\n\nIn general use, '''herbs'''<!--please do not change to the singular; this has caused problems over \"an herb\" vs. \"a herb\"--> are plants with savory or aromatic properties that are used for flavoring and [[garnish (food)|garnishing]] food, for medicinal purposes, or for fragrances; excluding [[vegetables]] and other plants consumed for [[macronutrients]]. Culinary use typically distinguishes herbs from [[spices]]. ''Herbs'' generally refers to the [[leaf]]y green or [[flower]]ing parts of a plant (either fresh or dried), while ''[[spices]]'' are usually dried and produced from other parts of the plant, including [[seed]]s, [[Bark (botany)|bark]], [[root]]s and [[fruit]]s.\n\nHerbs have a variety of uses including culinary, medicinal, and in some cases, spiritual. General usage of the term \"herb\" differs between culinary herbs and [[medicinal herb]]s; in medicinal or spiritual use, any parts of the plant might be considered as \"herbs\", including leaves, roots, flowers, seeds, root bark, inner bark (and [[Vascular cambium|cambium]]), [[resin]] and [[pericarp]].\n\nThe word \"herb\" is pronounced {{IPAc-en|h|\u025c\u02d0r|b}} in [[Commonwealth English]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Cambridge Advanced Learners' Dictionary & Thesaurus |publisher=Cambridge University Press |chapter=Herb |chapter-url=http://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/british/herb?q=herb}}</ref> but {{IPAc-en|\u025c\u02d0r|b}} is common among [[North American English]] speakers and those from other regions where [[h-dropping]] occurs. In [[botany]], the word \"herb\" is used as a synonym for \"[[herbaceous plant]]\".\n{{Quote box\n |quote=\"What is a herb?\" \"The friend of physicians and the praise of cooks.\"\n |author = --[[Alcuin]] and his student [[Charlemagne]]<ref name=\"Freeman\" />\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right\n}}\n\n==Definition==\n[[File:The Herb Garden - geograph.org.uk - 1629279.jpg|thumb|Herb garden at [[Hardwick Hall]], [[Derbyshire]], [[England]], originally planted in the 1870s by Lady Louisa Egerton, recreated by the [[National Trust]], largely following the original design.]]\nIn [[botany]], the term herb refers to a [[herbaceous plant]],<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\">{{cite book |title=The Royal Horticultural Society encyclopedia of gardening |publisher=Dorling Kindersley |isbn=9781405303538 |edition=2nd |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pulnPwAACAAJ|pages=404,679}}</ref> defined as a small, [[Spermatophyte|seed-bearing plant]] without a woody stem in which all aerial parts (i.e. above ground) die back to the ground at the end of each [[growing season]].<ref name=\"Allaby2012\">{{cite book |last1=Allaby |first1=Michael |title=A Dictionary of Plant Sciences |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191079030 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DB09DAAAQBAJ}}</ref> Usually the term refers to [[Perennial plant|perennials]],<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> although herbaceous plants can also be [[Annual plant|annuals]] (where the plant dies at the end of the growing season and grows back from seed next year),<ref name=\"Stuart1989\">{{cite book |last1=Stuart |first1=Malcolm |title=The Encyclopedia of herbs and herbalism |date=1989 |publisher=Crescent Books |isbn=978-0517353264 |page=7}}</ref> or [[Biennial plant|biennial]]s.<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> This term is in contrast to [[shrub]]s and [[tree]]s which possess a woody stem.<ref name=\"Allaby2012\" /> Shrubs and trees are also defined in terms of size, where shrubs are less than ten meters tall, and trees may grow over ten meters.<ref name=\"Allaby2012\" /> The word herbaceous is derived from Latin ''herb\u0101ceus'' meaning \"grassy\", from ''herba'' \"grass, herb\".<ref name=\"OED\">{{cite book |title=Oxford dictionary of English. |date=2010 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199571123 |page=819 |edition=3rd |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=anecAQAAQBAJ}}</ref>\n\nAnother sense of the term herb can refer to a much larger range of plants,<ref name=\"Bown1995\">{{cite book |last1=Bown |first1=Deni |title=Encyclopedia of herbs & their uses |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofhe00bown |url-access=registration |date=1995 |publisher=Dorling Kindersley |isbn=978-0751302035 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofhe00bown/page/10 10], 11}}</ref> with culinary, therapeutic or other uses.<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> For example, some of the most commonly described herbs such as [[Salvia|sage]], [[rosemary]] and [[Lavandula|lavender]] would be excluded from the botanical definition of a herb as they do not die down each year, and they possess woody stems.<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> In the wider sense, herbs may be herbaceous perennials but also trees,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> subshrubs,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> shrubs,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> annuals,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[liana]]s,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[fern]]s,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[moss]]es,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[algae]],<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[lichen]]s,<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> and [[fungi]].<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> [[Herbalism]] can utilize not just stems and leaves but also fruit, roots, bark and gums.<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> Therefore, one suggested definition of a herb is a plant which is of use to humans,<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> although this definition is problematic since it could cover a great many plants that are not commonly described as herbs.\n\nAncient Greek philosopher [[Theophrastus]] divided the plant world into trees, shrubs, and herbs.<ref name=\"Bremness1994\">{{cite book |last1=Bremness |first1=Lesley |title=The complete book of herbs |publisher=Viking Studio Books |isbn=9780140238020 |page=8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VqfnrH-W2kwC}}</ref> Herbs came to be considered in three groups, namely [[pot herb]]s (e.g. onions), sweet herbs (e.g. thyme), and salad herbs (e.g. wild celery).<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> During the seventeenth century as [[selective breeding]] changed the plants size and flavor away from the wild plant, pot herbs began to be referred to as [[vegetable]]s as they were no longer considered only suitable for the pot.<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" />\n\n== Culinary herbs ==\n[[File:Thyme-Bundle.jpg|thumb|A bundle of [[Thymus (plant)|thyme (''Thymus'')]]]]\n{{See also|List of culinary herbs and spices}}\nCulinary herbs are distinguished from [[vegetable]]s in that, like spices, they are used in small amounts and provide [[flavor]] rather than substance to [[food]].<ref name=\"Small National Research Council Canada 2006\">{{cite book |last=Small |first=E. |author2=National Research Council Canada |title=Culinary Herbs |publisher=NRC Research Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-660-19073-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UL9lpNrx0kwC&pg=PA1 |access-date=9 October 2018 |page=1}}</ref>\n\nHerbs can be perennials such as [[thyme]], sage or lavender, biennials such as [[parsley]], or annuals like [[basil]]. Perennial herbs can be shrubs such as rosemary (''Rosmarinus officinalis''), or trees such as [[bay laurel]] (''Laurus nobilis'') \u2013 this contrasts with [[Herbaceous plant|botanical herbs]], which by definition cannot be woody plants. Some plants are used as both herbs and spices, such as [[dill]] weed and dill seed or [[coriander]] leaves and seeds. There are also some herbs, such as those in the [[Lamiaceae|mint family]], that are used for both culinary and medicinal purposes.\n\nEmperor [[Charlemagne]] (742\u2013814) compiled a list of 74 different herbs that were to be planted in his gardens. The connection between herbs and health is important already in the European Middle Ages--''[[The Forme of Cury]]'' (that is, \"cookery\") promotes extensive use of herbs, including in salads, and claims in its preface \"the assent and advisement of the masters of physic and philosophy in the King's Court\".<ref name=\"Freeman\">{{cite book |title=Herbs for the Medieval Household, for Cooking, Healing and Divers uses |pages=ix\u2013x |first=Margaret B. |last=Freeman |location=New York |publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art |year=1943}}</ref>\n\n==Herbal teas==\n{{main|Herbal tea}}\nSome herbs can be infused in boiling water to make [[herbal tea]]s (also termed tisanes).<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /><ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> Typically the dried leaves, flowers or seeds are used, or fresh herbs are used.<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> Herbal teas tend to be made from aromatic herbs,<ref name=\"Bremness1994\" /> may not contain [[tannin]]s or [[caffeine]],<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> and are not typically mixed with milk.<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> Common examples include [[chamomile tea]],<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> or [[mint tea]].<ref name=\"Bremness1994\" /> Herbal teas are often used as a source of relaxation or can be associated with rituals.<ref name=\"Bremness1994\" />\n\n== Medicinal herbs ==\n{{Main|Medicinal plants|Herbalism}}\n{{see also|List of plants used in herbalism|}}\n[[File:In Effigiam Nicholai Culpeper Equitis by Richard Gaywood.jpg|thumb|[[Nicholas Culpeper]] was an English [[botany|botanist]], [[Herbalism|herbalist]], [[physician]], and [[astrology|astrologer]].<ref name=\"ODNB\">Patrick Curry: \"Culpeper, Nicholas (1616\u20131654)\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Oxford, UK: OUP, 2004)</ref> (etching by Richard Gaywood between 1644 and 1662)]]\n\nHerbs were used in [[prehistoric medicine]]. As far back as 5000 BCE, evidence that [[Sumer]]ians used herbs in medicine was inscribed on cuneiform.<ref>{{cite book |first=Ruth D. |last=Wrensch |title=The Essence of Herbs |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |year=1992 |page=9}}</ref> In 162 CE, the physician [[Galen]] was known for concocting complicated herbal remedies that contained up to 100 ingredients.<ref name=\"Tapsell\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Tapsell LC, Hemphill I, Cobiac L, Sullivan DR, Fenech M, Patch CS, Roodenrys S, Keogh JB, Clifton PM, Williams PG, Fazio VA, Inge KE |date=2006 |title=Health benefits of herbs and spices: The past, the present, the future |journal=Medical Journal of Australia |volume=185 |issue=4 |pages=S1\u2013S24 |url=http://ro.uow.edu.au/hbspapers/1397/}}</ref>\n\nSome plants contain [[phytochemical]]s that have effects on the body.  There may be some effects when consumed in the small levels that typify culinary \"spicing\", and some herbs are toxic in larger quantities. For instance, some types of herbal extract, such as the extract of St. John's-wort (''[[Hypericum perforatum]]'') or of kava (''[[Piper methysticum]]'') can be used for medical purposes to relieve depression and stress.<ref>{{cite book |author=Adele G Dawson |title=Herbs, Partners in Life: Healing, Gardening and Cooking with Wild Plants |publisher=Bear & Co. |year=2000 |pages=5\u20136}}</ref> However, large amounts of these herbs may lead to toxic overload that may involve complications, some of a serious nature, and should be used with caution. Complications can also arise when being taken with some prescription medicines.\n\nHerbs have long been used as the basis of traditional [[Chinese herbal medicine]], with usage dating as far back as the first century [[Common Era|CE]] and far before. In India, the [[Ayurveda]] medicinal system is based on herbs.  Medicinal use of herbs in Western cultures has its roots in the [[Hippocratic]] (Greek) elemental healing system, based on a quaternary elemental healing metaphor. Famous herbalist of the Western tradition include [[Avicenna]] (Persian), [[Galen]] (Roman), [[Paracelsus]] (German Swiss), [[Nicholas Culpeper|Culpepper]] (English) and the botanically inclined Eclectic physicians of 19th century/early 20th century America ([[John Milton Scudder]], [[Harvey Wickes Felter]], [[John Uri Lloyd]]). Modern pharmaceuticals had their origins in crude herbal medicines, and to this day, some drugs are still extracted as fractionate/isolate compounds from raw herbs and then purified to meet pharmaceutical standards.\n\nThere is a record dated 1226 for '12d for Roses for Baron's Chamber and in 1516 for flowers and rushes for chambers for henry the 9th<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" />\n\nCertain herbs contain psychoactive properties that have been used for both religious and recreational purposes by humans since the early [[Holocene]] era, notably the leaves and extracts of the [[cannabis]] and [[coca]] plants. The leaves of the coca plant have been chewed by people in northern [[Peru]]vian societies for over 8,000 years,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Dillehay T, Rossen J, Ugent D, Karathanasis A, V\u00e1squez V, Netherly P |year=2010 |title=Early Holocene coca chewing in northern Peru |journal=Antiquity |volume=84 |issue=326 |pages=939\u2013953 |doi=10.1017/S0003598X00067004}}</ref> while the use of cannabis as a psychoactive substance dates back to the first century CE in [[China]] and northern [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Ernest Abel |title=Marihuana: The First Twelve Thousand Years |publisher=Springer |location=New York |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-306-40496-2 |url=https://cannabis-truth.yolasite.com/resources/Abel.%20marihuana%20the%20first%20twelve%20thousand%20years.pdf |access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Indigenous Australian]] peoples developed \"[[bush medicine]]\" based on plants that were readily available to them. The isolation of these groups meant the remedies developed were for far less serious diseases than the western illnesses they contracted during colonisation. Herbs such as [[Mentha australis|river mint]], [[Acacia pycnantha|wattle]] and [[eucalyptus]] were used for coughs, diarrhea, fever and headaches.<ref name=\"Tapsell\" />\n\n== Sacred herbs ==\n{{Main|Sacred herb}}\n[[File:Balsamodendron ehrenbergianum00.jpg|thumb|''[[Commiphora gileadensis]]'' (Gilead myrrh)]]\nHerbs are used in many [[religion]]s.  During the monastic era, monks would cultivate herbs alongside vegetables, while others would be set aside in a [[physic garden]] for specific purposes.<ref>{{cite book |title=English Herb Garden |first=Guy |last=Cooper |first2=Gordon I. |last2=Taylor |publisher=Random House |year=1986}}</ref> For example, [[myrrh]] (''Commiphora myrrha'') and [[frankincense]] (''Boswellia'' species) in [[Hellenistic religion]], the [[Nine Herbs Charm|nine herbs charm]] in [[Anglo-Saxon paganism]], [[neem]] (''Azadirachta indica'') leaves, [[Aegle marmelos|bael]] (''Aegele marmelos'') leaves, holy basil or ''tulsi'' (''[[Ocimum tenuiflorum]]''), [[turmeric]] or \"haldi\" (''Curcuma longa''), [[cannabis]] in [[Hinduism]], and [[white sage]] in [[Wicca]]. [[Rastafari movement|Rastafari]] also consider [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] to be a holy plant.\n\n[[Siberia]]n [[shaman]]s also used herbs for spiritual purposes. Plants may be used to induce spiritual experiences for rites of passage, such as [[vision quest]]s in some [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] cultures. The [[Cherokee]] Native Americans use both [[Salvia apiana|white sage]] and [[Cedar wood|cedar]] for spiritual cleansing and [[Smudge stick|smudging]].\n\n== Herbal cosmetics ==\nOriginally there was always doubt in ancient societies, especially in the sceptical medium of western traditions, as to the efficacity of herbal medicines.  The use of [[herbal cosmetics]] dates back to around six centuries ago in the European and Western countries. Mixtures and pastes were often concocted to whiten the face. During the 1940s, herbal cosmetics took a turn with the emerging red lipstick color, with every year gaining a more intense red. Herbal cosmetics come in many forms, such as face creams, scrubs, lipstick, natural fragrances, powders, body oils, deodorants and sunscreens.  They activate through the epithelium of sebaceous glands to make the skin more supple.  Ayurvedic oils are widely used in India, prized for their natural health-giving properties.<ref>{{cite book |first=H. |last=Panda |title=Herbal Cosmetics Handbook |edition=3rd |publisher=Asia-Pacific Business Press |year=2015}}</ref>\n\nOne method and perhaps the best, used to extract natural oils from herbs to make lipstick is [[partition chromatography]].  The process involves separation in watery solution, and then the injection of colour under pressure.\n\n==Strewing herbs==\n{{main|Strewing herb}}\nStrewing herbs are scattered (strewn) over the floors of dwelling places and other buildings. Such plants usually have fragrant or astringent smells, and many also serve as insecticides (e.g. to repel fleas) or disinfectants. For example, [[meadowsweet]] was sometimes strewn across floors in the middle ages because of its sweet smell.<ref name=\"Bown1995\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Apothecary]]\n* [[Herb chopper]]\n* [[Herb farm]]\n* [[International Herb Association]]\n* [[Outline of herbs and spices]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Herbs}}\n* [http://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=786bafc6f6343634fbf79fcdca7061e1&rgn=div5&view=text&node=21:3.0.1.1.13&idno=21#se21.3.182_110 \u00a7&nbsp;182.10 Spices and other natural seasonings and flavorings that are generally recognized as safe], US Code of Federal Regulations\n* [https://www.healthexplanations.com/herbs/ List & Type of Herbs with Images], US Code of Federal Commission\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Herbs| ]]\n[[Category:Food and drink decorations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|In general rather than botanical use, plant used for flavoring, food, medicine, or perfume}}\n{{about|[[culinary]], medicinal, and spiritual herbs|the botanical usage|herbaceous plant|other uses}}\n[[File:Garden of herbs.jpg|thumb|A variety of herbs are visible in this [[garden]]. Pictured is [[Mentha|mint]], along with some other herbs.]]\n\nIn general use, '''herbs'''<!--please do not change to the singular; this has caused problems over \"an herb\" vs. \"a herb\"--> are plants with savory or aromatic properties that are used for flavoring and [[garnish (food)|garnishing]] food, for medicinal purposes, or for fragrances; excluding [[vegetables]] and other plants consumed for [[macronutrients]]. Culinary use typically distinguishes herbs from [[spices]]. ''Herbs'' generally refers to the [[leaf]]y green or [[flower]]ing parts of a plant (either fresh or dried), while ''[[spices]]'' are usually dried and produced from other parts of the plant, including [[seed]]s, [[Bark (botany)|bark]], [[root]]s and [[fruit]]s.\n\nHerbs have a variety of uses including culinary, medicinal, and in some cases, spiritual. General usage of the term \"herb\" differs between culinary herbs and [[medicinal herb]]s; in medicinal or spiritual use, any parts of the plant might be considered as \"herbs\", including leaves, roots, flowers, seeds, root bark, inner bark (and [[Vascular cambium|cambium]]), [[resin]] and [[pericarp]].\n\nThe word \"herb\" is pronounced {{IPAc-en|h|\u025c\u02d0r|b}} in [[Commonwealth English]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Cambridge Advanced Learners' Dictionary & Thesaurus |publisher=Cambridge University Press |chapter=Herb |chapter-url=http://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/british/herb?q=herb}}</ref> but {{IPAc-en|\u025c\u02d0r|b}} is common among [[North American English]] speakers and those from other regions where [[h-dropping]] occurs. In [[botany]], the word \"herb\" is used as a synonym for \"[[herbaceous plant]]\".\n{{Quote box\n |quote=\"What is a herb?\" \"The friend of physicians and the praise of cooks.\"\n |author = --[[Alcuin]] and his student [[Charlemagne]]<ref name=\"Freeman\" />\n |width  = 25%\n |align  = right\n}}\n\n==Definition==\n[[File:The Herb Garden - geograph.org.uk - 1629279.jpg|thumb|Herb garden at [[Hardwick Hall]], [[Derbyshire]], [[England]], originally planted in the 1870s by Lady Louisa Egerton, recreated by the [[National Trust]], largely following the original design.]]\nIn [[botany]], the term herb refers to a [[herbaceous plant]],<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\">{{cite book |title=The Royal Horticultural Society encyclopedia of gardening |publisher=Dorling Kindersley |isbn=9781405303538 |edition=2nd |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pulnPwAACAAJ|pages=404,679}}</ref> defined as a small, [[Spermatophyte|seed-bearing plant]] without a woody stem in which all aerial parts (i.e. above ground) die back to the ground at the end of each [[growing season]].<ref name=\"Allaby2012\">{{cite book |last1=Allaby |first1=Michael |title=A Dictionary of Plant Sciences |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191079030 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DB09DAAAQBAJ}}</ref> Usually the term refers to [[Perennial plant|perennials]],<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> although herbaceous plants can also be [[Annual plant|annuals]] (where the plant dies at the end of the growing season and grows back from seed next year),<ref name=\"Stuart1989\">{{cite book |last1=Stuart |first1=Malcolm |title=The Encyclopedia of herbs and herbalism |date=1989 |publisher=Crescent Books |isbn=978-0517353264 |page=7}}</ref> or [[Biennial plant|biennial]]s.<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> This term is in contrast to [[shrub]]s and [[tree]]s which possess a woody stem.<ref name=\"Allaby2012\" /> Shrubs and trees are also defined in terms of size, where shrubs are less than ten meters tall, and trees may grow over ten meters.<ref name=\"Allaby2012\" /> The word herbaceous is derived from Latin ''herb\u0101ceus'' meaning \"grassy\", from ''herba'' \"grass, herb\".<ref name=\"OED\">{{cite book |title=Oxford dictionary of English. |date=2010 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199571123 |page=819 |edition=3rd |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=anecAQAAQBAJ}}</ref>\n\nAnother sense of the term herb can refer to a much larger range of plants,<ref name=\"Bown1995\">{{cite book |last1=Bown |first1=Deni |title=Encyclopedia of herbs & their uses |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofhe00bown |url-access=registration |date=1995 |publisher=Dorling Kindersley |isbn=978-0751302035 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofhe00bown/page/10 10], 11}}</ref> with culinary, therapeutic or other uses.<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> For example, some of the most commonly described herbs such as [[Salvia|sage]], [[rosemary]] and [[Lavandula|lavender]] would be excluded from the botanical definition of a herb as they do not die down each year, and they possess woody stems.<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> In the wider sense, herbs may be herbaceous perennials but also trees,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> subshrubs,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> shrubs,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> annuals,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[liana]]s,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[fern]]s,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[moss]]es,<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[algae]],<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> [[lichen]]s,<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> and [[fungi]].<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> [[Herbalism]] can utilize not just stems and leaves but also fruit, roots, bark and gums.<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> Therefore, one suggested definition of a herb is a plant which is of use to humans,<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> although this definition is problematic since it could cover a great many plants that are not commonly described as herbs.\n\nAncient Greek philosopher [[Theophrastus]] divided the plant world into trees, shrubs, and herbs.<ref name=\"Bremness1994\">{{cite book |last1=Bremness |first1=Lesley |title=The complete book of herbs |publisher=Viking Studio Books |isbn=9780140238020 |page=8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VqfnrH-W2kwC}}</ref> Herbs came to be considered in three groups, namely [[pot herb]]s (e.g. onions), sweet herbs (e.g. thyme), and salad herbs (e.g. wild celery).<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" /> During the seventeenth century as [[selective breeding]] changed the plants size and flavor away from the wild plant, pot herbs began to be referred to as [[vegetable]]s as they were no longer considered only suitable for the pot.<ref name=\"Stuart1989\" />\n\n== Culinary herbs ==\n[[File:Thyme-Bundle.jpg|thumb|A bundle of [[Thymus (plant)|thyme (''Thymus'')]]]]\n{{See also|List of culinary herbs and spices}}\nCulinary herbs are distinguished from [[vegetable]]s in that, like spices, they are used in small amounts and provide [[flavor]] rather than substance to [[food]].<ref name=\"Small National Research Council Canada 2006\">{{cite book |last=Small |first=E. |author2=National Research Council Canada |title=Culinary Herbs |publisher=NRC Research Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-660-19073-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UL9lpNrx0kwC&pg=PA1 |access-date=9 October 2018 |page=1}}</ref>\n\nHerbs can be perennials such as [[thyme]], sage or lavender, biennials such as [[parsley]], or annuals like [[basil]]. Perennial herbs can be shrubs such as rosemary (''Rosmarinus officinalis''), or trees such as [[bay laurel]] (''Laurus nobilis'') \u2013 this contrasts with [[Herbaceous plant|botanical herbs]], which by definition cannot be woody plants. Some plants are used as both herbs and spices, such as [[dill]] weed and dill seed or [[coriander]] leaves and seeds. There are also some herbs, such as those in the [[Lamiaceae|mint family]], that are used for both culinary and medicinal purposes.\n\nEmperor [[Charlemagne]] (742\u2013814) compiled a list of 74 different herbs that were to be planted in his gardens. The connection between herbs and health is important already in the European Middle Ages--''[[The Forme of Cury]]'' (that is, \"cookery\") promotes extensive use of herbs, including in salads, and claims in its preface \"the assent and advisement of the masters of physic and philosophy in the King's Court\".<ref name=\"Freeman\">{{cite book |title=Herbs for the Medieval Household, for Cooking, Healing and Divers uses |pages=ix\u2013x |first=Margaret B. |last=Freeman |location=New York |publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art |year=1943}}</ref>\n\n==Herbal teas==\n{{main|Herbal tea}}\nSome herbs can be infused in boiling water to make [[herbal tea]]s (also termed tisanes).<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /><ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> Typically the dried leaves, flowers or seeds are used, or fresh herbs are used.<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> Herbal teas tend to be made from aromatic herbs,<ref name=\"Bremness1994\" /> may not contain [[tannin]]s or [[caffeine]],<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" /> and are not typically mixed with milk.<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> Common examples include [[chamomile tea]],<ref name=\"Bown1995\" /> or [[mint tea]].<ref name=\"Bremness1994\" /> Herbal teas are often used as a source of relaxation or can be associated with rituals.<ref name=\"Bremness1994\" />\n\n== Medicinal herbs ==\n{{Main|Medicinal plants|Herbalism}}\n{{see also|List of plants used in herbalism|}}\n[[File:In Effigiam Nicholai Culpeper Equitis by Richard Gaywood.jpg|thumb|[[Nicholas Culpeper]] was an English [[botany|botanist]], [[Herbalism|herbalist]], [[physician]], and [[astrology|astrologer]].<ref name=\"ODNB\">Patrick Curry: \"Culpeper, Nicholas (1616\u20131654)\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Oxford, UK: OUP, 2004)</ref> (etching by Richard Gaywood between 1644 and 1662)]]\n\nHerbs were used in [[prehistoric medicine]]. As far back as 5000 BCE, evidence that [[Sumer]]ians used herbs in medicine was inscribed on cuneiform.<ref>{{cite book |first=Ruth D. |last=Wrensch |title=The Essence of Herbs |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |year=1992 |page=9}}</ref> In 162 CE, the physician [[Galen]] was known for concocting complicated herbal remedies that contained up to 100 ingredients.<ref name=\"Tapsell\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Tapsell LC, Hemphill I, Cobiac L, Sullivan DR, Fenech M, Patch CS, Roodenrys S, Keogh JB, Clifton PM, Williams PG, Fazio VA, Inge KE |date=2006 |title=Health benefits of herbs and spices: The past, the present, the future |journal=Medical Journal of Australia |volume=185 |issue=4 |pages=S1\u2013S24 |url=http://ro.uow.edu.au/hbspapers/1397/}}</ref>\n\nSome plants contain [[phytochemical]]s that have effects on the body.  There may be some effects when consumed in the small levels that typify culinary \"spicing\", and some herbs are toxic in larger quantities. For instance, some types of herbal extract, such as the extract of St. John's-wort (''[[Hypericum perforatum]]'') or of kava (''[[Piper methysticum]]'') can be used for medical purposes to relieve depression and stress.<ref>{{cite book |author=Adele G Dawson |title=Herbs, Partners in Life: Healing, Gardening and Cooking with Wild Plants |publisher=Bear & Co. |year=2000 |pages=5\u20136}}</ref> However, large amounts of these herbs may lead to toxic overload that may involve complications, some of a serious nature, and should be used with caution. Complications can also arise when being taken with some prescription medicines.\n\nHerbs have long been used as the basis of traditional [[Chinese herbal medicine]], with usage dating as far back as the first century [[Common Era|CE]] and far before. In India, the [[Ayurveda]] medicinal system is based on herbs.  Medicinal use of herbs in Western cultures has its roots in the [[Hippocratic]] (Greek) elemental healing system, based on a quaternary elemental healing metaphor. Famous herbalist of the Western tradition include [[Avicenna]] (Persian), [[Galen]] (Roman), [[Paracelsus]] (German Swiss), [[Nicholas Culpeper|Culpepper]] (English) and the botanically inclined Eclectic physicians of 19th century/early 20th century America ([[John Milton Scudder]], [[Harvey Wickes Felter]], [[John Uri Lloyd]]). Modern pharmaceuticals had their origins in crude herbal medicines, and to this day, some drugs are still extracted as fractionate/isolate compounds from raw herbs and then purified to meet pharmaceutical standards.\n\nThere is a record dated 1226 for '12d for Roses for Baron's Chamber and in 1516 for flowers and rushes for chambers for henry the 9th<ref name=\"RHS encyclopedia\" />\n\nCertain herbs contain psychoactive properties that have been used for both religious and recreational purposes by humans since the early [[Holocene]] era, notably the leaves and extracts of the [[cannabis]] and [[coca]] plants. The leaves of the coca plant have been chewed by people in northern [[Peru]]vian societies for over 8,000 years,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Dillehay T, Rossen J, Ugent D, Karathanasis A, V\u00e1squez V, Netherly P |year=2010 |title=Early Holocene coca chewing in northern Peru |journal=Antiquity |volume=84 |issue=326 |pages=939\u2013953 |doi=10.1017/S0003598X00067004}}</ref> while the use of cannabis as a psychoactive substance dates back to the first century CE in [[China]] and northern [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Ernest Abel |title=Marihuana: The First Twelve Thousand Years |publisher=Springer |location=New York |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-306-40496-2 |url=https://cannabis-truth.yolasite.com/resources/Abel.%20marihuana%20the%20first%20twelve%20thousand%20years.pdf |access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Indigenous Australian]] peoples developed \"[[bush medicine]]\" based on plants that were readily available to them. The isolation of these groups meant the remedies developed were for far less serious diseases than the western illnesses they contracted during colonisation. Herbs such as [[Mentha australis|river mint]], [[Acacia pycnantha|wattle]] and [[eucalyptus]] were used for coughs, diarrhea, fever and headaches.<ref name=\"Tapsell\" />\n\n== Sacred herbs ==\n{{Main|Sacred herb}}\n[[File:Balsamodendron ehrenbergianum00.jpg|thumb|''[[Commiphora gileadensis]]'' (Gilead myrrh)]]\nHerbs are used in many [[religion]]s.  During the monastic era, monks would cultivate herbs alongside vegetables, while others would be set aside in a [[physic garden]] for specific purposes.<ref>{{cite book |title=English Herb Garden |first=Guy |last=Cooper |first2=Gordon I. |last2=Taylor |publisher=Random House |year=1986}}</ref> For example, [[myrrh]] (''Commiphora myrrha'') and [[frankincense]] (''Boswellia'' species) in [[Hellenistic religion]], the [[Nine Herbs Charm|nine herbs charm]] in [[Anglo-Saxon paganism]], [[neem]] (''Azadirachta indica'') leaves, [[Aegle marmelos|bael]] (''Aegele marmelos'') leaves, holy basil or ''tulsi'' (''[[Ocimum tenuiflorum]]''), [[turmeric]] or \"haldi\" (''Curcuma longa''), [[cannabis]] in [[Hinduism]], and [[white sage]] in [[Wicca]]. [[Rastafari movement|Rastafari]] also consider [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] to be a holy plant.\n\n[[Siberia]]n [[shaman]]s also used herbs for spiritual purposes. Plants may be used to induce spiritual experiences for rites of passage, such as [[vision quest]]s in some [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] cultures. The [[Cherokee]] Native Americans use both [[Salvia apiana|white sage]] and [[Cedar wood|cedar]] for spiritual cleansing and [[Smudge stick|smudging]].\n\n== Herbal cosmetics ==\nOriginally there was always doubt in ancient societies, especially in the sceptical medium of western traditions, as to the efficacity of herbal medicines.  The use of [[herbal cosmetics]] dates back to around six centuries ago in the European and Western countries. Mixtures and pastes were often concocted to whiten the face. During the 1940s, herbal cosmetics took a turn with the emerging red lipstick color, with every year gaining a more intense red. Herbal cosmetics come in many forms, such as face creams, scrubs, lipstick, natural fragrances, powders, body oils, deodorants and sunscreens.  They activate through the epithelium of sebaceous glands to make the skin more supple.  Ayurvedic oils are widely used in India, prized for their natural health-giving properties.<ref>{{cite book |first=H. |last=Panda |title=Herbal Cosmetics Handbook |edition=3rd |publisher=Asia-Pacific Business Press |year=2015}}</ref>\n\nOne method and perhaps the best, used to extract natural oils from herbs to make lipstick is [[partition chromatography]].  The process involves separation in watery solution, and then the injection of colour under pressure.\n\n==Strewing herbs==\n{{main|Strewing herb}}\nStrewing herbs are scattered (strewn) over the floors of dwelling places and other buildings. Such plants usually have fragrant or astringent smells, and many also serve as insecticides (e.g. to repel fleas) or disinfectants. For example, [[meadowsweet]] was sometimes strewn across floors in the middle ages because of its sweet smell.<ref name=\"Bown1995\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Apothecary]]\n* [[Herb chopper]]\n* [[Herb farm]]\n* [[International Herb Association]]\n* [[Outline of herbs and spices]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Herbs}}\n* [http://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?c=ecfr&sid=786bafc6f6343634fbf79fcdca7061e1&rgn=div5&view=text&node=21:3.0.1.1.13&idno=21#se21.3.182_110 \u00a7&nbsp;182.10 Spices and other natural seasonings and flavorings that are generally recognized as safe], US Code of Federal Regulations\n* [https://www.healthexplanations.com/herbs/ List & Type of Herbs with Images], US Code of Federal Commission\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Herbs| ]]\n[[Category:Food and drink decorations]]\n", "name_user": "Maddiethecoolest", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herb"}
{"title_page": "Interstate 95 in New York", "text_new": "{{Highway detail hatnote|Interstate 95}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=95\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 95 in New York}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Map of northern New York City and southern Westchester County with I-95 highlighted in red\n|maint=[[New York State Department of Transportation|NYSDOT]], [[New York State Thruway Authority|NYSTA]] and [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey|PANYNJ]]\n|length_mi=23.44\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=2014tdr/>\n|established=August&nbsp;14, 1957<ref name=\"1957ihmap\" />\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=NJ|I|95|NJTP||US|1|US|9|US|46}} at the [[New Jersey]] state line on the [[George Washington Bridge]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{Jct|state=NY|US|9|NY|9A|Parkway|Henry Hudson}} in [[Manhattan]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|Parkway|Harlem River}} in Manhattan\n*{{Jct|state=NY|I|87}} in [[Morris Heights, Bronx|Morris Heights]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|US|1}} in [[Tremont, Bronx|Tremont]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|Parkway|Bronx River|NY|895}} in [[Soundview, Bronx|Soundview]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|I|278|I|295|I|678|Parkway|Hutchinson River}} in [[Throggs Neck]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Pelham}} in [[Pelham Bay Park]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|Parkway|Hutchinson River}} in [[Pelham Bay Park]] and [[Eastchester, Bronx|Eastchester]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|US|1}} in [[Pelham, New York|Pelham]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|I|287|US|1}} in [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=CT|I|95|CTTP}} at the [[Connecticut]] state line in [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]\n|counties=[[Manhattan|New York]], [[The Bronx|Bronx]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]]\n|previous_type=NY\n|previous_route=94\n|next_type=NY\n|next_route=95\n}}\n\n'''Interstate&nbsp;95''' ('''I-95''') is a part of the [[Interstate Highway System]] that runs from [[Miami]], [[Florida]], to the [[Canada\u2013United States border]] near [[Houlton, Maine]]. In the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], I-95 extends {{convert|23.50|mi|2}} from the [[George Washington Bridge]] in [[New York City]] to the [[Connecticut]] state line at [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]. From the George Washington Bridge, which carries I-95 across the [[Hudson River]] from [[New Jersey]] into [[New York City]], it runs across [[upper Manhattan]] on the [[Trans-Manhattan Expressway]] and continues east across the [[Harlem River]] on the [[Alexander Hamilton Bridge]] and onto the [[Cross Bronx Expressway]]. In [[the Bronx]], I-95 leaves the Cross Bronx at the [[Bruckner Interchange]], joining the [[Bruckner Expressway]] to its end. North of the interchange with [[Pelham Parkway]], it then continues northeast via the '''New England Thruway''' (which is part of the [[New York State Thruway]] system) out of New York City into [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] and to the Connecticut state line, where I-95 continues on the [[Connecticut Turnpike]].\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Manhattan===\n{{main|Trans-Manhattan Expressway}}\nI-95 enters [[New York (state)|New York]] from [[New Jersey]] on the [[George Washington Bridge]] on a concurrency with [[U.S. Route 1 in New York|U.S. Route&nbsp;1]] (US&nbsp;1) and [[U.S. Route 9 in New York|US&nbsp;9]]. As the bridge's eastern approach enters [[Fort Washington Park (Manhattan)|Fort Washington Park]], I-95 enters exit&nbsp;1, which services [[New York State Route 9A]] (NY&nbsp;9A, the [[Henry Hudson Parkway]]). Access is also provided to [[181st Street (Manhattan)|181st Street]]. After crossing [[Fort Washington Avenue]], the interstate goes underground, providing a ramp to [[178th Street (Manhattan)|178th Street]], which is where US&nbsp;9 forks to [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]. I-95 continues east under [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], entering an interchange with the [[Harlem River Drive]] along with [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Amsterdam Avenue]].<ref name=\"bing\">{{bing maps|url=http://binged.it/1b6Ecrl|title=overview map of Interstate 95|accessdate=September 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===The Bronx===\n{{see also|Cross Bronx Expressway|Bruckner Expressway}}\nAfter exit&nbsp;2, I-95 crosses over the [[Harlem River]] and enters [[the Bronx]], entering an interchange with the [[Major Deegan Expressway]] ([[Interstate 87 (New York)|I-87]]), which is marked both exit&nbsp;1C (following with the Cross Bronx Expressway) and exit&nbsp;3A&nbsp;B (matching with the Trans-Manhattan Expressway). Now the Cross-Bronx Expressway, I-95 and US&nbsp;1 continue east over University Avenue and enter exit&nbsp;2A, which serves [[Jerome Avenue]]. Crossing over the [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse]], the six-lane expressway crosses into exit&nbsp;2B, which is for [[Webster Avenue]]. This interchange also marks the eastern end of the I-95/US&nbsp;1 [[Concurrency (road)|concurrency]]. Passing south of [[Tremont Park]], the Cross Bronx westbound serves exit&nbsp;3, which serves [[Third Avenue (Bronx)|Third Avenue]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n[[File:Cross Bronx Expressway.jpg|thumb|left|Congestion on the Cross Bronx Expressway westbound approaching exit&nbsp;4B]]\nAt East 176th Street, the Cross Bronx Expressway turns southeast, entering exit&nbsp;4A eastbound, which marks the northern terminus of [[New York State Route 895|NY 895]] (Sheridan Boulevard). After crossing the [[Bronx River]], the expressway enters a full interchange, exit&nbsp;4B, with the [[Bronx River Parkway]].<ref name=\"bing\" /> After a curve from the parkway, the Cross Bronx begins paralleling East 177th Street<ref>{{cite act|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1709698&GUID=9518C471-1983-4D22-82B5-15CE7EF4D9A4&Options=&Search= |title=\nA Local Law in relation to renaming two thoroughfares and public places in the Borough of the Bronx, East 177th Street, and to amend the official map of the city of New York accordingly.| number = 2018-035 |date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> and enters exit&nbsp;5A, which connects to [[White Plains Road]] in [[Parkchester, Bronx|Parkchester]]. Continuing southeast, the roadway enters exit&nbsp;5B, Castle Hill Avenue, which is an eastbound-only exit. After Castle Hill Avenue, the route enters exit&nbsp;6A, which reaches the [[Hutchinson River Parkway]] at the [[Bruckner Interchange]]. Changing to the [[Bruckner Expressway]], which runs to the northeast, I-95 enters the Bruckner Interchange with the northern termini of [[Interstate 678|I-678]] and [[Interstate 278|I-278]]; the Cross Bronx Expressway Extension turns southeast along [[Interstate 295 (New York)|I-295]] at the same interchange.<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nAfter the Bruckner Interchange, I-95 crosses Tremont Avenue before crossing over [[Interstate 695 (New York)|I-695]] (the Throgs Neck Expressway). Southbound, exit&nbsp;7A serves I-695, while northbound the two interstates merge. Continuing north, the Bruckner Expressway and I-95 parallel Bruckner Boulevard and run along the western edge of [[Pelham Bay Park]]. Entering exit&nbsp;8A southbound services Westchester Avenue while northbound, exits&nbsp;8B and 8C serve the [[Pelham Parkway (road)|Pelham Parkway]] and Shore Road through the park, which marks the northern end of the Bruckner Expressway. Now known as the New England Thruway, I-95 leaves Pelham Bay Park and enters exit&nbsp;9, a junction with the Hutchinson River Parkway. In the middle of the interchange with the Hutchinson River, exit&nbsp;10 forks to the left, reaching [[Gun Hill Road (Bronx)|Gun Hill Road]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nNow paralleling Baychester Avenue, which also services exit&nbsp;11 and Bartow Avenue, the New England Thruway continues north and enters exit&nbsp;12 which connects to [[Baychester, Bronx|Baychester]]. Conner Street is connected to via exit&nbsp;13 before I-95 turns east and crosses over the [[Hutchinson River]]. After crossing the river, the route enters an interchange once again with the Hutchinson River Parkway (exit&nbsp;14) but this time westbound only.<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\n===Westchester===\n[[File:NewEngThruway.svg|75px|thumb|Shield for the New England Thruway used between 1958 and 1970.]]\nCrossing through the northern reaches of Pelham Bay Park, I-95 turns more northeast and enters [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]]. Now in [[Pelham Manor, New York|Pelham Manor]], the route crosses through [[Pelham Country Club]], entering exit&nbsp;15, which connects to US&nbsp;1 (Main Street). After US&nbsp;1, the route crosses out of the Pelham Country Club, entering [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nCrossing over [[Metro-North Railroad]] tracks, the interstate turns northeast and crossing through downtown New Rochelle, reaching exit&nbsp;16, serving several local streets including Cross Avenue, Cedar Street and Garden Street. North of exit&nbsp;16, the New England Thruway enters its lone [[open road tolling|toll gantry]] along the alignment, serving the northbound direction only. The road continues northeast through New Rochelle, passing exit&nbsp;17 as it enters [[Mamaroneck (town), New York|the town of Mamaroneck]]. Exit&nbsp;17 connects to Chatsworth Avenue in the [[Larchmont, New York|Larchmont]] section.  Passing a pedestrian footbridge for the [[Larchmont (Metro-North station)|Larchmont station]], crossing over [[New York State Route 125|NY&nbsp;125]] (Weaver Street). Winding north through Mamaroneck, I-95 enters exit&nbsp;18A, servicing Fenimore Road in the [[Mamaroneck (village), New York|village of Mamaroneck]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nTurning northeast again, I-95 enters exit&nbsp;18B, a [[partial cloverleaf interchange]] with [[Mamaroneck Avenue]] before crossing into the town of [[Harrison, New York|Harrison]]. The road turns east, crossing over [[New York State Route 127|NY&nbsp;127]] (Harrison Avenue), and enters exit&nbsp;19, the western terminus of the [[Playland Parkway]], which connects the expressway to [[Rye Playland]] as the road enters [[Rye, New York|Rye]]. The route crosses through the Rye Village area, entering exit&nbsp;20, which connects to US&nbsp;1 ([[Boston Post Road]]) and the village. Almost immediately after exit&nbsp;20, exit&nbsp;21 marks the eastern end of the [[Cross-Westchester Expressway]] ([[Interstate 287|I-287]]). Proceeding westbound, exit&nbsp;21 and nearby exit&nbsp;22 (Midland Avenue and [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]) are merged, but are separate exits going eastbound. Crossing through the eastern edges of Port Chester, I-95 reaches the [[Byram River]] and crosses into [[Connecticut]], becoming the [[Connecticut Turnpike]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed|section|date=July 2016}}\n[[Robert Moses]] first recommended the construction of what became the New England Thruway in 1940. Construction began in 1951, but major work on the highway did not commence until 1956-1957. By 1950, the [[New York State Thruway Authority]] assumed control of the construction and made the New England Thruway a part of the Thruway toll system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/03/19/archives/city-speeds-highway-programs-expressways-arterial-roads-designed-to.html|title=CITY SPEEDS HIGHWAY PROGRAMS; Expressways, Arterial Roads Designed to Handle New Traffic Patterns to Result From Two Projected State Thruways|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=1950-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Construction lasted until 1961.\n\nI-95 was assigned on August&nbsp;14, 1957, as part of the establishment of the [[Interstate Highway System]],<ref name=\"1957ihmap\">{{cite map |publisher=[[American Association of State Highway Officials]] |title=[[Media:Interstate Highway plan August 14, 1957.jpg|Official route numbering for the National System of Interstate and Defense Highways]] |date=August 14, 1957}}</ref> and has always run along its current path in New York. The route was overlaid on the under-construction New England Thruway northeast of [[New York City]] and assigned to the then-proposed [[Cross Bronx Expressway|Cross Bronx]] and [[Bruckner Expressway]]s through [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite map |title=New York and New Jersey Tourgide<!--sic--> Map |publisher=[[Gulf Oil Company]] |cartography=[[Rand McNally and Company]] |year=1960}}</ref> The thruway opened in October 1958, connecting the Bruckner Expressway and the [[Connecticut Turnpike]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/10/05/archives/to-connecticut-new-england-thruway-to-open-direct-route-from-bronx.html|title=TO CONNECTICUT; New England Thruway to Open Direct Route From Bronx to Rhode Island|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=1958-10-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The final sections of the Cross Bronx and Bruckner Expressways were finished in 1963 and 1972, respectively. Prior to the 1972 completion of the Bruckner, coinciding with the completion of the new [[Bruckner Interchange]], the old [[Bruckner Boulevard]] (once part of [[New York State Route 164 (1940\u20131960s)|NY&nbsp;164]]) was used by through traffic.<ref>{{cite map |title=New York and Metropolitan New York |publisher=[[Sinclair Oil Corporation]] |year=1964 |cartography=Rand McNally and Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite map |title=New York State Highways |publisher=[[New York State Department of Commerce|State of New York Department of Commerce]] |year=1969 |cartography=Rand McNally and Company}}</ref>\n\n===Exit numbers===\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\nThe first change to exit numbers along the New England Thruway section of Interstate&nbsp;95 was in April&nbsp;1980 when the section was converted for sequential exits.<ref>{{cite news|title=New England Thruway exit numbers to change|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252010%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2520-%25202287.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4fe404d3%26DocId%3D1561709%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D4%26hits%3D292%2B293%2B2a6%2B2a7%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252010%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2520-%25202287.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4fe404d3%26DocId%3D1561709%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D4%26hits%3D292%2B293%2B2a6%2B2a7%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=April 20, 2017|work=Gannett Westchester Newspapers|date=February 7, 1980|page=D3}}</ref> Prior to the change, the Cross Bronx Expressway and New England Thruway sections had different exit numbering systems. More specifically, exit 19 on the Cross Bronx Expressway was followed immediately by exit 2 on the New England Thruway. As a result, because exit numbers on I-95 repeated themselves in close succession, the old exit numbering system frequently caused confusion.<ref>{{cite web | title=New England Thruway to Get New Exit Numbers; Last Exit to New York | website=The New York Times | date=February 17, 1980 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1980/02/17/archives/new-england-thruway-to-get-new-exit-numbers-last-exit-to-new-york.html | access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs part of an experiment, I-95 was one of the few roads in New York to receive mileage-based exit numbers. This was implemented over both the Port Authority section and the NYSDOT section of the highway (Exits 1A through 8C). The Thruway section (which had originally carried its own sequential exit numbers) was then renumbered by the Thruway Authority to a system of sequential numbers starting from 9 (where the mileage-based system left off). This led to a situation in which Exits 1 through 8 were mileage based (all but one of which contained lettered suffixes as a result) and Exits 9 through 22 were sequential.\n\nAround 2005, NYSDOT began a project to renumber I-95 with sequential numbers throughout. However the idea never fully got traction with all three agencies. The Port Authority did complete the renumbering on its section of the road. NYSDOT itself renumbered only one section of the road in Parkchester. Meanwhile, the Thruway Authority did not renumber any of the exits on its stretch of the road. This led to a situation from 2005 through 2012 in which some exits were signed with two different numbers, while some numbers were repeated twice, but only on some of the signs.\n\nFinally, in 2012, NYSDOT restored the mileage-based numbers to its portion of the highway, which once again line up with the Thruway portion. This has eliminated all of the exit number conflicts, with one exception. The exception exists because the Port Authority has not changed the numbers back on its portion of the road creating a confusing situation at the Amsterdam Avenue exit, which is maintained by NYSDOT southbound but the Port Authority northbound. The exit is signed as Exit 1B southbound (which is the proper number within the mileage-based), but as Exit 2 northbound (a holdover from the failed renumbering project).\n\n==Exit list==\nExit numbers on the New England Thruway (north of exit 8C) are sequential, but exit numbers on the remaining section are mileage-based.\n{{NYinttop|old|length_ref=<br><ref name=\"2014tdr\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/NYSDOT_Traffic_Data_Report_2014.pdf |title=2014 Traffic Data Report for New York State |date=July 22, 2016 |format=PDF |page=79 |publisher=[[New York State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=inventory>{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/HighwayInventory-NewYorkCounty-2016.zip |title=New York County Inventory Listing |date=August 7, 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Transportation |format=CSV |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/HighwayInventory-BronxCounty-2016.zip |title=Bronx County Inventory Listing |date=August 7, 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Transportation |format=CSV |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/HighwayInventory-WestchesterCounty-2016.zip |title=Westchester County Inventory Listing |date=August 7, 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Transportation |format=CSV |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=google>{{google maps |url=https://goo.gl/maps/wv2qcLjgZ9r |title=Interstate 95 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Jctint|old\n|river=[[Hudson River]]\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.00\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|I|95|dir1=south|NJTP||dir2=south|US|1|US|9|dir3=south|dir4=south|US|46|dir5=west|name5=[[George Washington Bridge]]|location1=[[New Jersey]]|location2=[[Philadelphia]]}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[New Jersey]] at the river's center; eastern terminus of US&nbsp;46\n}}\n{{Jctbridge|old\n|mile=0.00\n|mile2=0.43\n|type=toll\n|bridge=[[George Washington Bridge]] (northbound toll plaza in New Jersey)\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|county=New York\n|cspan=2\n|location=Washington Heights\n|borough=Manhattan\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.43\n|old=1\n|exit=1\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|9|dir1=north|NY|9A|Parkway|Henry Hudson|road=[[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] / [[178th Street (Manhattan)|West 178th Street]] / West 181st Street|location1=[[Midtown Manhattan|Downtown]]|city2=Yonkers}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 9 [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]]; southbound access via Lower Level lanes; exit 14 on NY 9A&nbsp;/ H.H. Parkway\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=1.16\n|old=2\n|exit=2\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Harlem River|dir1=south|road=[[Amsterdam Avenue (Manhattan)|Amsterdam Avenue]]&nbsp;/ University Avenue|location1=[[Manhattan]]}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; exit 24 on H.R. Drive\n}}\n{{jctbridge|old\n|river=[[Harlem River]]\n|mile=1.24\n|mile2=1.41<!--countyline=1.34, +0.07-->\n|type=trans\n|bridge=[[Alexander Hamilton Bridge]]<br>(Route transition between [[Trans-Manhattan Expressway|Trans-Manhattan]] and [[Cross Bronx Expressway]]s)\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|county=Bronx\n|cspan=26\n|location=Morris Heights\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=3\n|mile=1.41<!--+0.07-->\n|mspan=2\n|old=2\n|exit=1B\n|type=incomplete\n|road=To [[Amsterdam Avenue (Manhattan)|Amsterdam Avenue]]\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; shared ramp with exits 1C\u2013D\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=none\n|old=3\n|exit=3<br>1C\u2013D\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|87|name1=[[Major Deegan Expressway]]|city1=Albany|location2=[[RFK Bridge]]|location3=[[Yankee Stadium]]}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 1C (north) and 1D (south) southbound; signed as exit 3 northbound<ref>In Manhattan, I-95 is maintained by the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey|Port Authority of NY-NJ]], who signs it as exit 3, whereas in The  Bronx, I-95 is maintained by NYCDOT, who signs it as exits 1C-1D.</ref>\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=2.08<!--+0.74-->\n|old=4\n|exit=2A\n|road=[[Jerome Avenue]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Tremont\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=2\n|mile=2.66<!--+1.32-->\n|old=5\n|exit=2B\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|1|dir1=north|name1=[[Webster Avenue]]}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 1 concurrency; northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=2.95<!--+1.61-->\n|old=6\n|exit=3\n|road={{jct|state=NY|road|[[Third Avenue (Bronx)|Third Avenue]]|US|1|dir2=north|name2=[[Webster Avenue]]|to2=yes}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=West Farms\n|borough=Bronx\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=3.97<!--+2.63-->\n|old=7\n|exit=4A\n|road={{jct|state=NY|NY|895|dir1=south|name1=Sheridan Boulevard|location1=[[RFK Bridge]]|location2=[[Hunts Point Market]]}}\n|notes=Southbound exit via exit 4B; former I-895\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Soundview\n|borough=Bronx\n|mile=4.34<!--3.00-->\n|old=8\n|exit=4B\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NY|road|Rosedale Avenue|Parkway|Bronx River|to2=yes|dir2=north}}\n|notes=Southbound entrance via exit 4A; exit 4 on Bronx Parkway; serves [[Bronx Zoo]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Parkchester\n|borough=Bronx\n|mile=5.05<!--+3.71-->\n|old=9\n|exit=5A\n|road=[[White Plains Road]]&nbsp;/ [[Westchester Avenue]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Castle Hill\n|borough=Bronx\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=5.60\n|old=10\n|exit=5B\n|road=Castle Hill Avenue\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Throggs Neck\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=4\n|mile=5.76<!--+4.42-->\n|old=11\n|exit=6A\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|678|dir1=south|location1=[[Whitestone Bridge]]|city1=Queens|road=[[Bruckner Boulevard]]}}\n|notes=[[Bruckner Interchange]]; no northbound access to Bruckner Boulevard; northern terminus of I-678\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=5.81<!--+4.47-->\n|mspan=2\n|exit=6B\n|old=12\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|278|dir1=west|location1=[[RFK Bridge]]|city2=Manhattan}}\n|notes=[[Bruckner Interchange]]; southbound exit and northbound entrance; eastern terminus of I-278\n}}\n{{jctplace|old\n|mile=none\n|type=trans\n|place=Route transition between [[Cross Bronx Expressway|Cross Bronx]] and [[Bruckner Expressway]]s\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=6.02<!--+4.68-->\n|type=incomplete\n|old=12\n|exit=6B\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|295|dir1=south|location1=[[Throgs Neck Bridge]]}}\n|notes=[[Bruckner Interchange]]; northbound exit and southbound entrance; northern terminus of I-295\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Schuylerville\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=2\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=7.40\n|mspan=2\n|old=13\n|exit=7A\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|695|dir1=south|to2=to|I|295|dir2=south|location1=[[Throgs Neck Bridge]]|city2=Long Island}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; northern terminus of I-695\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=none\n|old=14\n|exit=7B\n|road=[[Tremont Avenue|East Tremont Avenue]]\n|notes=Southbound exit only\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Country Club\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=2\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=7.70\n|old=15\n|exit=7C\n|road=Country Club Road&nbsp;\u2013 [[Pelham Bay Park]]\n|notes=Northbound exit and entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=8.40\n|old=16\n|exit=8A\n|road=Westchester Avenue\n|notes=Southbound exit and entrance\n}}\n{{Jctint|old\n|location_special=[[Pelham Bay Park]]\n|lspan=4\n|mile=8.66<!--+7.32-->\n|mspan=3\n|old=17\n|exit=8B\n|road=[[Orchard Beach, New York|Orchard Beach]], [[City Island, Bronx|City Island]]\n|notes=Access via [[Shore Road (Bronx)|Shore Road]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=none\n|old=18\n|exit=8C\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Pelham|dir1=west}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Pelham Parkway\n}}\n{{jctplace|old\n|mile=none\n|type=trans\n|place=Route transition between [[Bruckner Expressway]] and New England Thruway\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=8.99<!--+7.65-->\n|mspan=2\n|old=1<br>19\n|exit=9\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Hutchinson River|dir1=north|road=Erskine Place&nbsp;/ Palmer Avenue}}\n|notes=Exit 4 on Hutchinson Parkway; signed for Palmer northbound, Erskine southbound\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Baychester\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=3\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=none\n|old=2\n|exit=10\n|roa