B\n|road=Mamaroneck Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Mamaroneck (village), New York|Mamaroneck]], [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]]\n|notes=Signed as 18A (east) and 18B (west) southbound; serves [[Mamaroneck station]]\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|location=Rye\n|lspan=4\n|area=city\n|mile=20.91<!--+8.92-->\n|old=11\n|exit=19\n|road=[[Playland Parkway]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]], [[Harrison, New York|Harrison]]\n|notes=Western terminus of Playland Parkway\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=22.14<!--+10.15-->\n|old=12\n|exit=20\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|1|dir1=south|city1=Rye|areadab1=city}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=22.54<!--+10.55-->\n|mile2=22.68<!--+10.69-->\n|mspan=2\n|old=13\n|exit=21\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|287|dir1=west|US|1|dir2=north|city1=White Plains|location2=[[New Tappan Zee Bridge|Tappan Zee Bridge]]}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of I-287; no southbound signage for US 1; serves [[Port Chester station]]\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=none\n|old=14\n|exit=22\n|road=Midland Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]], [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]]\n|notes=Northbound exit only\n}}\n{{jctint|old\n|river=[[Byram River]]\n|mile=23.44<!--+11.45-->\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=CT|I|95|CTTP||dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=New Haven}}\n|notes=Bridge; continues into [[Connecticut]] as the [[Connecticut Turnpike]]\n}}\n{{jctbtm|col=8|keys=concur,incomplete,toll,trans}}\n\n==Auxiliary routes==\n===Current===\n* [[Interstate 295 (New York)|I-295]] runs southeast from the [[Bruckner Interchange]] along the [[Cross Bronx Expressway]], then south over the [[Throgs Neck Bridge]] and [[Clearview Expressway]] to its terminus at [[Hillside Avenue (Queens)|Hillside Avenue]], just south of the [[Grand Central Parkway]].<ref name=\"2017log\">{{cite book |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/operating/oom/transportation-systems/repository/2017%20tour-bk.pdf |format=PDF |title=Official Description of Highway Touring Routes, Bicycling Touring Routes, Scenic Byways, & Commemorative/Memorial Designations in New York State |author=[[New York State Department of Transportation]] |date=January 2017 |accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref> It was once signed as part of [[Interstate 78 in New York|I-78]]<ref name=\"RPA-WorldClass-2011\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Lower Manhattan Road Killed Under State Plan |first=Francis X. |last=Cliness |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/03/25/archives/lower-manhattan-road-killed-under-state-plan.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 25, 1971 |page=78 |accessdate=April 14, 2010}}</ref> and was planned to terminate at the [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]].<ref name=\"NYTimes-JFK-VanWyck-Oct1968\">{{cite news|last1=Fowle|first1=Farnsworth|title=Van Wyck Roads Are Under Study: Better Use of Service Lanes Sought for Kennedy Traffic|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9901E7DD1130E034BC4B51DFB6678383679EDE&legacy=true|accessdate=March 15, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 23, 1968}}</ref><ref name=\"RPA-ExpresswayPlans-1964\">{{cite journal|title=Expressway Plans|journal=[[Regional Plan Association|Regional Plan News]]|date=May 1964|issue=73-74|pages=1\u201318|url=https://archive.org/details/regionalplannews7374regi|accessdate=February 27, 2017|publisher=[[Regional Plan Association]]}}</ref><ref name=\"RPA-WorldClass-2011\">{{cite web|last1=Zupan|first1=Jeffrey M.|last2=Barone|first2=Richard E.|last3=Lee|first3=Mathew H.|title=Upgrading to World Class: The Future of the New York Region's Airports|url=http://www.rpa.org/pdf/RPA-Upgrading-to-World-Class.pdf|publisher=[[Regional Plan Association]]|accessdate=March 15, 2017|date=January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924092424/http://www.rpa.org/pdf/RPA-Upgrading-to-World-Class.pdf|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Interstate 495 (New York)|I-495]] runs from the [[Queens&ndash;Midtown Tunnel]] east along the [[Long Island Expressway]] to [[Riverhead, New York|Riverhead]], crossing I-295 in [[Queens]].<ref name=\"2017log\"/> It was once planned to continue west to I-95 in [[New Jersey]]; that part is now [[Lincoln Tunnel]] and [[New Jersey Route&nbsp;495]]. It was also to go east and meet I-95 again in either Connecticut or in Rhode Island. This would have made I-495 a [[bypass (road)|bypass road]] for I-95.<ref>{{cite book| title=Expressway Plans |date=1964 |work=Regional Plan Association |via=nycroads.com | url=http://www.nycroads.com/history/expwy-plans/ | access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Interstate 695 (New York)|I-695]] is a short route along the [[Throgs Neck Expressway]], connecting I-295 to I-95 in [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"2017log\"/> It was once signed as part of I-78.<ref>{{cite map |title=New York State Highways |publisher=[[New York State Department of Commerce|State of New York Department of Commerce]] |year=1969 |cartography=[[Rand McNally and Company]]}}</ref>  The number had been used for other plans, including a route parallel to [[Woodhaven Boulevard]] and an upgrade of the [[West Side Highway]] and [[Henry Hudson Parkway]].\n===Former===\n* [[New York State Route 895|I-895]], also known as the Sheridan Expressway, was a short connection from I-278 to I-95 in [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"2017log\"/> It was planned to continue north from I-95 to rejoin it near [[Pelham Bay Park]], making it another bypass road.<ref name=\"SheridanStudy-Dec2013\">{{cite web |title = The Sheridan Expressway Study: Reconnecting the Neighborhoods Around the Sheridan Expressway and Improving Access to Hunts Point |url = http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/plans-studies/sheridan-hunts-point/final_full_report.pdf |access-date = February 19, 2017 |publisher = [[Government of New York City|City of New York]] |date = December 2013|page=3 }}</ref><ref name=\"30YrsOfProgress\">{{cite book |title = 30 Years of Progress: 1934-1965 |date = June 9, 1964 |publisher = New York City Department of Parks and Recreation |url = https://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_about/parks_history/library/pdf/thirty_years_of_progress.pdf |access-date = March 31, 2017 }}</ref> I-895 was downgraded to NY&nbsp;895 in 2017,<ref name=AASHTO-2017A>{{AASHTO minutes |year = 2017A |access-date=October 21, 2017 |page = 4 |link = yes }}</ref> and was converted to a [[boulevard]] between 2018 and 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|U.S. Roads|New York (state)|New York City}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Interstate 95 in New York (state)}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n{{NYSR external links|type=I|nyroutes=yes|route=95|alps=yes}}\n* [http://www.nycroads.com/roads/new-england/ New England Thruway (I-95)]\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/ny4/expwy/net/photonet.htm Jeff's Expressways Site Photo Gallery]\n* [http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-095.html I-95]\n* [http://www.greaternyroads.info/roads/nyinter/i95 I-95 (Greater New York Roads)]\n\n{{State detail page browse|type=I|route=95|state=New York|statebefore=New Jersey|stateafter=Connecticut}}\n{{3di|95}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interstate 095 In New York}}\n[[Category:New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in New York (state)|95]]\n[[Category:Interstate 95|New York]]\n[[Category:Expressways in New York City]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Transportation in New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Harrison, New York]]\n[[Category:Pelham, New York]]\n[[Category:Port Chester, New York]]\n[[Category:Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:Larchmont, New York]]\n[[Category:Mamaroneck, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Highway detail hatnote|Interstate 95}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=95\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 95 in New York}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Map of northern New York City and southern Westchester County with I-95 highlighted in red\n|maint=[[New York State Department of Transportation|NYSDOT]], [[New York State Thruway Authority|NYSTA]] and [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey|PANYNJ]]\n|length_mi=23.44\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=2014tdr/>\n|established=August&nbsp;14, 1957<ref name=\"1957ihmap\" />\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=NJ|I|95|NJTP||US|1|US|9|US|46}} at the [[New Jersey]] state line on the [[George Washington Bridge]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{Jct|state=NY|US|9|NY|9A|Parkway|Henry Hudson}} in [[Manhattan]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|Parkway|Harlem River}} in Manhattan\n*{{Jct|state=NY|I|87}} in [[Morris Heights, Bronx|Morris Heights]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|US|1}} in [[Tremont, Bronx|Tremont]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|Parkway|Bronx River|NY|895}} in [[Soundview, Bronx|Soundview]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|I|278|I|295|I|678|Parkway|Hutchinson River}} in [[Throggs Neck]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Pelham}} in [[Pelham Bay Park]]\n*{{Jct|state=NY|Parkway|Hutchinson River}} in [[Pelham Bay Park]] and [[Eastchester, Bronx|Eastchester]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|US|1}} in [[Pelham, New York|Pelham]]\n*{{jct|state=NY|I|287|US|1}} in [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=CT|I|95|CTTP}} at the [[Connecticut]] state line in [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]\n|counties=[[Manhattan|New York]], [[The Bronx|Bronx]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]]\n|previous_type=NY\n|previous_route=94\n|next_type=NY\n|next_route=95\n}}\n\n'''Interstate&nbsp;95''' ('''I-95''') is a part of the [[Interstate Highway System]] that runs from [[Miami]], [[Florida]], to the [[Canada\u2013United States border]] near [[Houlton, Maine]]. In the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], I-95 extends {{convert|23.50|mi|2}} from the [[George Washington Bridge]] in [[New York City]] to the [[Connecticut]] state line at [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]. From the George Washington Bridge, which carries I-95 across the [[Hudson River]] from [[New Jersey]] into [[New York City]], it runs across [[upper Manhattan]] on the [[Trans-Manhattan Expressway]] and continues east across the [[Harlem River]] on the [[Alexander Hamilton Bridge]] and onto the [[Cross Bronx Expressway]]. In [[the Bronx]], I-95 leaves the Cross Bronx at the [[Bruckner Interchange]], joining the [[Bruckner Expressway]] to its end. North of the interchange with [[Pelham Parkway]], it then continues northeast via the '''New England Thruway''' (which is part of the [[New York State Thruway]] system) out of New York City into [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] and to the Connecticut state line, where I-95 continues on the [[Connecticut Turnpike]].\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Manhattan===\n{{main|Trans-Manhattan Expressway}}\nI-95 enters [[New York (state)|New York]] from [[New Jersey]] on the [[George Washington Bridge]] on a concurrency with [[U.S. Route 1 in New York|U.S. Route&nbsp;1]] (US&nbsp;1) and [[U.S. Route 9 in New York|US&nbsp;9]]. As the bridge's eastern approach enters [[Fort Washington Park (Manhattan)|Fort Washington Park]], I-95 enters exit&nbsp;1, which services [[New York State Route 9A]] (NY&nbsp;9A, the [[Henry Hudson Parkway]]). Access is also provided to [[181st Street (Manhattan)|181st Street]]. After crossing [[Fort Washington Avenue]], the interstate goes underground, providing a ramp to [[178th Street (Manhattan)|178th Street]], which is where US&nbsp;9 forks to [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]. I-95 continues east under [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], entering an interchange with the [[Harlem River Drive]] along with [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Amsterdam Avenue]].<ref name=\"bing\">{{bing maps|url=http://binged.it/1b6Ecrl|title=overview map of Interstate 95|accessdate=September 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===The Bronx===\n{{see also|Cross Bronx Expressway|Bruckner Expressway}}\nAfter exit&nbsp;2, I-95 crosses over the [[Harlem River]] and enters [[the Bronx]], entering an interchange with the [[Major Deegan Expressway]] ([[Interstate 87 (New York)|I-87]]), which is marked both exit&nbsp;1C (following with the Cross Bronx Expressway) and exit&nbsp;3A&nbsp;B (matching with the Trans-Manhattan Expressway). Now the Cross-Bronx Expressway, I-95 and US&nbsp;1 continue east over University Avenue and enter exit&nbsp;2A, which serves [[Jerome Avenue]]. Crossing over the [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse]], the six-lane expressway crosses into exit&nbsp;2B, which is for [[Webster Avenue]]. This interchange also marks the eastern end of the I-95/US&nbsp;1 [[Concurrency (road)|concurrency]]. Passing south of [[Tremont Park]], the Cross Bronx westbound serves exit&nbsp;3, which serves [[Third Avenue (Bronx)|Third Avenue]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n[[File:Cross Bronx Expressway.jpg|thumb|left|Congestion on the Cross Bronx Expressway westbound approaching exit&nbsp;4B]]\nAt East 176th Street, the Cross Bronx Expressway turns southeast, entering exit&nbsp;4A eastbound, which marks the northern terminus of [[New York State Route 895|NY 895]] (Sheridan Boulevard). After crossing the [[Bronx River]], the expressway enters a full interchange, exit&nbsp;4B, with the [[Bronx River Parkway]].<ref name=\"bing\" /> After a curve from the parkway, the Cross Bronx begins paralleling East 177th Street<ref>{{cite act|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=1709698&GUID=9518C471-1983-4D22-82B5-15CE7EF4D9A4&Options=&Search= |title=\nA Local Law in relation to renaming two thoroughfares and public places in the Borough of the Bronx, East 177th Street, and to amend the official map of the city of New York accordingly.| number = 2018-035 |date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> and enters exit&nbsp;5A, which connects to [[White Plains Road]] in [[Parkchester, Bronx|Parkchester]]. Continuing southeast, the roadway enters exit&nbsp;5B, Castle Hill Avenue, which is an eastbound-only exit. After Castle Hill Avenue, the route enters exit&nbsp;6A, which reaches the [[Hutchinson River Parkway]] at the [[Bruckner Interchange]]. Changing to the [[Bruckner Expressway]], which runs to the northeast, I-95 enters the Bruckner Interchange with the northern termini of [[Interstate 678|I-678]] and [[Interstate 278|I-278]]; the Cross Bronx Expressway Extension turns southeast along [[Interstate 295 (New York)|I-295]] at the same interchange.<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nAfter the Bruckner Interchange, I-95 crosses Tremont Avenue before crossing over [[Interstate 695 (New York)|I-695]] (the Throgs Neck Expressway). Southbound, exit&nbsp;7A serves I-695, while northbound the two interstates merge. Continuing north, the Bruckner Expressway and I-95 parallel Bruckner Boulevard and run along the western edge of [[Pelham Bay Park]]. Entering exit&nbsp;8A southbound services Westchester Avenue while northbound, exits&nbsp;8B and 8C serve the [[Pelham Parkway (road)|Pelham Parkway]] and Shore Road through the park, which marks the northern end of the Bruckner Expressway. Now known as the New England Thruway, I-95 leaves Pelham Bay Park and enters exit&nbsp;9, a junction with the Hutchinson River Parkway. In the middle of the interchange with the Hutchinson River, exit&nbsp;10 forks to the left, reaching [[Gun Hill Road (Bronx)|Gun Hill Road]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nNow paralleling Baychester Avenue, which also services exit&nbsp;11 and Bartow Avenue, the New England Thruway continues north and enters exit&nbsp;12 which connects to [[Baychester, Bronx|Baychester]]. Conner Street is connected to via exit&nbsp;13 before I-95 turns east and crosses over the [[Hutchinson River]]. After crossing the river, the route enters an interchange once again with the Hutchinson River Parkway (exit&nbsp;14) but this time westbound only.<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\n===Westchester===\n[[File:NewEngThruway.svg|75px|thumb|Shield for the New England Thruway used between 1958 and 1970.]]\nCrossing through the northern reaches of Pelham Bay Park, I-95 turns more northeast and enters [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]]. Now in [[Pelham Manor, New York|Pelham Manor]], the route crosses through [[Pelham Country Club]], entering exit&nbsp;15, which connects to US&nbsp;1 (Main Street). After US&nbsp;1, the route crosses out of the Pelham Country Club, entering [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nCrossing over [[Metro-North Railroad]] tracks, the interstate turns northeast and crossing through downtown New Rochelle, reaching exit&nbsp;16, serving several local streets including Cross Avenue, Cedar Street and Garden Street. North of exit&nbsp;16, the New England Thruway enters its lone [[open road tolling|toll gantry]] along the alignment, serving the northbound direction only. The road continues northeast through New Rochelle, passing exit&nbsp;17 as it enters [[Mamaroneck (town), New York|the town of Mamaroneck]]. Exit&nbsp;17 connects to Chatsworth Avenue in the [[Larchmont, New York|Larchmont]] section.  Passing a pedestrian footbridge for the [[Larchmont (Metro-North station)|Larchmont station]], crossing over [[New York State Route 125|NY&nbsp;125]] (Weaver Street). Winding north through Mamaroneck, I-95 enters exit&nbsp;18A, servicing Fenimore Road in the [[Mamaroneck (village), New York|village of Mamaroneck]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\nTurning northeast again, I-95 enters exit&nbsp;18B, a [[partial cloverleaf interchange]] with [[Mamaroneck Avenue]] before crossing into the town of [[Harrison, New York|Harrison]]. The road turns east, crossing over [[New York State Route 127|NY&nbsp;127]] (Harrison Avenue), and enters exit&nbsp;19, the western terminus of the [[Playland Parkway]], which connects the expressway to [[Rye Playland]] as the road enters [[Rye, New York|Rye]]. The route crosses through the Rye Village area, entering exit&nbsp;20, which connects to US&nbsp;1 ([[Boston Post Road]]) and the village. Almost immediately after exit&nbsp;20, exit&nbsp;21 marks the eastern end of the [[Cross-Westchester Expressway]] ([[Interstate 287|I-287]]). Proceeding westbound, exit&nbsp;21 and nearby exit&nbsp;22 (Midland Avenue and [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]) are merged, but are separate exits going eastbound. Crossing through the eastern edges of Port Chester, I-95 reaches the [[Byram River]] and crosses into [[Connecticut]], becoming the [[Connecticut Turnpike]].<ref name=\"bing\" />\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed|section|date=July 2016}}\n[[Robert Moses]] first recommended the construction of what became the New England Thruway in 1940. Construction began in 1951, but major work on the highway did not commence until 1956-1957. By 1950, the [[New York State Thruway Authority]] assumed control of the construction and made the New England Thruway a part of the Thruway toll system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/03/19/archives/city-speeds-highway-programs-expressways-arterial-roads-designed-to.html|title=CITY SPEEDS HIGHWAY PROGRAMS; Expressways, Arterial Roads Designed to Handle New Traffic Patterns to Result From Two Projected State Thruways|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|date=1950-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Construction lasted until 1961.\n\nI-95 was assigned on August&nbsp;14, 1957, as part of the establishment of the [[Interstate Highway System]],<ref name=\"1957ihmap\">{{cite map |publisher=[[American Association of State Highway Officials]] |title=[[Media:Interstate Highway plan August 14, 1957.jpg|Official route numbering for the National System of Interstate and Defense Highways]] |date=August 14, 1957}}</ref> and has always run along its current path in New York. The route was overlaid on the under-construction New England Thruway northeast of [[New York City]] and assigned to the then-proposed [[Cross Bronx Expressway|Cross Bronx]] and [[Bruckner Expressway]]s through [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite map |title=New York and New Jersey Tourgide<!--sic--> Map |publisher=[[Gulf Oil Company]] |cartography=[[Rand McNally and Company]] |year=1960}}</ref> The thruway opened in October 1958, connecting the Bruckner Expressway and the [[Connecticut Turnpike]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/10/05/archives/to-connecticut-new-england-thruway-to-open-direct-route-from-bronx.html|title=TO CONNECTICUT; New England Thruway to Open Direct Route From Bronx to Rhode Island|last=Ingraham|first=Joseph C.|date=1958-10-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The final sections of the Cross Bronx and Bruckner Expressways were finished in 1963 and 1972, respectively. Prior to the 1972 completion of the Bruckner, coinciding with the completion of the new [[Bruckner Interchange]], the old [[Bruckner Boulevard]] (once part of [[New York State Route 164 (1940\u20131960s)|NY&nbsp;164]]) was used by through traffic.<ref>{{cite map |title=New York and Metropolitan New York |publisher=[[Sinclair Oil Corporation]] |year=1964 |cartography=Rand McNally and Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite map |title=New York State Highways |publisher=[[New York State Department of Commerce|State of New York Department of Commerce]] |year=1969 |cartography=Rand McNally and Company}}</ref>\n\n===Exit numbers===\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\nThe first change to exit numbers along the New England Thruway section of Interstate&nbsp;95 was in April&nbsp;1980 when the section was converted for sequential exits.<ref>{{cite news|title=New England Thruway exit numbers to change|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252010%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2520-%25202287.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4fe404d3%26DocId%3D1561709%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D4%26hits%3D292%2B293%2B2a6%2B2a7%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252010%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2FYonkers%2520NY%2520Herald%2520Statesman%25201980%2520Grayscale%2520-%25202287.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4fe404d3%26DocId%3D1561709%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520I%252dE%252dV%26HitCount%3D4%26hits%3D292%2B293%2B2a6%2B2a7%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fNew%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|accessdate=April 20, 2017|work=Gannett Westchester Newspapers|date=February 7, 1980|page=D3}}</ref> Prior to the change, the Cross Bronx Expressway and New England Thruway sections had different exit numbering systems. More specifically, exit 19 on the Cross Bronx Expressway was followed immediately by exit 2 on the New England Thruway. As a result, because exit numbers on I-95 repeated themselves in close succession, the old exit numbering system frequently caused confusion.<ref>{{cite web | title=New England Thruway to Get New Exit Numbers; Last Exit to New York | website=The New York Times | date=February 17, 1980 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1980/02/17/archives/new-england-thruway-to-get-new-exit-numbers-last-exit-to-new-york.html | access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs part of an experiment, I-95 was one of the few roads in New York to receive mileage-based exit numbers. This was implemented over both the Port Authority section and the NYSDOT section of the highway (Exits 1A through 8C). The Thruway section (which had originally carried its own sequential exit numbers) was then renumbered by the Thruway Authority to a system of sequential numbers starting from 9 (where the mileage-based system left off). This led to a situation in which Exits 1 through 8 were mileage based (all but one of which contained lettered suffixes as a result) and Exits 9 through 22 were sequential.\n\nAround 2005, NYSDOT began a project to renumber I-95 with sequential numbers throughout. However the idea never fully got traction with all three agencies. The Port Authority did complete the renumbering on its section of the road. NYSDOT itself renumbered only one section of the road in Parkchester. Meanwhile, the Thruway Authority did not renumber any of the exits on its stretch of the road. This led to a situation from 2005 through 2012 in which some exits were signed with two different numbers, while some numbers were repeated twice, but only on some of the signs.\n\nFinally, in 2012, NYSDOT restored the mileage-based numbers to its portion of the highway, which once again line up with the Thruway portion. This has eliminated all of the exit number conflicts, with one exception. The exception exists because the Port Authority has not changed the numbers back on its portion of the road creating a confusing situation at the Amsterdam Avenue exit, which is maintained by NYSDOT southbound but the Port Authority northbound. The exit is signed as Exit 1B southbound (which is the proper number within the mileage-based), but as Exit 2 northbound (a holdover from the failed renumbering project).\n\n==Exit list==\nExit numbers on the New England Thruway (north of exit 8C) are sequential, but exit numbers on the remaining section are mileage-based.\n{{NYinttop|old|length_ref=<br><ref name=\"2014tdr\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/NYSDOT_Traffic_Data_Report_2014.pdf |title=2014 Traffic Data Report for New York State |date=July 22, 2016 |format=PDF |page=79 |publisher=[[New York State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=inventory>{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/HighwayInventory-NewYorkCounty-2016.zip |title=New York County Inventory Listing |date=August 7, 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Transportation |format=CSV |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/HighwayInventory-BronxCounty-2016.zip |title=Bronx County Inventory Listing |date=August 7, 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Transportation |format=CSV |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/HighwayInventory-WestchesterCounty-2016.zip |title=Westchester County Inventory Listing |date=August 7, 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Transportation |format=CSV |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=google>{{google maps |url=https://goo.gl/maps/wv2qcLjgZ9r |title=Interstate 95 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Jctint|old\n|river=[[Hudson River]]\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.00\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|I|95|dir1=south|NJTP||dir2=south|US|1|US|9|dir3=south|dir4=south|US|46|dir5=west|name5=[[George Washington Bridge]]|location1=[[New Jersey]]|location2=[[Philadelphia]]}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[New Jersey]] at the river's center; eastern terminus of US&nbsp;46\n}}\n{{Jctbridge|old\n|mile=0.00\n|mile2=0.43\n|type=toll\n|bridge=[[George Washington Bridge]] (northbound toll plaza in New Jersey)\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|county=New York\n|cspan=2\n|location=Washington Heights\n|borough=Manhattan\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.43\n|old=1\n|exit=1\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|9|dir1=north|NY|9A|Parkway|Henry Hudson|road=[[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] / [[178th Street (Manhattan)|West 178th Street]] / West 181st Street|location1=[[Midtown Manhattan|Downtown]]|city2=Yonkers}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 9 [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]]; southbound access via Lower Level lanes; exit 14 on NY 9A&nbsp;/ H.H. Parkway\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=1.16\n|old=2\n|exit=2\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Harlem River|dir1=south|road=[[Amsterdam Avenue (Manhattan)|Amsterdam Avenue]]&nbsp;/ University Avenue|location1=[[Manhattan]]}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; exit 24 on H.R. Drive\n}}\n{{jctbridge|old\n|river=[[Harlem River]]\n|mile=1.24\n|mile2=1.41<!--countyline=1.34, +0.07-->\n|type=trans\n|bridge=[[Alexander Hamilton Bridge]]<br>(Route transition between [[Trans-Manhattan Expressway|Trans-Manhattan]] and [[Cross Bronx Expressway]]s)\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|county=Bronx\n|cspan=26\n|location=Morris Heights\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=3\n|mile=1.41<!--+0.07-->\n|mspan=2\n|old=2\n|exit=1B\n|type=incomplete\n|road=[[Amsterdam Avenue (Manhattan)|Amsterdam Avenue]]\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; shared ramp with exits 1C\u2013D\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=none\n|old=3\n|exit=3<br>1C\u2013D\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|87|name1=[[Major Deegan Expressway]]|city1=Albany|location2=[[RFK Bridge]]|location3=[[Yankee Stadium]]}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 1C (north) and 1D (south) southbound; signed as exit 3 northbound<ref>In Manhattan, I-95 is maintained by the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey|Port Authority of NY-NJ]], who signs it as exit 3, whereas in The  Bronx, I-95 is maintained by NYCDOT, who signs it as exits 1C-1D.</ref>\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=2.08<!--+0.74-->\n|old=4\n|exit=2A\n|road=[[Jerome Avenue]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Tremont\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=2\n|mile=2.66<!--+1.32-->\n|old=5\n|exit=2B\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|1|dir1=north|name1=[[Webster Avenue]]}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 1 concurrency; northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=2.95<!--+1.61-->\n|old=6\n|exit=3\n|road={{jct|state=NY|road|[[Third Avenue (Bronx)|Third Avenue]]|US|1|dir2=north|name2=[[Webster Avenue]]|to2=yes}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=West Farms\n|borough=Bronx\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=3.97<!--+2.63-->\n|old=7\n|exit=4A\n|road={{jct|state=NY|NY|895|dir1=south|name1=Sheridan Boulevard|location1=[[RFK Bridge]]|location2=[[Hunts Point Market]]}}\n|notes=Southbound exit via exit 4B; former I-895\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Soundview\n|borough=Bronx\n|mile=4.34<!--3.00-->\n|old=8\n|exit=4B\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NY|road|Rosedale Avenue|Parkway|Bronx River|to2=yes|dir2=north}}\n|notes=Southbound entrance via exit 4A; exit 4 on Bronx Parkway; serves [[Bronx Zoo]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Parkchester\n|borough=Bronx\n|mile=5.05<!--+3.71-->\n|old=9\n|exit=5A\n|road=[[White Plains Road]]&nbsp;/ [[Westchester Avenue]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Castle Hill\n|borough=Bronx\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=5.60\n|old=10\n|exit=5B\n|road=Castle Hill Avenue\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Throggs Neck\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=4\n|mile=5.76<!--+4.42-->\n|old=11\n|exit=6A\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|678|dir1=south|location1=[[Whitestone Bridge]]|city1=Queens|road=[[Bruckner Boulevard]]}}\n|notes=[[Bruckner Interchange]]; no northbound access to Bruckner Boulevard; northern terminus of I-678\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=5.81<!--+4.47-->\n|mspan=2\n|exit=6B\n|old=12\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|278|dir1=west|location1=[[RFK Bridge]]|city2=Manhattan}}\n|notes=[[Bruckner Interchange]]; southbound exit and northbound entrance; eastern terminus of I-278\n}}\n{{jctplace|old\n|mile=none\n|type=trans\n|place=Route transition between [[Cross Bronx Expressway|Cross Bronx]] and [[Bruckner Expressway]]s\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=6.02<!--+4.68-->\n|type=incomplete\n|old=12\n|exit=6B\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|295|dir1=south|location1=[[Throgs Neck Bridge]]}}\n|notes=[[Bruckner Interchange]]; northbound exit and southbound entrance; northern terminus of I-295\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Schuylerville\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=2\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=7.40\n|mspan=2\n|old=13\n|exit=7A\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|695|dir1=south|to2=to|I|295|dir2=south|location1=[[Throgs Neck Bridge]]|city2=Long Island}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; northern terminus of I-695\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=none\n|old=14\n|exit=7B\n|road=[[Tremont Avenue|East Tremont Avenue]]\n|notes=Southbound exit only\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Country Club\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=2\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=7.70\n|old=15\n|exit=7C\n|road=Country Club Road&nbsp;\u2013 [[Pelham Bay Park]]\n|notes=Northbound exit and entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=8.40\n|old=16\n|exit=8A\n|road=Westchester Avenue\n|notes=Southbound exit and entrance\n}}\n{{Jctint|old\n|location_special=[[Pelham Bay Park]]\n|lspan=4\n|mile=8.66<!--+7.32-->\n|mspan=3\n|old=17\n|exit=8B\n|road=[[Orchard Beach, New York|Orchard Beach]], [[City Island, Bronx|City Island]]\n|notes=Access via [[Shore Road (Bronx)|Shore Road]]\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=none\n|old=18\n|exit=8C\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Pelham|dir1=west}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Pelham Parkway\n}}\n{{jctplace|old\n|mile=none\n|type=trans\n|place=Route transition between [[Bruckner Expressway]] and New England Thruway\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|mile=8.99<!--+7.65-->\n|mspan=2\n|old=1<br>19\n|exit=9\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Hutchinson River|dir1=north|road=Erskine Place&nbsp;/ Palmer Avenue}}\n|notes=Exit 4 on Hutchinson Parkway; signed for Palmer northbound, Erskine southbound\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Baychester\n|borough=Bronx\n|lspan=3\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=none\n|old=2\n|exit=10\n|road=[[Gun Hill Road (Bronx)|Gun Hill Road]]\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=9.56<!--+8.22-->\n|old=3\n|exit=11\n|road=Bartow Avenue&nbsp;/ Co-op City Boulevard\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=9.71<!--+8.37-->\n|old=4\n|exit=12\n|road=Baychester Avenue\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYCint|old\n|location=Eastchester\n|borough=Bronx\n|mile=10.82<!--+9.48-->\n|old=5\n|exit=13\n|road=Conner Street&nbsp;/ Baychester Avenue\n|notes=No northbound signage for Baychester Avenue; to [[NY 22]]\n}}\n{{Jctint|old\n|location_special=[[Pelham Bay Park]]\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=11.41<!--+10.07-->\n|old=6\n|exit=14\n|road={{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Hutchinson River|dir1=south|location1=[[Whitestone Bridge]]}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; exit 6 on Hutchinson Parkway\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|county=Westchester\n|cspan=11\n|location=New Rochelle\n|lspan=5\n|mile=13.04<!--countyline=10.65 (+1.34) +1.05-->\n|old=7\n|exit=15\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|1|city1=New Rochelle|city2=The Pelhams}}\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=13.97<!--+1.98-->\n|exit=\u2013\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Division Street\n|notes=Southbound entrance only\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=14.20<!--+2.21-->\n|old=8\n|exit=16\n|road=North Avenue&nbsp;/ Cedar Street&nbsp;\u2013 [[New Rochelle, NY|New Rochelle]]\n|notes=Serves [[New Rochelle station]]\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|type=toll\n|mile=15.60\n|mspan=2\n|old=9\n|exit=17\n|road=Chatsworth Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Larchmont, New York|Larchmont]]\n|notes=Northbound exit (with toll gantry) and southbound entrance; serves [[Larchmont station]]\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|type=toll\n|mile=none\n|place=New Rochelle Toll Gantry (northbound)\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|location=Mamaroneck\n|area=village\n|lspan=2\n|mile=17.57<!--+5.58-->\n|old=10\n|ospan=2\n|exit=18A\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Fenimore Road \u2013 [[Mamaroneck (village), New York|Mamaroneck]]\n|notes=Northbound exit only\n}}\n{{NYint|exit\n|mile=18.46<!--+6.47-->\n|exit=18B\n|road=Mamaroneck Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Mamaroneck (village), New York|Mamaroneck]], [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]]\n|notes=Signed as 18A (east) and 18B (west) southbound; serves [[Mamaroneck station]]\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|location=Rye\n|lspan=4\n|area=city\n|mile=20.91<!--+8.92-->\n|old=11\n|exit=19\n|road=[[Playland Parkway]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]], [[Harrison, New York|Harrison]]\n|notes=Western terminus of Playland Parkway\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=22.14<!--+10.15-->\n|old=12\n|exit=20\n|road={{jct|state=NY|US|1|dir1=south|city1=Rye|areadab1=city}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|mile=22.54<!--+10.55-->\n|mile2=22.68<!--+10.69-->\n|mspan=2\n|old=13\n|exit=21\n|road={{jct|state=NY|I|287|dir1=west|US|1|dir2=north|city1=White Plains|location2=[[New Tappan Zee Bridge|Tappan Zee Bridge]]}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of I-287; no southbound signage for US 1; serves [[Port Chester station]]\n}}\n{{NYint|old\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=none\n|old=14\n|exit=22\n|road=Midland Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]], [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]]\n|notes=Northbound exit only\n}}\n{{jctint|old\n|river=[[Byram River]]\n|mile=23.44<!--+11.45-->\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=CT|I|95|CTTP||dir1=north|dir2=north|city1=New Haven}}\n|notes=Bridge; continues into [[Connecticut]] as the [[Connecticut Turnpike]]\n}}\n{{jctbtm|col=8|keys=concur,incomplete,toll,trans}}\n\n==Auxiliary routes==\n===Current===\n* [[Interstate 295 (New York)|I-295]] runs southeast from the [[Bruckner Interchange]] along the [[Cross Bronx Expressway]], then south over the [[Throgs Neck Bridge]] and [[Clearview Expressway]] to its terminus at [[Hillside Avenue (Queens)|Hillside Avenue]], just south of the [[Grand Central Parkway]].<ref name=\"2017log\">{{cite book |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/operating/oom/transportation-systems/repository/2017%20tour-bk.pdf |format=PDF |title=Official Description of Highway Touring Routes, Bicycling Touring Routes, Scenic Byways, & Commemorative/Memorial Designations in New York State |author=[[New York State Department of Transportation]] |date=January 2017 |accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref> It was once signed as part of [[Interstate 78 in New York|I-78]]<ref name=\"RPA-WorldClass-2011\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Lower Manhattan Road Killed Under State Plan |first=Francis X. |last=Cliness |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/03/25/archives/lower-manhattan-road-killed-under-state-plan.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 25, 1971 |page=78 |accessdate=April 14, 2010}}</ref> and was planned to terminate at the [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]].<ref name=\"NYTimes-JFK-VanWyck-Oct1968\">{{cite news|last1=Fowle|first1=Farnsworth|title=Van Wyck Roads Are Under Study: Better Use of Service Lanes Sought for Kennedy Traffic|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9901E7DD1130E034BC4B51DFB6678383679EDE&legacy=true|accessdate=March 15, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 23, 1968}}</ref><ref name=\"RPA-ExpresswayPlans-1964\">{{cite journal|title=Expressway Plans|journal=[[Regional Plan Association|Regional Plan News]]|date=May 1964|issue=73-74|pages=1\u201318|url=https://archive.org/details/regionalplannews7374regi|accessdate=February 27, 2017|publisher=[[Regional Plan Association]]}}</ref><ref name=\"RPA-WorldClass-2011\">{{cite web|last1=Zupan|first1=Jeffrey M.|last2=Barone|first2=Richard E.|last3=Lee|first3=Mathew H.|title=Upgrading to World Class: The Future of the New York Region's Airports|url=http://www.rpa.org/pdf/RPA-Upgrading-to-World-Class.pdf|publisher=[[Regional Plan Association]]|accessdate=March 15, 2017|date=January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924092424/http://www.rpa.org/pdf/RPA-Upgrading-to-World-Class.pdf|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Interstate 495 (New York)|I-495]] runs from the [[Queens&ndash;Midtown Tunnel]] east along the [[Long Island Expressway]] to [[Riverhead, New York|Riverhead]], crossing I-295 in [[Queens]].<ref name=\"2017log\"/> It was once planned to continue west to I-95 in [[New Jersey]]; that part is now [[Lincoln Tunnel]] and [[New Jersey Route&nbsp;495]]. It was also to go east and meet I-95 again in either Connecticut or in Rhode Island. This would have made I-495 a [[bypass (road)|bypass road]] for I-95.<ref>{{cite book| title=Expressway Plans |date=1964 |work=Regional Plan Association |via=nycroads.com | url=http://www.nycroads.com/history/expwy-plans/ | access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Interstate 695 (New York)|I-695]] is a short route along the [[Throgs Neck Expressway]], connecting I-295 to I-95 in [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"2017log\"/> It was once signed as part of I-78.<ref>{{cite map |title=New York State Highways |publisher=[[New York State Department of Commerce|State of New York Department of Commerce]] |year=1969 |cartography=[[Rand McNally and Company]]}}</ref>  The number had been used for other plans, including a route parallel to [[Woodhaven Boulevard]] and an upgrade of the [[West Side Highway]] and [[Henry Hudson Parkway]].\n===Former===\n* [[New York State Route 895|I-895]], also known as the Sheridan Expressway, was a short connection from I-278 to I-95 in [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"2017log\"/> It was planned to continue north from I-95 to rejoin it near [[Pelham Bay Park]], making it another bypass road.<ref name=\"SheridanStudy-Dec2013\">{{cite web |title = The Sheridan Expressway Study: Reconnecting the Neighborhoods Around the Sheridan Expressway and Improving Access to Hunts Point |url = http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/plans-studies/sheridan-hunts-point/final_full_report.pdf |access-date = February 19, 2017 |publisher = [[Government of New York City|City of New York]] |date = December 2013|page=3 }}</ref><ref name=\"30YrsOfProgress\">{{cite book |title = 30 Years of Progress: 1934-1965 |date = June 9, 1964 |publisher = New York City Department of Parks and Recreation |url = https://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_about/parks_history/library/pdf/thirty_years_of_progress.pdf |access-date = March 31, 2017 }}</ref> I-895 was downgraded to NY&nbsp;895 in 2017,<ref name=AASHTO-2017A>{{AASHTO minutes |year = 2017A |access-date=October 21, 2017 |page = 4 |link = yes }}</ref> and was converted to a [[boulevard]] between 2018 and 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|U.S. Roads|New York (state)|New York City}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Interstate 95 in New York (state)}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n{{NYSR external links|type=I|nyroutes=yes|route=95|alps=yes}}\n* [http://www.nycroads.com/roads/new-england/ New England Thruway (I-95)]\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/ny4/expwy/net/photonet.htm Jeff's Expressways Site Photo Gallery]\n* [http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-095.html I-95]\n* [http://www.greaternyroads.info/roads/nyinter/i95 I-95 (Greater New York Roads)]\n\n{{State detail page browse|type=I|route=95|state=New York|statebefore=New Jersey|stateafter=Connecticut}}\n{{3di|95}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interstate 095 In New York}}\n[[Category:New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in New York (state)|95]]\n[[Category:Interstate 95|New York]]\n[[Category:Expressways in New York City]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Transportation in New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Harrison, New York]]\n[[Category:Pelham, New York]]\n[[Category:Port Chester, New York]]\n[[Category:Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:Larchmont, New York]]\n[[Category:Mamaroneck, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Smith0124", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interstate_95_in_New_York"}
{"title_page": "CTS-1", "text_new": "{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name = Boeing Starliner-1\n| image = Calypso Starliner capsule postflight.jpg\n| image_caption = Starliner to be used for CTS-1 in processing\n| insignia = \n| mission_type = \n| operator = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boeing]]\n| COSPAR_ID = \n| SATCAT = \n| mission_duration = \n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed = \n| spacecraft = Calypso\n| spacecraft_type = [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner|Starliner]]\n| manufacturer = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boeing]]\n| launch_mass = {{convert|NNNN| | |abbr=on}}\n| landing_mass = {{convert|NNNN| | |abbr=on}}\n| launch_date = 2021\n| launch_rocket = [[Atlas V]] N22\n| launch_site = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| landing_date = Late 2021\n| landing_site = \n| crew_size = 4\n| crew_members = [[Sunita Williams]]<br />[[Josh A. Cassada]]<br />[[Thomas Pesquet]]<br />TBA\n| crew_callsign = \n| crew_photo = \n| crew_photo_caption = \n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   |docking_target      = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   |docking_type        = dock\n   |docking_port        = [[Harmony Module]]\n   |docking_date        = \n   |undocking_date      = \n   |time_docked         = Six months\n }}\n| apsis = gee\n| orbit_epoch = \n| orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis = \n| orbit_apoapsis = \n| orbit_period = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\u00b0<!-- anticipated due to ISS mission --->\n| programme = [[Commercial Crew Development|Commercial Crew Program]]\n| previous_mission = [[Boeing Crewed Flight Test]]\n| next_mission = [[USCV-TBD]]\n}}\n\n'''CTS-1''', sometimes referred to as '''Boeing Starliner-1'''<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/specials/ccp-press-kit/main.html</ref>, is the first operational crewed mission of the [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner]] to the [[International Space Station]], and the fourth orbital flight mission of the Starliner overall. It is scheduled for launch in 2021 with a crew of four. It will transport members of a future ISS Expedition to the ISS. This would only be the fourth US spaceflight with a female commander, after [[STS-93]], [[STS-114]], and [[STS-120]]. \n\n==Crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology       = Crew member\n|position1         = Commander\n|crew1_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Sunita Williams]]\n|agency1_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up       = Third\n|expedition1_up    = Expedition TBA\n|position2         = Pilot\n|crew2_up          ={{flagicon|USA}} [[Josh A. Cassada]]\n|agency2_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up       = First\n|expedition2_up    = Expedition TBA\n|position3         = Mission Specialist 1\n|crew3_up          = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Thomas Pesquet]]\n|agency3_up        = [[ESA]]\n|flights3_up       = Second\n|expedition3_up    = Expedition TBA \n|position4         = Mission Specialist 2\n|crew4_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} TBA\n|agency4_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights4_up       = TBA\n|expedition4_up    = Expedition TBA }}\n\n==Backup crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology       = Crew member\n|position1         = Commander\n|crew1_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Barry E. Wilmore]]\n|agency1_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up       = \n|expedition1_up    = \n|position2         = Pilot\n|crew2_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} TBA\n|agency2_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up       = \n|expedition2_up    = \n|position3         = Mission Specialist 1\n|crew3_up          = TBA\n|agency3_up        = \n|flights3_up       = \n|expedition3_up    = \n|position4        = Mission Specialist 2\n|crew4_up          = TBA\n|agency4_up        = \n|flights4_up       = \n|expedition4_up    = \n}}\n\n==Spacecraft==\nThis mission will be the first reuse of a Starliner spacecraft. The USCV-2 vehicle was previously used for the uncrewed [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test|Orbital Flight Test]] mission in December 2019. On December 22, 2019, commander Sunita Williams announced the name \"Calypso\" for the spacecraft.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Astro_Suni |number=1208780116630876160 |date=December 22, 2019 |title=Thanking two mission control personnel |last=Williams|first=Sunita}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\nCurrently, CTS-1 holds the designation USCV-2, as it is scheduled to be the second operational flight of the Commercial Crew Program, following [[USCV-1]] which will be flown by a [[SpaceX]] [[Crew Dragon]] spacecraft<ref>http://spacefacts.de/mission/english/uscv-1.htm</ref>. Nominally, Commercial Crew missions will rotate spacecraft between Crew Dragon and Starliner, although, due to the issues on Boeing's Orbital Flight Test which has most likely pushed the companies Crew Flight Test into 2021, it is unclear weather Starliner will be ready in time to fly on USCV-2, meaning the designation may go to the second operational flight of Crew Dragon<ref>https://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=46136.1220</ref>.\n\nAs this flight marks the first operational flight of Starliner, a Russian cosmonaut will most likely not be on board as [[Roscosmos]] has stated they do not want to put Russian cosmonauts on either Starliner or Crew Dragon until they have flown successful USCV flights. The fourth seat will probably be taken by a third NASA astronaut, like what happened with USCV-1<ref>https://spacenews.com/nasa-selects-astronauts-for-crew-dragon-mission/</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dragon 2]]\n\n== Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Starliner spaceflights}}\n{{Manned ISS flights}}\n{{Future spaceflights}}\n\n[[Category:2021 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Future human spaceflights]]\n[[Category:Boeing CST-100 Starliner]]\n[[Category:2021 in the United States]]\n\n{{space-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name = Boeing Starliner-1\n| image = Calypso Starliner capsule postflight.jpg\n| image_caption = Starliner to be used for CTS-1 in processing\n| insignia = \n| mission_type = \n| operator = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boeing]]\n| COSPAR_ID = \n| SATCAT = \n| mission_duration = \n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed = \n| spacecraft = Calypso\n| spacecraft_type = [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner|Starliner]]\n| manufacturer = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boeing]]\n| launch_mass = {{convert|NNNN| | |abbr=on}}\n| landing_mass = {{convert|NNNN| | |abbr=on}}\n| launch_date = 2021\n| launch_rocket = [[Atlas V]] N22\n| launch_site = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| landing_date = Late 2021\n| landing_site = \n| crew_size = 4\n| crew_members = [[Sunita Williams]]<br />[[Josh A. Cassada]]<br />[[Thomas Pesquet]]<br />[[Andrei Borisenko]]\n| crew_callsign = \n| crew_photo = \n| crew_photo_caption = \n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   |docking_target      = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   |docking_type        = dock\n   |docking_port        = [[Harmony Module]]\n   |docking_date        = \n   |undocking_date      = \n   |time_docked         = Six months\n }}\n| apsis = gee\n| orbit_epoch = \n| orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis = \n| orbit_apoapsis = \n| orbit_period = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\u00b0<!-- anticipated due to ISS mission --->\n| programme = [[Commercial Crew Development|Commercial Crew Program]]\n| previous_mission = [[Boeing Crewed Flight Test]]\n| next_mission = [[USCV-TBD]]\n}}\n\n'''CTS-1''', sometimes referred to as '''Boeing Starliner-1'''<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/specials/ccp-press-kit/main.html</ref>, is the first operational crewed mission of the [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner]] to the [[International Space Station]], and the fourth orbital flight mission of the Starliner overall. It is scheduled for launch in 2021 with a crew of four. It will transport members of a future ISS Expedition to the ISS. This would only be the fourth US spaceflight with a female commander, after [[STS-93]], [[STS-114]], and [[STS-120]]. \n\n==Crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology       = Crew member\n|position1         = Commander\n|crew1_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Sunita Williams]]\n|agency1_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up       = Third\n|expedition1_up    = Expedition TBA\n|position2         = Pilot\n|crew2_up          ={{flagicon|USA}} [[Josh A. Cassada]]\n|agency2_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up       = First\n|expedition2_up    = Expedition TBA\n|position3         = Mission Specialist 1\n|crew3_up          = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Thomas Pesquet]]\n|agency3_up        = [[ESA]]\n|flights3_up       = Second\n|expedition3_up    = Expedition TBA \n|position4         = Mission Specialist 2\n|crew4_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} TBA\n|agency4_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights4_up       = TBA\n|expedition4_up    = Expedition TBA }}\n\n==Backup crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology       = Crew member\n|position1         = Commander\n|crew1_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Barry E. Wilmore]]\n|agency1_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights1_up       = \n|expedition1_up    = \n|position2         = Pilot\n|crew2_up          = {{flagicon|USA}} TBA\n|agency2_up        = [[NASA]]\n|flights2_up       = \n|expedition2_up    = \n|position3         = Mission Specialist 1\n|crew3_up          = TBA\n|agency3_up        = \n|flights3_up       = \n|expedition3_up    = \n|position4        = Mission Specialist 2\n|crew4_up          = TBA\n|agency4_up        = \n|flights4_up       = \n|expedition4_up    = \n}}\n\n==Spacecraft==\nThis mission will be the first reuse of a Starliner spacecraft. The USCV-2 vehicle was previously used for the uncrewed [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test|Orbital Flight Test]] mission in December 2019. On December 22, 2019, commander Sunita Williams announced the name \"Calypso\" for the spacecraft.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Astro_Suni |number=1208780116630876160 |date=December 22, 2019 |title=Thanking two mission control personnel |last=Williams|first=Sunita}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\nCurrently, CTS-1 holds the designation USCV-2, as it is scheduled to be the second operational flight of the Commercial Crew Program, following [[USCV-1]] which will be flown by a [[SpaceX]] [[Crew Dragon]] spacecraft<ref>http://spacefacts.de/mission/english/uscv-1.htm</ref>. Nominally, Commercial Crew missions will rotate spacecraft between Crew Dragon and Starliner, although, due to the issues on Boeing's Orbital Flight Test which has most likely pushed the companies Crew Flight Test into 2021, it is unclear weather Starliner will be ready in time to fly on USCV-2, meaning the designation may go to the second operational flight of Crew Dragon<ref>https://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=46136.1220</ref>.\n\nAs this flight marks the first operational flight of Starliner, a Russian cosmonaut will most likely not be on board as [[Roscosmos]] has stated they do not want to put Russian cosmonauts on either Starliner or Crew Dragon until they have flown successful USCV flights. The fourth seat will probably be taken by a third NASA astronaut, like what happened with USCV-1<ref>https://spacenews.com/nasa-selects-astronauts-for-crew-dragon-mission/</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dragon 2]]\n\n== Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Starliner spaceflights}}\n{{Manned ISS flights}}\n{{Future spaceflights}}\n\n[[Category:2021 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Future human spaceflights]]\n[[Category:Boeing CST-100 Starliner]]\n[[Category:2021 in the United States]]\n\n{{space-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Toby6250", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CTS-1"}
{"title_page": "Burnin' (instrumental)", "text_new": "{{short description|1997 song by Daft Punk}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Burnin'\n| cover      = Burnin' (Daft Punk).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Daft Punk]]\n| album      = [[Homework (Daft Punk album)|Homework]]\n| released   = 15 September 1997\n| format     =\n* [[Compact disc|CD]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Chicago house]]\n| length     =\n* 6:53 {{small|(album version)}}\n* 3:48 {{small|(edit version)}}\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Thomas Bangalter]]\n* [[Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo]]\n| producer   = Daft Punk\n| prev_title = [[Around the World (Daft Punk song)|Around the World]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[Revolution 909]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|DBHipNYuAZk|\"Burnin'\"}}\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Burnin{{'}}'''\" is an [[instrumental]] track from the [[Daft Punk]] album ''[[Homework (Daft Punk album)|Homework]]''. It was the fourth single from the album, released in 1997.  The [[music video]] for the track was directed by [[Seb Janiak]]. The song later had a remix entitled \"Extravaganza\", created by Korean band [[BanYa]] for the dance video game ''[[Pump It Up (video game)|Pump It Up]]''. Elements of \"Burnin'\" were combined with the song \"Too Long\" in Daft Punk's live album ''[[Alive 2007]]''.  \n\n\nSample:freaky behavior\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Burnin'\" pays tribute to [[Chicago house]] producers that Daft Punk found inspiration in. The party scene in the video features [[DJ Sneak]], [[Roger Sanchez]], [[Derrick Carter]], [[Roy Davis Jr.]], [[Paul Johnson (producer)|Paul Johnson]], Robert Armani and DJ Hyperactive. [[Thomas Bangalter]] and [[Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo]] of Daft Punk also make brief [[cameo appearance]]s in the video as people at the party; Bangalter wears sunglasses and a long-haired, dark wig, while de Homem-Chisto appears in a purple suit, sunglasses and blonde wig.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0279758/fullcredits IMDB Full Cast and Crew for ''D.A.F.T.'']</ref> The video was shot in [[Chicago]] using an office building at One South [[Wacker Drive]] as the setting.<ref>[http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=1southwacker-chicago-il-usa One South Wacker] emporis.com. Retrieved on April 29, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe video begins with a boy playing with a toy fire truck in a suburb while his father cooks steak on a barbecue. The scene oscillates from this setting to a party scene within a skyscraper, in which a fire spreads while nobody at the party seems to notice. A team of firefighters eventually alert the party attendants of the fire and escort them from the building. It is suggested that the boy and his fire truck are somehow connected to the firefighter rescue and evacuation in the video.\n\n==Track listing==\n===5-track UK 12\"===\n# \"Burnin'\" ([[Ian Pooley]] \"Cut Up\" Mix) \u2013 5:20\n# \"Burnin'\" ([[Slam (band)|Slam]] Mix) \u2013 6:48\n# \"Burnin'\" (Original Mix) \u2013 6:53\n# \"Burnin'\" ([[DJ Sneak]] \"Mongowarrior\" Mix) \u2013 10:22\n# \"Burnin'\" (DJ Sneak Main Mix) \u2013 9:10\n\n===CD===\n# \"Burnin'\" (Edit Version) \u2013 3:48\n# \"Burnin'\" (Ian Pooley \"Cut Up\" Mix) \u2013 5:20\n# \"Burnin'\" (Slam Mix) \u2013 6:48\n# \"Burnin'\" (Original Mix) \u2013 6:53\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1997)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/pd4F2Ze.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received July 12, 2016|publisher=Imgur.com|accessdate=July 12, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|151\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|6|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Wallonia|38|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Finland|20|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|French|29|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italy ([[Federation of the Italian Music Industry|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/ad.htm|title=Hit Parade Italia - Indice per Interprete: D|accessdate=July 6, 2012|publisher=Hit Parade Italia}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|UK|30|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|date=1997-04-10|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs release|name=\"Burnin'\"|id=8084}}\n\n{{Daft Punk singles}}\n\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Daft Punk songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Thomas Bangalter]]\n[[Category:1997 songs]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 song by Daft Punk}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Burnin'\n| cover      = Burnin' (Daft Punk).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Daft Punk]]\n| album      = [[Homework (Daft Punk album)|Homework]]\n| released   = 15 September 1997\n| format     =\n* [[Compact disc|CD]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Chicago house]]\n| length     =\n* 6:53 {{small|(album version)}}\n* 3:48 {{small|(edit version)}}\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Thomas Bangalter]]\n* [[Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo]]\n| producer   = Daft Punk\n| prev_title = [[Around the World (Daft Punk song)|Around the World]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[Revolution 909]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|DBHipNYuAZk|\"Burnin'\"}}\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Burnin{{'}}'''\" is an [[instrumental]] track from the [[Daft Punk]] album ''[[Homework (Daft Punk album)|Homework]]''. It was the fourth single from the album, released in 1997.  The [[music video]] for the track was directed by [[Seb Janiak]]. The song later had a remix entitled \"Extravaganza\", created by Korean band [[BanYa]] for the dance video game ''[[Pump It Up (video game)|Pump It Up]]''. Elements of \"Burnin'\" were combined with the song \"Too Long\" in Daft Punk's live album ''[[Alive 2007]]''.\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Burnin'\" pays tribute to [[Chicago house]] producers that Daft Punk found inspiration in. The party scene in the video features [[DJ Sneak]], [[Roger Sanchez]], [[Derrick Carter]], [[Roy Davis Jr.]], [[Paul Johnson (producer)|Paul Johnson]], Robert Armani and DJ Hyperactive. [[Thomas Bangalter]] and [[Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo]] of Daft Punk also make brief [[cameo appearance]]s in the video as people at the party; Bangalter wears sunglasses and a long-haired, dark wig, while de Homem-Chisto appears in a purple suit, sunglasses and blonde wig.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0279758/fullcredits IMDB Full Cast and Crew for ''D.A.F.T.'']</ref> The video was shot in [[Chicago]] using an office building at One South [[Wacker Drive]] as the setting.<ref>[http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=1southwacker-chicago-il-usa One South Wacker] emporis.com. Retrieved on April 29, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe video begins with a boy playing with a toy fire truck in a suburb while his father cooks steak on a barbecue. The scene oscillates from this setting to a party scene within a skyscraper, in which a fire spreads while nobody at the party seems to notice. A team of firefighters eventually alert the party attendants of the fire and escort them from the building. It is suggested that the boy and his fire truck are somehow connected to the firefighter rescue and evacuation in the video.\n\n==Track listing==\n===5-track UK 12\"===\n# \"Burnin'\" ([[Ian Pooley]] \"Cut Up\" Mix) \u2013 5:20\n# \"Burnin'\" ([[Slam (band)|Slam]] Mix) \u2013 6:48\n# \"Burnin'\" (Original Mix) \u2013 6:53\n# \"Burnin'\" ([[DJ Sneak]] \"Mongowarrior\" Mix) \u2013 10:22\n# \"Burnin'\" (DJ Sneak Main Mix) \u2013 9:10\n\n===CD===\n# \"Burnin'\" (Edit Version) \u2013 3:48\n# \"Burnin'\" (Ian Pooley \"Cut Up\" Mix) \u2013 5:20\n# \"Burnin'\" (Slam Mix) \u2013 6:48\n# \"Burnin'\" (Original Mix) \u2013 6:53\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1997)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/pd4F2Ze.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received July 12, 2016|publisher=Imgur.com|accessdate=July 12, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|151\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|6|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Wallonia|38|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Finland|20|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|French|29|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italy ([[Federation of the Italian Music Industry|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/ad.htm|title=Hit Parade Italia - Indice per Interprete: D|accessdate=July 6, 2012|publisher=Hit Parade Italia}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|UK|30|artist=Daft Punk|song=Burnin'|date=1997-04-10|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs release|name=\"Burnin'\"|id=8084}}\n\n{{Daft Punk singles}}\n\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Daft Punk songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Thomas Bangalter]]\n[[Category:1997 songs]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "2003:c4:5f45:8e00:cc31:b678:8872:27f8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burnin%27_(instrumental)"}
{"title_page": "Chip Arndt", "text_new": "{{Like resume|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Chip Arndt\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Willis Chapman Arndt Jr.\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1966|10|2}}\n| birth_place = [[West Hartford, Connecticut]], US\n| residence   = [[Miami Beach]], [[Florida]], US\n| alma mater = [[Yale University]]<br>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation  = [[Business consultant]], [[LGBT rights]] [[activist]]\n| partner  = [[Reichen Lehmkuhl]] (1999&ndash;2003)\n| television  = [[The Amazing Race 4]]\n| years active = 1990&ndash;present\n}}\n\n'''Willis Chapman '''\"'''Chip'''\"''' Arndt Jr.''' (born October 2, 1966 in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]]) is an [[Americans|American]] [[gay]] [[activist]], best known as a winner of ''[[The Amazing Race 4]]'' in 2003 with former partner [[Reichen Lehmkuhl]]. Arndt attended [[Hotchkiss School]], [[Yale University]], and  [[Harvard University]], where he was the president of the [[Harvard Business School]] Gay and Lesbian Student Association. Prior to ''The Amazing Race'', he worked as an investment banker.\n\n==Early life==\nThe youngest and only boy of four children, Arndt attended [[Hotchkiss School]], a private school in his native [[Connecticut]], and won a fellowship to a 13th year at [[Harrow College]] in Northwest [[London]].<ref name=\"equality Giving\">[http://www.equalitygiving.org/Chip-Arndt-Who-Won-The-Amazing-Race-TV-Show Chip Arndt Who Won The Amazing Race TV Show]</ref> He earned his undergraduate degree in history, with honors, at Yale University in 1990, where he was captain of the [[golf]] team. He worked for five years as an investment banker for [[Morgan Stanley]] as well as in the entertainment industry in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"equality Giving\"/> He then entered [[Harvard University]] for an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1996.<ref name=\"equality Giving\"/> He was president of the [[Harvard Graduate School]] Leadership and Ethics Forum, chairman and founder of the Annual Harvard Business, Law, and [[Kennedy School of Government]] Debate, and president of the [[Harvard Business School]] Gay and Lesbian Student Association.\n\n==''The Amazing Race''==\n{{Main|The Amazing Race 4}}\n\nArndt and former partner [[Reichen Lehmkuhl]] competed against eleven other teams the fourth season, taped in January and February 2003, and premiering in May. The couple, who had met in 1999 while Reichen was still in the United States Air Force, had a commitment ceremony on February 2, 2002.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QWUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&dq=chip+reichen+reality+advocate&hl=en&ei=rFv-TYGwFsSg8QOFs-GwBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=chip%20reichen%20reality%20advocate&f=false The Advocate]</ref> While not legally married, they had asked that  [[Columbia Broadcasting System|CBS]] identify them as a married couple.<ref name=\"Reality TV world\">[http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/amazing-race-4-winners-reichen-lehmkuhl-and-chip-arndt-confirm-end-of-marriage-1827.php 'Amazing Race 4' winners Reichen Lehmkuhl and Chip Arndt confirm end of \"marriage\"]</ref> The identification of a gay couple as married drew criticism from anti-gay groups. By the final episode, Reichen and Chip had an 83% popularity rating on the show's official website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbs.com/primetime/amazing_race4/ |title=CBS.com |accessdate=2007-08-12 |work=CBS}}</ref> Arndt performed seven of eleven roadblocks (tasks only one team member can perform). In total, they placed second on five legs of the race, with their win on the final leg being their second first place, eight minutes ahead of runners up Kelly and Jon. The finale was broadcast on August 21, 2003, with CBS winning both its time slot and the night. Season 4 would later win an [[Emmy award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Reality-Competition Program|Outstanding Reality-Competition Program]].\n\n==Post-''Amazing Race''==\nArndt has been active in the LGBT community following the win,<ref>[http://www.bilerico.com/2011/05/the_amazing_pace_of_chip_arndt_co-founder_of_coupl.php The Amazing Pace of Chip Arndt, Co-Founder of CouplesforEquality.org]</ref> and has appeared on the cover of ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QWUEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&rview=1&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false The Advocate Cover]</ref> Later that month, Arndt addressed a group of [[gay-straight alliance]] leaders.<ref>''Miami Herald'', December 8, 2006</ref> ''Express Gay News'' named him \"Best Local Male Hero\" for using \"his fame and good fortune to help others.\"<ref>''Express Gay News'',October 15, 2004</ref> He is a spokesperson for the annual five-state Braking the Cycle AIDS ride benefiting New York's GLBT Community Center, and Miami's SMART AIDS rides, and has helped raise money for other groups including the [[Point Foundation (LGBT)|Point Foundation]], the [[Human Rights Campaign]], and the [[Matthew Shepard Foundation]] for which he is a Strategic Advisor. He is a co-Director of The Gay American Heroes Foundation,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Holland|first1=Scott|title=Gay American Heroes Foundation|url=https://hotspotsmagazine.com/2010/04/15/gayamericanheroesv2515/|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=hotspots magazine|date=15 April 2010}}</ref> (founded by Scott Hall <ref name=\"queermeup\">{{cite web|title=Eating Out Actor Chris Salvatore Exclusive Interview|url=http://queermeup.com/featured-2/eating-out-actor-chris-salvatore-exclusive-interview/|publisher=queermeup.com|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>) and the website CoupleForEquality.com.<ref name=\"xinfinity\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gayamericanheroes.com/ |title=Gay American Heroes |access-date=2011-06-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711075918/http://gayamericanheroes.com/ |archive-date=2011-07-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.couplesforequality.com/ Couples for Equality]</ref> Arndt was also one of the commentators on the official CBS Website for ''[[The Amazing Race 10]]'', where he answered questions from fans of the show about his experiences and behind-the-scenes knowledge about the series, and revealed that he accidentally ran into the returning teams secretly chosen for the program's 11th season, the anticipated \"[[The Amazing Race 11|All Stars]]\" version, at an airport.\n\nEach year, Arndt conducts a golf clinic at the Advocate Golf Classic benefiting the National Gay & Lesbian Task Force ([[NGLTF]]). As the former Public Relations and Marketing Manager for [[Care Resource]], South Florida's oldest and largest HIV/AIDS services organization, he produced the 2005 AIDS Walk Miami, and spearheaded the 21st annual [[White Party]],<ref>[http://www.boimagazine.com/16.05/16.05-white.html boi magazine]</ref> its week-long fund-raiser, which, at his initiative, emphasized a [[zero tolerance]] drugs policy for the first time. Other charity initiative includes a US$100,000 challenge benefiting nine HIV/AIDS service organizations through his participation in two AIDS ride and two AIDS walks in 2007,<ref>[http://www.metroweekly.com/feature/?ak=2998 Chip Arndt, AIDS Walk Washington's Grand Marshal, puts money, muscle and moxie where his mouth is]</ref> and solicited donations via a special [[MySpace]] page.<ref>[http://www.pr.com/press-release/54560 Chip Arndt, Winner of CBS Reality Show \u201cAmazing Race,\u201d Partners with Hollywood Professionals to Raise Awareness of HIV/AIDS]</ref>\n\nCurrently, he is Executive Vice President and Director of Business Development at Merchant Advantage, a Miami-based [[e-commerce]] software company he helped found.<ref name=\"xinfinity\">[http://xfinitytv.comcast.net/blogs/2009/the-amazing-race/the-amazing-races-chip-arndt-where-is-he-now/ The Amazing Race\u2019s Chip Arndt: Where Is He Now?]</ref><ref name=\"merchadv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.merchantadvantage.com |title=Merchant Advantage's |accessdate=2007-08-12}}</ref>\n\nArndt was elected a PLEO (Party Leader and Elected Official) Obama delegate to the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] and was named one of Florida's 27 electors representing the state in the Electoral College.<ref>[http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/2008/08/meet-the-democr.html Meet the Democratic electors]</ref>  He cast his vote in the state capital of [[Tallahassee, Florida]] for [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[Barack Obama|Obama]] and Vice President-elect [[Joe Biden|Biden]].  Chip was the first openly gay man to have cast an electoral vote in the state of Florida.<ref>[http://www.towleroad.com/2008/12/first-openly-ga.html First Openly Gay Electors Cast Votes for Obama in Florida]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1405899}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=QWUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&dq=chip+reichen+reality+advocate&hl=en&ei=rFv-TYGwFsSg8QOFs-GwBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=chip%20reichen%20reality%20advocate&f=false The Advocate 2003 article]\n{{The Amazing Race contestants}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arndt, Chip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:People from West Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:The Amazing Race contestants]]\n[[Category:Reality show winners]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:2008 United States presidential electors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Like resume|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Chip Arndt\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Willis Chapman Arndt Jr.\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1966|10|2}}\n| birth_place = [[West Hartford, Connecticut]], US\n| residence   = [[Miami Beach]], [[Florida]], US\n| alma mater = [[Yale University]]<br>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation  = [[Business consultant]], [[LGBT rights]] [[activist]]\n| partner  = [[Reichen Lehmkuhl]] (1999&ndash;2003)\n| television  = [[The Amazing Race 4]]\n| years active = 1990&ndash;present\n}}\n\n'''Willis Chapman '''\"'''Chip'''\"''' Arndt Jr.''' (born October 2, 1966 in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]]) is an [[Americans|American]] [[gay]] [[activist]], best known as a winner of ''[[The Amazing Race 4]]'' in 2003 with former partner [[Reichen Lehmkuhl]]. Arndt attended [[Hotchkiss School]], [[Yale University]], and  [[Harvard University]], where he was the president of the [[Harvard Business School]] Gay and Lesbian Student Association. Prior to ''The Amazing Race'', he worked as an investment banker.\n\n==Early life==\nThe youngest and only boy of four children, Arndt attended [[Hotchkiss School]], a private school in his native [[Connecticut]], and won a fellowship to a 13th year at [[Harrow College]] in Northwest [[London]].<ref name=\"equality Giving\">[http://www.equalitygiving.org/Chip-Arndt-Who-Won-The-Amazing-Race-TV-Show Chip Arndt Who Won The Amazing Race TV Show]</ref> He earned his undergraduate degree in history, with honors, at Yale University in 1990, where he was captain of the [[golf]] team. He worked for five years as an investment banker for [[Morgan Stanley]] as well as in the entertainment industry in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"equality Giving\"/> He then entered [[Harvard University]] for an [[Masters of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1996.<ref name=\"equality Giving\"/> He was President of the [[Harvard Graduate School]] Leadership and Ethics Forum, Chairman and Founder of the Annual Harvard Business, Law, and [[Kennedy School of Government]] Debate, and President of the [[Harvard Business School]] Gay and Lesbian Student Association.\n\n==''The Amazing Race''==\n{{Main|The Amazing Race 4}}\n\nArndt and former partner [[Reichen Lehmkuhl]] competed against eleven other teams the fourth season, taped in January and February 2003, and premiering in May. The couple, who had met in 1999 while Reichen was still in the United States Air Force, had a commitment ceremony on February 2, 2002.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QWUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&dq=chip+reichen+reality+advocate&hl=en&ei=rFv-TYGwFsSg8QOFs-GwBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=chip%20reichen%20reality%20advocate&f=false The Advocate]</ref> While not legally married, they had asked that  [[Columbia Broadcasting System|CBS]] identify them as a married couple.<ref name=\"Reality TV world\">[http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/amazing-race-4-winners-reichen-lehmkuhl-and-chip-arndt-confirm-end-of-marriage-1827.php 'Amazing Race 4' winners Reichen Lehmkuhl and Chip Arndt confirm end of \"marriage\"]</ref> The identification of a gay couple as married drew criticism from anti-gay groups. By the final episode, Reichen and Chip had an 83% popularity rating on the show's official website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbs.com/primetime/amazing_race4/ |title=CBS.com |accessdate=2007-08-12 |work=CBS}}</ref> Arndt performed seven of eleven roadblocks (tasks only one team member can perform). In total, they placed second on five legs of the race, with their win on the final leg being their second first place, eight minutes ahead of runners up Kelly and Jon. The finale was broadcast on August 21, 2003, with CBS winning both its time slot and the night. Season 4 would later win an [[Emmy award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Reality-Competition Program|Outstanding Reality-Competition Program]].\n\n==Post-''Amazing Race''==\nArndt has been active in the LGBT community following the win,<ref>[http://www.bilerico.com/2011/05/the_amazing_pace_of_chip_arndt_co-founder_of_coupl.php The Amazing Pace of Chip Arndt, Co-Founder of CouplesforEquality.org]</ref> and has appeared on the cover of ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QWUEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&rview=1&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false The Advocate Cover]</ref> Later that month, Arndt addressed a group of [[gay-straight alliance]] leaders.<ref>''Miami Herald'', December 8, 2006</ref> ''Express Gay News'' named him \"Best Local Male Hero\" for using \"his fame and good fortune to help others.\"<ref>''Express Gay News'',October 15, 2004</ref> He is a spokesperson for the annual five-state Braking the Cycle AIDS ride benefiting New York's GLBT Community Center, and Miami's SMART AIDS rides, and has helped raise money for other groups including the [[Point Foundation (LGBT)|Point Foundation]], the [[Human Rights Campaign]], and the [[Matthew Shepard Foundation]] for which he is a Strategic Advisor. He is a co-Director of The Gay American Heroes Foundation,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Holland|first1=Scott|title=Gay American Heroes Foundation|url=https://hotspotsmagazine.com/2010/04/15/gayamericanheroesv2515/|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=hotspots magazine|date=15 April 2010}}</ref> (founded by Scott Hall <ref name=\"queermeup\">{{cite web|title=Eating Out Actor Chris Salvatore Exclusive Interview|url=http://queermeup.com/featured-2/eating-out-actor-chris-salvatore-exclusive-interview/|publisher=queermeup.com|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref>) and the website CoupleForEquality.com.<ref name=\"xinfinity\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gayamericanheroes.com/ |title=Gay American Heroes |access-date=2011-06-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711075918/http://gayamericanheroes.com/ |archive-date=2011-07-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.couplesforequality.com/ Couples for Equality]</ref> Arndt was also one of the commentators on the official CBS Website for ''[[The Amazing Race 10]]'', where he answered questions from fans of the show about his experiences and behind-the-scenes knowledge about the series, and revealed that he accidentally ran into the returning teams secretly chosen for the program's 11th season, the anticipated \"[[The Amazing Race 11|All Stars]]\" version, at an airport.\n\nEach year, Arndt conducts a golf clinic at the Advocate Golf Classic benefiting the National Gay & Lesbian Task Force ([[NGLTF]]). As the former Public Relations and Marketing Manager for [[Care Resource]], South Florida's oldest and largest HIV/AIDS services organization, he produced the 2005 AIDS Walk Miami, and spearheaded the 21st annual [[White Party]],<ref>[http://www.boimagazine.com/16.05/16.05-white.html boi magazine]</ref> its week-long fund-raiser, which, at his initiative, emphasized a [[zero tolerance]] drugs policy for the first time. Other charity initiative includes a US$100,000 challenge benefiting nine HIV/AIDS service organizations through his participation in two AIDS ride and two AIDS walks in 2007,<ref>[http://www.metroweekly.com/feature/?ak=2998 Chip Arndt, AIDS Walk Washington's Grand Marshal, puts money, muscle and moxie where his mouth is]</ref> and solicited donations via a special [[MySpace]] page.<ref>[http://www.pr.com/press-release/54560 Chip Arndt, Winner of CBS Reality Show \u201cAmazing Race,\u201d Partners with Hollywood Professionals to Raise Awareness of HIV/AIDS]</ref>\n\nCurrently, he is Executive Vice President and Director of Business Development at Merchant Advantage, a Miami-based [[e-commerce]] software company he helped found.<ref name=\"xinfinity\">[http://xfinitytv.comcast.net/blogs/2009/the-amazing-race/the-amazing-races-chip-arndt-where-is-he-now/ The Amazing Race\u2019s Chip Arndt: Where Is He Now?]</ref><ref name=\"merchadv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.merchantadvantage.com |title=Merchant Advantage's |accessdate=2007-08-12}}</ref>\n\nArndt was elected a PLEO (Party Leader and Elected Official) Obama delegate to the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] and was named one of Florida's 27 electors representing the state in the Electoral College.<ref>[http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/2008/08/meet-the-democr.html Meet the Democratic electors]</ref>  He cast his vote in the state capital of [[Tallahassee, Florida]] for [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[Barack Obama|Obama]] and Vice President-elect [[Joe Biden|Biden]].  Chip was the first openly gay man to have cast an electoral vote in the state of Florida.<ref>[http://www.towleroad.com/2008/12/first-openly-ga.html First Openly Gay Electors Cast Votes for Obama in Florida]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1405899}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=QWUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&dq=chip+reichen+reality+advocate&hl=en&ei=rFv-TYGwFsSg8QOFs-GwBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=chip%20reichen%20reality%20advocate&f=false The Advocate 2003 article]\n{{The Amazing Race contestants}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arndt, Chip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:People from West Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:The Amazing Race contestants]]\n[[Category:Reality show winners]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:2008 United States presidential electors]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chip_Arndt"}
{"title_page": "Confirmation in the Catholic Church", "text_new": "{{for|other Christian interpretations of baptism|Confirmation (Christian sacrament)}}\n[[File:Confirmation VanderWeyden.png|thumb|right|The ''[[Seven Sacraments Altarpiece]]'', by [[Rogier van der Weyden]], depicting a [[Latin Church]] bishop administering confirmation in the 14th century]]\n'''Confirmation''' or '''Chrismation''' is one of the seven [[Sacraments (Catholic Church)|sacraments]] of the [[Catholic Church]].<ref>Oregon Catholic Press [https://www.ocp.org/confirmation What is Confirmation?]</ref> It is also one of the three sacraments of initiation into the Catholic Church, the other two being [[Baptism]] and [[First Holy Communion|Holy Communion]].<ref>The Holy See. [https://www.vatican.va/archive/compendium_ccc/documents/archive_2005_compendium-ccc_en.html</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe ''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'' states:<ref>It is evident from its celebration cb.org/catechism/text/pt2sect2chpt1art2.htm ''Catechism of the Catholic Church'' 1302-1303</ref>\n<blockquote>Recall then that you have received the spiritual seal, the Spirit of wisdom and understanding and courage, the spirit of right judgment and courage, the spirit of knowledge and reverence, the Spirit of holy fear in God's presence. Guard what you have received'''. God our Father has marked you with his sign; Christ the Lord has confirmed you and has placed his pledge, the Spirit, in your heart.<ref>St. Ambrose, ''De myst.'' 7, 42: PL 16, 402-403.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe ''Catechism of the Catholic Church'' sees as a scriptural basis for Confirmation as a sacrament distinct from Baptism the account in the [[Acts of the Apostles]] {{bibleverse-nb||Acts|8:14-17}}:<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P3V.HTM Catechism of the Catholic Church, 1315]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rciaresources.com/confirmation |title=RCIA Catechetical Resources, Confirmation, Nature of the Sacrament |access-date=8 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408225824/http://www.rciaresources.com/confirmation |archive-date=8 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<blockquote>Now when the apostles, who were in Jerusalem, had heard that Samaria had received the word of God, they sent unto them Peter and John. Who, when they were come down, prayed for them, that they might receive the Holy Spirit. For he was not as yet come upon any of them; but they were only baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus. Then they laid their hands upon them, and they received the Holy Spirit.</blockquote>\n\n==Western Church==\nIn the [[Latin Church]] (i.e. Western Catholic Church), the [[Sacraments of the Catholic Church|sacrament]] is to be conferred on the faithful above the age of discretion (generally taken to be about 7), unless the [[Episcopal Conference]] has decided on a different age, or there is danger of death or, in the judgment of the minister, a grave reason suggests otherwise.<ref>[http://www.deacons.net/Canon_Law/book_4.htm canon 891 of the Code of Canon Law] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060718135812/http://www.deacons.net/Canon_Law/book_4.htm |date=18 July 2006 }} canon 891</ref> Even in those countries where the [[episcopal conference]] has set a later age as normal, a bishop may not refuse to confer the sacrament on younger children who request it, provided they are baptized, have the use of reason, are suitably instructed and are properly disposed and able to renew the baptismal promises.<ref name=\"Letter547-540\">letter of the [[Congregation for Divine Worship and the Discipline of the Sacraments]] published in its 1999 bulletin, pages 537\u2013540</ref>\n\nThe sacrament is customarily conferred only on people old enough to understand it, and the ordinary minister of Confirmation is a bishop. Only for a serious reason may the diocesan bishop delegate a priest to administer the sacrament (canon 884 of the Code of Canon Law). However, a priest may confer the sacrament when he baptizes someone who is no longer an infant or admits a person already baptized to full [[Communion (Christian)|communion]] with the Catholic Church, or if the person (adult or child) to be confirmed is in danger of death (canon 883). Priests typically administer the sacrament during the [[Easter Vigil]] Mass to adults becoming members of the Catholic Church. It is the conclusion of the [[Rite of Christian Initiation of Adults]] (RCIA) program. Priests customarily ask for and are granted permission for this occasion.<ref name=\"Canon 882-888\">Canon 882-888</ref>\n\n==Age==\n[[File:Confirmation in Mostar 2013b.jpg|250px|thumbnail|Bishop anoints young adult by using [[Chrism|oil of chrism]]]]\nIn the early Church, through the Middle Ages, confirmation was closely linked with [[baptism]] and it was often performed on infants before their first birthday, but in some churches, the minimal age of 10 years comes into play.<ref>Encyclopedia of Children and Childhood in History and Society; \n\n\n\n[http://www.faqs.org/childhood/Bo-Ch/Catholicism.html Catholicism:  Early Church]; accessed 17.     January 2011.</ref> Like baptism, confirmation was an act for which the parents were held responsible. Two [[Synods of Westminster|synods]] held in England during the thirteenth century differed over whether confirmation had to be administered within one year after birth, or within three years.<ref>''Councils and Synods with other Documents relating to the English Church: II. Part 1 (1205-1265), Part II (1265-1313)''; edited by F.M. Powicke and C.R. Cheny (Oxford, 1964)</ref> Confirmation became a much more important rite when concerns about understanding and faith grew, in particular following the [[Reformation]].<ref>Brewer, Holly. [http://uncpress.unc.edu/browse/book_detail?title_id=833 By Birth or Consent: Children, Law, & the Anglo-American Revolution in Authority]; Univ. of North Carolina Press (Chapel Hill, 2005); pp 65-68; accessed 16 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Fourth Lateran Council]], Communion, which continued to be given only after Confirmation, was to be administered only on reaching the age of reason. Some time after the 13th century, the age of Confirmation and Communion began to be delayed further, from seven, to twelve and to fifteen.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=21K7EEXAivMC&pg=PA91 Kay Lynn Isca, ''Catholic Etiquette''] (Our Sunday Visitor 1997 {{ISBN|0-87973-590-2}}), p. 91</ref> The 1917 Code of Canon Law, while recommending that Confirmation be delayed until about seven years of age, allowed it be given at an earlier age.<ref>[http://www.intratext.com/IXT/LAT0813/_P2G.HTM canon 788] of the 1917 Code of Canon Law</ref> Only on 30 June 1932 was official permission given to change the traditional order of the three sacraments of Christian initiation: the Sacred Congregation for the Sacraments then allowed, where necessary, that Confirmation be administered ''after'' [[first Holy Communion]]. This novelty, originally seen as exceptional, became more and more the accepted practice. Thus, in the mid-20th century, Confirmation began to be seen as an occasion for professing personal commitment to the faith on the part of someone approaching adulthood.\n\nHowever, the Catechism of the Catholic Church, 1308 warns: \"Although Confirmation is sometimes called the 'sacrament of Christian maturity,' we must not confuse adult faith with the adult age of natural growth, nor forget that the baptismal grace is a grace of free, unmerited election and does not need 'ratification' to become effective.\"<ref>[http://www.usccb.org/catechism/text/pt1sect2.htm ''Catechism of the Catholic Church'', 1308]</ref>\n\nOn the [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|canonical]] age for confirmation in the [[Latin Church|Latin or Western]] Catholic Church, the present (1983) Code of Canon Law, which maintains unaltered the rule in the 1917 Code, specifies that the sacrament is to be conferred on the faithful at about the [[Age of reason (canon law)|age of discretion]] (generally taken to be about 18),unless the [[episcopal conference]] has decided on a different age, or there is a danger of death or, in the judgement of the [[Catholic minister|minister]], a grave reason suggests otherwise (canon 891 of the Code of Canon Law). The Code prescribes the age of discretion also for the sacraments of Penance<ref>[http://www.intratext.com/IXT/ENG0017/_P3G.HTM canon 989]</ref> and first Holy Communion.<ref>[http://www.intratext.com/IXT/ENG0017/_P38.HTM canons 913\u2013914]</ref>\n\nSince the [[Second Vatican Council]], the setting of a later age, e.g. mid-teens in the United States, early teens in Ireland and Britain, has been abandoned in some places in favour of restoring the traditional order of the three sacraments of Christian initiation.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/BISHOPS/ordsacinit.htm The Restored Order of Sacraments of Initiation]</ref><ref>[http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=24839 Confirmation before communion, Liverpool decides] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411202541/http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=24839 |date=11 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.interchurchfamilies.org/journal/firs_com.shtm Interchurch Families] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003045214/http://www.interchurchfamilies.org/journal/firs_com.shtm |date=3 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.thelostcoin.org/2010/07/why-confirmation-should-be-before-age.html Why Confirmation should be before the age of ten]</ref> Even where a later age has been set, a bishop may not refuse to confer the sacrament on younger children who request it, provided they are baptized, have the use of reason, are suitably instructed and are properly disposed and able to renew the baptismal promises (letter of the [[Congregation for Divine Worship and the Discipline of the Sacraments]] published in its 1999 bulletin, pages 537\u2013540).\n\n==Imagery==\n:''Although Confirmation is sometimes called the \"sacrament of Christian maturity,\" we must not confuse adult faith with the adult age of natural growth, nor forget that the baptismal grace is a grace of free, unmerited election and does not need \"ratification\" to become effective. St. Thomas Aquinas reminds us of this: Age of body does not determine age of soul. Even in childhood man can attain spiritual maturity: as the book of Wisdom says: For old age is not honored for length of time, or measured by number of years. Many children, through the strength of the Holy Spirit they have received, have bravely fought for Christ even to the shedding of their blood.'' (Catechism of the Catholic Church #1308)\n\nThe \"soldier of Christ\" imagery, remains valid<ref>[http://www.dioceseofbmt.org/Documents/PrepConfirmation.htm Confirmation Preparation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060404070450/http://www.dioceseofbmt.org/Documents/PrepConfirmation.htm |date=4 April 2006}}</ref> but is downplayed if seen as part of the once common idea of Confirmation as a \"sacrament of maturity\",<ref>[http://www.eriercd.org/theology05.asp link not working] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419190549/http://www.eriercd.org/theology05.asp |date=19 April 2006 }}</ref> was used as far back as 350, by St Cyril of Jerusalem.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/CATECHSM/CONFIRM1.HTM SACRAMENT OF CONFIRMATION (WHAT IS IT ALL ABOUT?)]</ref> In this connection, the touch on the cheek that the bishop gave while saying \"Pax tecum\" (Peace be with you) to the person he had just confirmed was interpreted in the Roman Pontifical as a slap, a reminder to be brave in spreading and defending the faith: \"Deinde leviter eum in maxilla caedit, dicens: Pax tecum\" (Then he strikes him lightly on the cheek, saying: Peace be with you) (cf. the knightly custom of the [[accolade]]). When, in application of the [[Second Vatican Council]]'s Constitution on the Sacred Liturgy,<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_const_19631204_sacrosanctum-concilium_en.html ''CONSTITUTION ON THE SACRED LITURGY''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221180735/https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_const_19631204_sacrosanctum-concilium_en.html |date=21 February 2008 }}</ref> the Confirmation rite was revised in 1971, mention of this gesture was omitted. However, the French and Italian translations, indication that the bishop should accompany the words \"Peace be with you\" with \"a friendly gesture\" (French text) or \"the sign of peace\" (Italian text), explicitly allow a gesture such as the touch on the cheek, to which they restore its original meaning. This is in accord with the Introduction to the Rite of Confirmation, 17, which indicates that the episcopal conference may decide \"to introduce a different manner for the minister to give the sign of peace after the anointing, either to each individual or to all the newly confirmed together.\"\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n* [[Sacraments of initiation]]\n* [[Seven gifts of the Holy Spirit]]\n* [[Parish register]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Summa Theologiae/Third Part/Question 72|Thomas Aquinas on Confirmation}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120425013957/http://catechumen.org.uk/confirmation/ The Rite of Confirmation Resource Site]\n* [http://www.usccb.org/catechism/text/pt2sect2chpt1art2.shtml 1285-1321. ]''Catechism of the Catholic Church''\n\n{{Seven Sacraments}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic liturgy]]\n[[Category:Sacraments of the Catholic Church]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other Christian interpretations of baptism|Confirmation (Christian sacrament)}}\n[[File:Confirmation VanderWeyden.png|thumb|right|The ''[[Seven Sacraments Altarpiece]]'', by [[Rogier van der Weyden]], depicting a [[Latin Church]] bishop administering confirmation in the 14th century]]\n'''Confirmation''' or '''Chrismation''' is one of the seven [[Sacraments (Catholic Church)|sacraments]] of the [[Catholic Church]].<ref>Oregon Catholic Press [https://www.ocp.org/confirmation What is Confirmation?]</ref> It is also one of the three sacraments of initiation into the Catholic Church, the other two being [[Baptism]] and [[First Holy Communion|Holy Communion]].<ref>The Holy See. [https://www.vatican.va/archive/compendium_ccc/documents/archive_2005_compendium-ccc_en.html</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe ''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'' states:<ref>It is evident from its celebration cb.org/catechism/text/pt2sect2chpt1art2.htm ''Catechism of the Catholic Church'' 1302-1303</ref>\n<blockquote>Recall then that you have received the spiritual seal, the Spirit of wisdom and understanding and courage, the spirit of right judgment and courage, the spirit of knowledge and reverence, the Spirit of holy fear in God's presence. Guard what you have received'''. God our Father has marked you with his sign; Christ the Lord has confirmed you and has placed his pledge, the Spirit, in your heart.<ref>St. Ambrose, ''De myst.'' 7, 42: PL 16, 402-403.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe ''Catechism of the Catholic Church'' sees as a scriptural basis for Confirmation as a sacrament distinct from Baptism the account in the [[Acts of the Apostles]] {{bibleverse-nb||Acts|8:14-17}}:<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P3V.HTM Catechism of the Catholic Church, 1315]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rciaresources.com/confirmation |title=RCIA Catechetical Resources, Confirmation, Nature of the Sacrament |access-date=8 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408225824/http://www.rciaresources.com/confirmation |archive-date=8 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<blockquote>Now when the apostles, who were in Jerusalem, had heard that Samaria had received the word of God, they sent unto them Peter and John. Who, when they were come down, prayed for them, that they might receive the Holy Spirit. For he was not as yet come upon any of them; but they were only baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus. Then they laid their hands upon them, and they received the Holy Spirit.</blockquote>\n\n==Western Church==\nIn the [[Latin Church]] (i.e. Western Catholic Church), the [[Sacraments of the Catholic Church|sacrament]] is to be conferred on the faithful above the age of discretion (generally taken to be about 7), unless the [[Episcopal Conference]] has decided on a different age, or there is danger of death or, in the judgment of the minister, a grave reason suggests otherwise.<ref>[http://www.deacons.net/Canon_Law/book_4.htm canon 891 of the Code of Canon Law] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060718135812/http://www.deacons.net/Canon_Law/book_4.htm |date=18 July 2006 }} canon 891</ref> Even in those countries where the [[episcopal conference]] has set a later age as normal, a bishop may not refuse to confer the sacrament on younger children who request it, provided they are baptized, have the use of reason, are suitably instructed and are properly disposed and able to renew the baptismal promises.<ref name=\"Letter547-540\">letter of the [[Congregation for Divine Worship and the Discipline of the Sacraments]] published in its 1999 bulletin, pages 537\u2013540</ref>\n\nThe sacrament is customarily conferred only on people old enough to understand it, and the ordinary minister of Confirmation is a bishop. Only for a serious reason may the diocesan bishop delegate a priest to administer the sacrament (canon 884 of the Code of Canon Law). However, a priest may confer the sacrament when he baptizes someone who is no longer an infant or admits a person already baptized to full [[Communion (Christian)|communion]] with the Catholic Church, or if the person (adult or child) to be confirmed is in danger of death (canon 883). Priests typically administer the sacrament during the [[Easter Vigil]] Mass to adults becoming members of the Catholic Church. It is the conclusion of the [[Rite of Christian Initiation of Adults]] (RCIA) program. Priests customarily ask for and are granted permission for this occasion.<ref name=\"Canon 882-888\">Canon 882-888</ref>\n\n==Age==\n[[File:Confirmation in Mostar 2013b.jpg|250px|thumbnail|Bishop anoints young adult by using [[Chrism|oil of Chrism]]]]\nIn the early Church, through the Middle Ages, confirmation was closely linked with [[baptism]] and it was often performed on infants before their first birthday, but in some churches, the minimal age of 10 years comes into play.<ref>Encyclopedia of Children and Childhood in History and Society; \n\n\n\n[http://www.faqs.org/childhood/Bo-Ch/Catholicism.html Catholicism:  Early Church]; accessed 17.     January 2011.</ref> Like baptism, confirmation was an act for which the parents were held responsible. Two [[Synods of Westminster|synods]] held in England during the thirteenth century differed over whether confirmation had to be administered within one year after birth, or within three years.<ref>''Councils and Synods with other Documents relating to the English Church: II. Part 1 (1205-1265), Part II (1265-1313)''; edited by F.M. Powicke and C.R. Cheny (Oxford, 1964)</ref> Confirmation became a much more important rite when concerns about understanding and faith grew, in particular following the [[Reformation]].<ref>Brewer, Holly. [http://uncpress.unc.edu/browse/book_detail?title_id=833 By Birth or Consent: Children, Law, & the Anglo-American Revolution in Authority]; Univ. of North Carolina Press (Chapel Hill, 2005); pp 65-68; accessed 16 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Fourth Lateran Council]], Communion, which continued to be given only after Confirmation, was to be administered only on reaching the age of reason. Some time after the 13th century, the age of Confirmation and Communion began to be delayed further, from seven, to twelve and to fifteen.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=21K7EEXAivMC&pg=PA91 Kay Lynn Isca, ''Catholic Etiquette''] (Our Sunday Visitor 1997 {{ISBN|0-87973-590-2}}), p. 91</ref> The 1917 Code of Canon Law, while recommending that Confirmation be delayed until about seven years of age, allowed it be given at an earlier age.<ref>[http://www.intratext.com/IXT/LAT0813/_P2G.HTM canon 788] of the 1917 Code of Canon Law</ref> Only on 30 June 1932 was official permission given to change the traditional order of the three sacraments of Christian initiation: the Sacred Congregation for the Sacraments then allowed, where necessary, that Confirmation be administered ''after'' [[first Holy Communion]]. This novelty, originally seen as exceptional, became more and more the accepted practice. Thus, in the mid-20th century, Confirmation began to be seen as an occasion for professing personal commitment to the faith on the part of someone approaching adulthood.\n\nHowever, the Catechism of the Catholic Church, 1308 warns: \"Although Confirmation is sometimes called the 'sacrament of Christian maturity,' we must not confuse adult faith with the adult age of natural growth, nor forget that the baptismal grace is a grace of free, unmerited election and does not need 'ratification' to become effective.\"<ref>[http://www.usccb.org/catechism/text/pt1sect2.htm ''Catechism of the Catholic Church'', 1308]</ref>\n\nOn the [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|canonical]] age for confirmation in the [[Latin Church|Latin or Western]] Catholic Church, the present (1983) Code of Canon Law, which maintains unaltered the rule in the 1917 Code, specifies that the sacrament is to be conferred on the faithful at about the [[Age of reason (canon law)|age of discretion]] (generally taken to be about 18),unless the [[episcopal conference]] has decided on a different age, or there is a danger of death or, in the judgement of the [[Catholic minister|minister]], a grave reason suggests otherwise (canon 891 of the Code of Canon Law). The Code prescribes the age of discretion also for the sacraments of Penance<ref>[http://www.intratext.com/IXT/ENG0017/_P3G.HTM canon 989]</ref> and first Holy Communion.<ref>[http://www.intratext.com/IXT/ENG0017/_P38.HTM canons 913\u2013914]</ref>\n\nSince the [[Second Vatican Council]], the setting of a later age, e.g. mid-teens in the United States, early teens in Ireland and Britain, has been abandoned in some places in favour of restoring the traditional order of the three sacraments of Christian initiation.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/BISHOPS/ordsacinit.htm The Restored Order of Sacraments of Initiation]</ref><ref>[http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=24839 Confirmation before communion, Liverpool decides] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411202541/http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=24839 |date=11 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.interchurchfamilies.org/journal/firs_com.shtm Interchurch Families] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003045214/http://www.interchurchfamilies.org/journal/firs_com.shtm |date=3 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.thelostcoin.org/2010/07/why-confirmation-should-be-before-age.html Why Confirmation should be before the age of ten]</ref> Even where a later age has been set, a bishop may not refuse to confer the sacrament on younger children who request it, provided they are baptized, have the use of reason, are suitably instructed and are properly disposed and able to renew the baptismal promises (letter of the [[Congregation for Divine Worship and the Discipline of the Sacraments]] published in its 1999 bulletin, pages 537\u2013540).\n\n==Imagery==\n:''Although Confirmation is sometimes called the \"sacrament of Christian maturity,\" we must not confuse adult faith with the adult age of natural growth, nor forget that the baptismal grace is a grace of free, unmerited election and does not need \"ratification\" to become effective. St. Thomas Aquinas reminds us of this: Age of body does not determine age of soul. Even in childhood man can attain spiritual maturity: as the book of Wisdom says: For old age is not honored for length of time, or measured by number of years. Many children, through the strength of the Holy Spirit they have received, have bravely fought for Christ even to the shedding of their blood.'' (Catechism of the Catholic Church #1308)\n\nThe \"soldier of Christ\" imagery, remains valid<ref>[http://www.dioceseofbmt.org/Documents/PrepConfirmation.htm Confirmation Preparation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060404070450/http://www.dioceseofbmt.org/Documents/PrepConfirmation.htm |date=4 April 2006}}</ref> but is downplayed if seen as part of the once common idea of Confirmation as a \"sacrament of maturity\",<ref>[http://www.eriercd.org/theology05.asp link not working] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419190549/http://www.eriercd.org/theology05.asp |date=19 April 2006 }}</ref> was used as far back as 350, by St Cyril of Jerusalem.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/CATECHSM/CONFIRM1.HTM SACRAMENT OF CONFIRMATION (WHAT IS IT ALL ABOUT?)]</ref> In this connection, the touch on the cheek that the bishop gave while saying \"Pax tecum\" (Peace be with you) to the person he had just confirmed was interpreted in the Roman Pontifical as a slap, a reminder to be brave in spreading and defending the faith: \"Deinde leviter eum in maxilla caedit, dicens: Pax tecum\" (Then he strikes him lightly on the cheek, saying: Peace be with you) (cf. the knightly custom of the [[accolade]]). When, in application of the [[Second Vatican Council]]'s Constitution on the Sacred Liturgy,<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_const_19631204_sacrosanctum-concilium_en.html ''CONSTITUTION ON THE SACRED LITURGY''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221180735/https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_const_19631204_sacrosanctum-concilium_en.html |date=21 February 2008 }}</ref> the Confirmation rite was revised in 1971, mention of this gesture was omitted. However, the French and Italian translations, indication that the bishop should accompany the words \"Peace be with you\" with \"a friendly gesture\" (French text) or \"the sign of peace\" (Italian text), explicitly allow a gesture such as the touch on the cheek, to which they restore its original meaning. This is in accord with the Introduction to the Rite of Confirmation, 17, which indicates that the episcopal conference may decide \"to introduce a different manner for the minister to give the sign of peace after the anointing, either to each individual or to all the newly confirmed together.\"\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n* [[Sacraments of initiation]]\n* [[Seven gifts of the Holy Spirit]]\n* [[Parish register]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Summa Theologiae/Third Part/Question 72|Thomas Aquinas on Confirmation}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120425013957/http://catechumen.org.uk/confirmation/ The Rite of Confirmation Resource Site]\n* [http://www.usccb.org/catechism/text/pt2sect2chpt1art2.shtml 1285-1321. ]''Catechism of the Catholic Church''\n\n{{Seven Sacraments}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic liturgy]]\n[[Category:Sacraments of the Catholic Church]]\n", "name_user": "Esrever", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confirmation_in_the_Catholic_Church"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Argentina", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Argentina}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 COVID-19 virus pandemic in Argentina\n| map1            = COVID-19 Pandemic Cases in Argentina by number by province.svg\n| legend1         = Provinces by number of cases (as of 16 April){{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1~9}}{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10~49}}{{legend|#E36654|Confirmed 50~99}}{{legend|#E5354B|Confirmed 100~499}}{{legend|#87353F|Confirmed >500}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Argentina]]\n| first_case      = [[Buenos Aires]]\n| arrival_date    = 3 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=3|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Milan]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]] (local)<br />[[Wuhan]], [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]] (global)<br />\n| recovery_cases  = 630\n| deaths          = 122\n| confirmed_cases = 2,658{{efn|name=c|According to the numbers provided by the national [[Ministry of Health (Argentina)|Ministry of Health]].}}{{efn|Excluding [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Falkland Islands|confirmed cases]] on the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute|claimed territory]] of the [[Falkland Islands]]. Since 11 April, the Ministry of Health includes them.}}\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.argentina.gob.ar/salud/coronavirus-COVID-19|www.argentina.gob.ar/COVID-19}}\n| First Case detected: = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Argentina]] on 3 March 2020,<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirmaron el primer caso de coronavirus en la Argentina: es un hombre que viaj\u00f3 a Italia|url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-confirmaron-primer-caso-argentina-espera-conferencia-gobierno_0_awnywhZX.html|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|accessdate=3 March 2020|date=3 March 2020|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303212736/https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-confirmaron-primer-caso-argentina-espera-conferencia-gobierno_0_awnywhZX.html|archive-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> with 2,658 people being infected.<ref name=InfobaePrimer>{{cite news|title=Confirmaron el primer caso de coronavirus en la Argentina|url=https://www.infobae.com/coronavirus/2020/03/03/confirmaron-el-primer-caso-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina/|website=[[Infobae]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=3 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Sarah Marsh (now); Ben|last1=Quinn|first2=Lucy|last2=Campbell|first3=Alison|last3=Rourke (earlier)|first4=Lorenzo|last4=Tondo|accessdate=3 March 2020|title=Coronavirus: Iran to mobilise 300,000 soldiers and volunteers as 23 MPs infected - latest news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/03/coronavirus-live-updates-china-latest-news-us-australia-deaths-markets-italy-iran-update-cases-italy-south-korea-japan?page=with%3Ablock-5e5e98008f086a28115b6f21|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 March 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com|first5=Sarah|last5=Marsh|first6=Rowena|last6=Mason|first7=Lucy|last7=Campbell}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Se confirm\u00f3 el segundo caso de coronavirus en Argentina: es un hombre de 23 a\u00f1os que vino de Italia|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/05/se-confirmo-el-segundo-caso-de-coronavirus-en-argentina-es-un-hombre-de-23-anos-que-vino-de-italia/|website=[[Infobae]]|accessdate=5 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, the [[Ministry of Health (Argentina)|Ministry of Health]] confirmed the country's first death, a 64-year-old man who had travelled to Paris, France, who also had other health conditions;<ref name=\"argentina.1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/07/confirman-la-primera-muerte-por-coronavirus-en-argentina/|title=Primera muerte por coronavirus en Argentina: era un hombre que hab\u00eda viajado a Francia y estaba internado en el Argerich|website=[[Infobae]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307235849/https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/07/confirman-la-primera-muerte-por-coronavirus-en-argentina/|archive-date=7 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020|date=7 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> the case was only confirmed as positive after the patient's demise.<ref name=\"argentina.1\" /> This also marked the first documented death from the virus in [[Latin America]].<ref name=\"argentina.1\" />\n\nOn 20 March, Argentina entered a nation-wide lockdown.<ref name=\"quarantine\">{{cite news|title=Argentina announces mandatory quarantine to curb coronavirus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-argentina/argentina-announces-mandatory-quarantine-to-curb-coronavirus-idUSKBN216446|accessdate=20 March 2020|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lockdown\">{{cite news|last1=Do Rosario|first1=Jorgelina|title=Argentina Orders 'Exceptional' Lockdown in Bid to Stem Virus|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/argentina-orders-exceptional-lockdown-in-bid-to-contain-virus|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The Argentine government announced the extension of the lockdown, originally intended to end on March 31 until mid April.<ref name=\"quarantine-extension\">{{cite news|title=Argentina extends coronavirus quarantine until mid April|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-argentina/argentina-extends-coronavirus-quarantine-until-mid-april-idUSKBN21H034|accessdate=30 March 2020|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=29 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, President [[Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez]] announced that the lockdown would be extended in major cities until 26 April.<ref name=\"extension26apr\">{{cite news |title=Argentina's Fernandez extends coronavirus lockdown through April 26 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirius-argentina-lockdow/argentinas-fernandez-extends-coronavirus-lockdown-through-april-26-idUSKCN21T00I?il=0 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Argentina medical cases chart}}\n===February===\nOn February 4, the [[cruise ship]] ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' was [[Quarantine|quarantined]] in the [[Port of Yokohama]] in [[Japan]] when 10 passengers were diagnosed with [[COVID-19]] during the early stages of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: confirman diez enfermos m\u00e1s en el crucero varado en Jap\u00f3n con ocho argentinos |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/el-mundo/coronavirus-china-argentinos-crucero-japon-cuarentena-epidemia-nid2331095 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=6 February 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Among the diagnosed passengers was a 61-year-old man of Argentine nationality, who was travelling accompanied by his wife and who had no symptoms, being the first Latin American infected. The patient was transferred to a hospital in Japan \"for studies and treatment\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Un argentino contrajo coronavirus en el crucero en Jap\u00f3n y fue derivado a un hospital |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/el-mundo/primer-latinoamericano-pasajero-argentino-del-crucero-japon-nid2331517 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=7 February 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The other seven Argentinians on board, including his wife, remained on the cruise in quarantine until February 21.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: evacuaron a cinco argentinos del crucero Diamond Princess y dos siguen aislados |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/el-mundo/coronavirus-salio-mayoria-argentinos-del-crucero-diamond-nid2336005 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=21 February 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The man was in perfect health and was released on February 17. He finally left Japan on February 24 and arrived in Argentina on February 26, moving to his home in the city of [[Buenos Aires]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: el primer argentino que se contagi\u00f3 en el crucero japon\u00e9s se recuper\u00f3 y volvi\u00f3 al pa\u00eds |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/04/coronavirus-el-primer-argentino-que-se-contagio-en-el-crucero-japones-se-recupero-y-volvio-al-pais/ |work=Infobae |date=4 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n===March===\n\n'''3 March''': A first case of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] has been confirmed in [[Buenos Aires]]. The patient is a 43-year-old man who arrived on 1 March from [[Milan|Milan, Italy]].<ref name=InfobaePrimer/>\n\n'''5 March''': The [[Ministry of Health (Argentina)|Ministry of Health]] confirmed a second case in a 23-year-old man living in Buenos Aires, who had recently returned from [[Northern Italy]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirman el segundo caso de coronavirus en Argentina|url=https://www.cronista.com/informaciongral/Confirman-el-segundo-caso-de-coronavirus-en-Argentina-20200305-0056.html |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=El Cronista |date=5 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''6 March''': An Italian tourist, a 25-year-old local man who arrived from [[Madrid]], a 60-year-old woman who had arrived from Italy and a Japanese citizen are confirmed to have the virus, bringing the total cases to 8.<ref name=\"6cases\">{{cite news |title=Hay seis casos confirmados en el pa\u00eds |url=https://tn.com.ar/salud/lo-ultimo/coronavirus-en-la-argentina-hay-cinco-casos-confirmados-en-el-pais_1040396 |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=[[Todo Noticias]] |date=6 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''7 March''': The Ministry of Health confirmed the country's first death from coronavirus, a 64-year-old man who had travelled to [[Paris]] who also had other health conditions.<ref name=\"argentina.1\" /> This marks the first death in Latin America.<ref name=\"argentina.1\" /> The person was not among the eight already diagnosed with the disease and was diagnosed post-mortem.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Costa |first1=Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda |title=Confirman el primer muerto por coronavirus en la Argentina: un hombre de 64 a\u00f1os que estuvo en Francia |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/confirman-primer-muerto-coronavirus-argentina-hombre-63-nid2341027 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]] |date=7 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''8 March''': A 53-year-old local woman who arrived from Europe, a 71-year-old Italian citizen who arrived from [[Parma]], and another person who had recently returned from the United States are confirmed to have the virus, bringing the total cases to 12.<ref name=\"12cases\">{{cite news |title=Se suman otros tres casos positivos y ya son 12 los contagiados en el pa\u00eds por Coronavirus |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/08/se-suman-otros-tres-casos-positivos-y-ya-son-12-los-contagiados-en-el-pais-por-coronavirus/|accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=[[Infobae]] |date=8 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''9 March''': The Ministry of Health confirmed five new cases, in Buenos Aires, [[San Luis Province|San Luis]], [[Chaco Province|Chaco]] (2), and [[R\u00edo Negro Province|R\u00edo Negro]], bringing the total to 17.<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman cinco nuevos casos de Coronavirus en el pa\u00eds|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/confirman-nuevo-caso-coronavirus-hay-13-infectados-nid2341510|accessdate=9 March 2020|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=9 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''10 March''': The Ministry of Health confirmed two new cases, in [[La Matanza Partido|La Matanza]] and Buenos Aires, a 42-year-old man who returned from Spain and a 23-year-old man who arrived from France, respectively, bringing the total cases to 19.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/10/hay-dos-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-ya-son-19-los-contagiados/|title=Hay dos nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y ya son 19 los contagiados|date=10 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|access-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20200311 - UniRioTV - SPOT PREVENCI\u00d3N POR CORONAVIRUS.webm|thumb|thumtime=0:00|Coronavirus prevention video from the [[National University of R\u00edo Cuarto]].]]\n\n'''11 March''': Two new cases were confirmed, a 54-year-old man from Buenos Aires who returned from Germany and a 48-year-old woman from [[Buenos Aires Province]] who recently returned from Spain, bringing the total cases to 21.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nuevo Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Informe diario - 11 de marzo de 2020|url=https://www.argentina.gob.ar/sites/default/files/11-03-2020-nuevo-coronavirus-covid-19-reporte-diario.pdf|publisher=[[Ministry of Health (Argentina)|Ministry of Health of Argentina]]|accessdate=11 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Confirmaron dos nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y el total de contagiados asciende a 21|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/11/confirmaron-dos-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-total-de-contagiados-asciende-a-21/|date=11 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''12 March''': Ten new cases were confirmed (three are from local transmission) in Buenos Aires and the provinces of Buenos Aires, Chaco, and [[C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], bringing the total cases to 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/12/confirmaron-otros-nueve-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-cuatro-de-ellos-son-autoctonos/|title=Confirmaron otros diez casos de coronavirus y tres de ellos se contagiaron en la Argentina|date=12 March 2020|work=Infobae|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> In Chaco, the first native transmission is confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chaco confirma el primer caso vinculado con importaci\u00f3n de COVID19 |url=https://www.jujuyalmomento.com/chaco/chaco-confirma-el-primer-caso-vinculado-importacion-covid19-n104145|website=jujuyalmomento.com|accessdate=13 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe first patient with the virus in the country was discharged and left the hospital in Buenos Aires the next day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dieron de alta al primer infectado por coronavirus en la Argentina|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/12/dieron-de-alta-al-primer-infectado-por-coronavirus-en-la-argentina/|accessdate=12 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|date=12 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dieron el alta al \"paciente cero\" local pero debe seguir en aislamiento domiciliario |url=https://www.telam.com.ar/notas/202003/440520-paciente-cero-alta-coronavirus.html |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=[[T\u00e9lam]] |date=13 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''13 March:''' The second death in the country linked to the virus has been confirmed on this day, a 61-year-old man from Chaco Province who had travelled to Egypt, Turkey, and Germany, and also had other underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: el segundo muerto en la Argentina es un ingeniero de 61 a\u00f1os|url=https://www.ambito.com/informacion-general/coronavirus/coronavirus-el-segundo-muerto-la-argentina-es-un-ingeniero-61-anos-n5088538|accessdate=13 March 2020|work=[[\u00c1mbito Financiero]]|date=13 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Later that same day three new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 34.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-confirman-tres-nuevos-casos-lista-nid2343161|title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: confirman tres nuevos casos y la lista llega a 34|date=13 March 2020|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''14 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed eleven new cases in Buenos Aires and the provinces of Buenos Aires, Chaco, and [[Santa Fe Province|Santa Fe]], bringing the total to 45.<ref name=LaNacion45>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-se-sumaron-11-casos-nuevos-nid2343459|title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: se sumaron 11 casos nuevos y llegan a 45|date=14 March 2020|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|access-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''15 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed eleven new cases: 6 in Buenos Aires, 2 in Chaco, 2 in [[Tierra del Fuego Province, Argentina|Tierra del Fuego]] (first cases), and one in Buenos Aires Province.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nuevo Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Informe diario - 15 de marzo de 2020|url=https://www.argentina.gob.ar/sites/default/files/15032020-nuevo-coronavirus-covid-19.pdf|publisher=[[Ministry of Health (Argentina)|Ministry of Health of Argentina]]|accessdate=15 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> One of the cases in Chaco, the first announced this day, was of a 64-year-old woman who contracted the virus through casual contact.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chaco confirma un nuevo caso de coronavirus|url=https://www.ellitoral.com/index.php/id_um/230096-chaco-confirma-un-nuevo-caso-de-coronavirus-ya-son-6-en-esa-provincia-y-46-en-el-pais-salud.html|accessdate=16 March 2020|work=[[El Litoral]]|date=15 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''16 March:''' Nine new cases were confirmed by the national Ministry of Health in the City of Buenos Aires (5) and the provinces of Chaco (3) and Buenos Aires (1), bringing the total to 65.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nuevo Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Informe diario - 16 de marzo de 2020|url=https://www.argentina.gob.ar/sites/default/files/16-03-20-reporte-diario-covid-19.pdf|publisher=[[Ministry of Health (Argentina)|Ministry of Health of Argentina]]|accessdate=16 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Soon after in the night, the Governor of Chaco confirmed the provincial number of four more cases instead of three, bringing the total to 66.<ref name=Chaco11>{{cite news|title=Cuatro nuevos casos de coronavirus en el Chaco|url=https://www.datachaco.com/cuatro-nuevos-casos-coronavirus-el-chaco-n142350|website=datachaco.com|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=16 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Tierra del Fuego was put on lockdown later that day, becoming the first province to do so.<ref>{{cite news|title=Todo Tierra del Fuego queda en cuarentena hasta el 31 de marzo|url=https://www.infofueguina.com/tu-ciudad/2020/3/16/todo-tierra-del-fuego-queda-en-cuarentena-hasta-el-31-de-marzo-45257.html|website=infofueguina.com|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=16 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''17 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed fourteen new cases in the City of Buenos Aires (4), Buenos Aires Province (2), C\u00f3rdoba (2), Chaco (1), [[Jujuy Province|Jujuy]] (1), R\u00edo Negro (1), [[Salta Province|Salta]] (1), [[Entre R\u00edos Province|Entre R\u00edos]] (1), and [[Santa Cruz Province, Argentina|Santa Cruz]] (1), bringing the total to 79.<ref name=\"17mar\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/17/confirmaron-14-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-total-de-contagiados-asciende-a-79/|title=Confirmaron 14 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y el total de contagiados asciende a 79|date=17 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''18 March:''' 19 new cases were confirmed in the City of Buenos Aires (10), Buenos Aires Province (6), Chaco (1), C\u00f3rdoba (1), and Entre R\u00edos (1), and one case of the 14 reported the day before was reclassified, bringing the total to 97.<ref name=\"18mar\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-confirman-19-nuevos-casos-97-infectados_0_g5lkhqXH7.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: confirman 19 nuevos casos y ya son 97 los infectados|date=18 March 2020|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref> After the report from the Ministry of Health, it became known the third death from the virus.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: confirman un tercer muerto|url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-confirman-tercer-muerto_0_C62gkz0T4.html|quote=La tercera v\u00edctima se conoci\u00f3 despu\u00e9s de que el Ministerio de Salud de la Naci\u00f3n reportara 19 nuevos contagios de coronavirus|accessdate=20 March 2020|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|date=18 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''19 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed 31 new cases in the City of Buenos Aires (8), Buenos Aires Province (15), C\u00f3rdoba (3), Chaco (2), [[Tucum\u00e1n Province|Tucum\u00e1n]] (1), Santa Fe (1), and R\u00edo Negro (1), bringing the total to 128.<ref name=\"19mar\">{{cite news|title=Confirman 31 nuevos casos de coronavirus en el pa\u00eds|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/254103-confirman-31-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-el-pais|accessdate=20 March 2020|work=[[P\u00e1gina/12]]|date=20 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn the night, President [[Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez]] announced a mandatory quarantine, in effect from midnight on 20 March until 31 March.<ref name=\"quarantine\" /><ref name=\"lockdown\" />\n\n'''20 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed 30 new cases in the City of Buenos Aires (9) and the provinces of Buenos Aires (9), C\u00f3rdoba (4), [[Neuqu\u00e9n Province|Neuqu\u00e9n]] (2), Chaco, Tierra del Fuego, Entre R\u00edos, San Luis, [[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]], and [[Santiago del Estero Province|Santiago del Estero]] (one each). The number of confirmed cases has risen to 158.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: confirmaron otros 30 casos y ascienden a 158 los infectados|url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-confirmaron-13-casos-capital-aguarda-nuevo-parte-nacional_0_yKT2dQZPb.html|accessdate=21 March 2020|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|date=20 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''21 March:''' Another death was reported from the Province of Buenos Aires, bringing the total number of deaths in the country to four.<ref>{{cite web|title=Una mujer de 67 a\u00f1os se convirti\u00f3 en la cuarta muerte por coronavirus en la Argentina|url=https://www.telam.com.ar/notas/202003/443157-una-mujer-de-67-anos-se-convirtio-en-la-cuarta-muerte-por-coronavirus-en-la-argentina.html|agency=[[T\u00e9lam]]|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Later, the Ministry of Health confirmed 67 new cases in the City of Buenos Aires (29) and the provinces of Buenos Aires (15), Chaco (5), [[Mendoza Province|Mendoza]] (5), C\u00f3rdoba (4), Tierra del Fuego (3), Corrientes (2), Santa Fe (2), Tucum\u00e1n (1), and R\u00edo Negro (1), bringing the total to 225.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: en Argentina hay otras 67 personas contagiadas|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/254520-coronavirus-en-argentina-hay-otras-67-personas-contagiadas|accessdate=21 March 2020|work=[[P\u00e1gina/12]]|date=21 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed 41 new cases in the City of Buenos Aires (12), and the provinces of Buenos Aires (8), C\u00f3rdoba (8), Chaco (7), Tucum\u00e1n (5), and [[Misiones Province|Misiones]] (1). The number of confirmed cases has risen to 266.<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirmaron 41 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y el total de infectados asciende a 266|url=https://www.infobae.com/coronavirus/2020/03/22/confirmaron-41-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-total-de-infectados-asciende-a-266/|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|language=Spanish|work=[[Infobae]]}}</ref> After the national report, the Government of Misiones denied having a case in the province, and said the case belonged to the Province of C\u00f3rdoba,<ref name=MisionesNo>{{cite web|title=Comunicado de Prensa|url=https://salud.misiones.gob.ar/comunicado-de-prensa/|publisher=Ministry of Public Health of Misiones|accessdate=23 March 2020|language=Spanish|date=22 March 2020|quote=el paciente que fue informado recientemente en el reporte nacional de COVID 19, no reside en la provincia, por lo cual no es un caso detectado en Misiones}}</ref> and the Province of Santiago del Estero announced its second confirmed case.<ref name=Liberal2>{{cite news|title=Confirmaron el segundo caso positivo de coronavirus en Santiago del Estero|url=https://www.elliberal.com.ar/noticia/523880/confirmaron-segundo-caso-positivo-coronavirus-santiago-estero|accessdate=23 March 2020|work=[[El Liberal (Argentine newspaper)|El Liberal]]|date=22 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' Ministry of Health officials reported the coronavirus is spreading via \"community transmission\" in the City of Buenos Aires, its surroundings and some cities in Chaco, Tierra del Fuego and C\u00f3rdoba provinces. Also reported 51 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: se registr\u00f3 el primer caso de transmisi\u00f3n comunitaria|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/23/coronavirus-en-la-argentina-se-registro-el-primer-caso-sin-antecedente-de-viajes-o-contacto-estrecho-con-un-enfermo/|accessdate=24 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|date=23 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Later in the daily report, the Ministry of Health confirmed 36 new cases in the City of Buenos Aires (11) and the provinces of Buenos Aires (5), C\u00f3rdoba (3), Santa Fe (13) and Chaco (4). The number of confirmed cases has risen to 301.<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman 36 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/254887-confirman-36-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina|accessdate=24 March 2020|work=[[P\u00e1gina/12]]|date=23 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn the Province of Santa Fe, five inmates died during riots in two jails, amid tensions over coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|title=Motines en Santa Fe: confirmaron cinco muertos por los incidentes en los penales de Coronda y Las Flores|url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/policiales/2020/03/24/motines-en-carceles-confirmaron-que-son-tres-los-muertos-en-los-penales-de-corona-y-las-flores/|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[Infobae]]|date=24 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' In the morning, the Ministry of Health confirmed a total of 52 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: el Ministerio de Salud pidi\u00f3 que, si aumentan los casos, \"no pensemos que estamos peor\"|url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-ministerio-salud-pidio-aumentan-casos-pensemos-peor-_0_jQASeV6b7.html|accessdate=24 March 2020|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|date=24 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> The fifth death was reported, a 71-year-old man who had returned from Spain and was hospitalised in [[Mar del Plata]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Muri\u00f3 el primer paciente contagiado de coronavirus en Mar del Plata|url=https://www.lacapitalmdp.com/murio-el-primer-contagiado-de-coronavirus-de-mar-del-plata/|accessdate=24 March 2020|work=[[La Capital (Mar del Plata)|La Capital]]|date=24 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> and then a sixth death was reported in Chaco, a 53-year-old man without [[Comorbidity|comorbidities]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Conti|first1=Gonzalo|title=Un chaque\u00f1o de 53 a\u00f1os es el sexto muerto por conoravirus en Argentina|url=https://www.mdzol.com/sociedad/2020/3/24/un-chaqueno-de-53-anos-es-el-sexto-muerto-por-conoravirus-en-argentina-69032.html|accessdate=25 March 2020|date=24 March 2020|website=mdzol.com|language=Spanish}}</ref> Later, 86 new cases were confirmed with 30 being in the City of Buenos Aires, 30 in Buenos Aires Province, 9 in Chaco, 7 in C\u00f3rdoba, 4 in Tierra del Fuego, 3 in Santa Fe and 1 in Neuqu\u00e9n, [[La Pampa Province|La Pampa]], and Santa Cruz, bringing the total to 387.<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman 86 nuevos contagios de coronavirus en el pa\u00eds|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/255116-confirman-86-nuevos-contagios-de-coronavirus-en-el-pais|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[P\u00e1gina/12]]|date=25 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''25 March:''' In the morning, the Ministry of Health confirmed a total of 63 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vizzotti: \"No aflojemos porque el cumplimiento de las medidas va a definir la curva\"|url=https://www.telam.com.ar/notas/202003/444366-vizzott-no-aflojemos-porque-el-cumplimiento-de-las-medidas-va-a-definir-la-curva.html|accessdate=25 March 2020|agency=[[T\u00e9lam]]|date=25 March 2020|language=Spanish|quote=a la fecha fueron dados de alta 63 casos, indica el informe distribuido esta ma\u00f1ana}}</ref> Later new deaths were reported, two women hospitalized in the City of Buenos Aires and Chaco, bringing the death toll to eight.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: muri\u00f3 una mujer en la Ciudad de Buenos Aires y otra en Chaco y ya son 8 las v\u00edctimas fatales|url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-murio-mujer-ciudad-buenos-aires-7-victimas-fatales_0_eU7A59kJr.html|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|date=25 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> The Ministry of Health confirmed 117 new cases of which 21 belong to the City of Buenos Aires, 30 to Buenos Aires Province, 22 to Santa Fe, 15 to C\u00f3rdoba, 12 to Chaco, 5 to Santa Cruz, 4 to San Luis, 3 to Entre R\u00edos, 2 to Tucum\u00e1n and one each in the provinces of Mendoza, Neuqu\u00e9n and Tierra del Fuego. The number of confirmed cases has risen to 502.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ya hay 502 casos de coronavirus confirmados en el pa\u00eds|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/255379-ya-hay-502-casos-de-coronavirus-confirmados-en-el-pais|accessdate=26 March 2020|work=[[P\u00e1gina/12]]|date=26 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''26 March:''' In the morning, the Ministry of Health confirmed a total of 72 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: cu\u00e1ntas personas se recuperaron de la enfermedad en la Argentina|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-cuantas-personas-se-recuperaron-del-covid-19-nid2347700|accessdate=26 March 2020|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=26 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> The ninth death (and fourth in Chaco) was reported, a 59-year-old man who died the previous day and was diagnosed post-mortem.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Costa|first1=Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: un hombre que muri\u00f3 ayer en Chaco se convirti\u00f3 en la novena v\u00edctima|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-hombre-murio-ayer-chaco-se-nid2347766|accessdate=26 March 2020|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=26 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> Later, 87 new cases were confirmed with 30 in the City of Buenos Aires and 27 in Buenos Aires Province, 12 in Santa Fe, 3 in Chaco, 3 in C\u00f3rdoba, 3 in Neuqu\u00e9n, 3 in Tierra del Fuego, 2 in Jujuy, 2 in Santa Cruz, 1 in Mendoza and the other one in San Luis, raising the number of confirmed cases to 589. Also, four new deaths were reported, compared to the previous day report, raising the number of confirmed deaths to 12.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: 12 muertos y 589 infectados|url=https://www.lavoz.com.ar/ciudadanos/coronavirus-en-argentina-12-muertos-y-589-infectados|accessdate=27 March 2020|work=[[La Voz del Interior]]|date=26 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''27 March:''' In the morning, the Ministry of Health confirmed a total of 76 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Ya son 76 las personas que se recuperaron en la Argentina|url=https://tn.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-ya-son-76-las-personas-que-se-recuperaron-en-la-argentina_1052285|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=[[TN (TV channel)|TN]]|date=27 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> The death of a 59-year-old traumatologist who had travelled to Europe in Neuqu\u00e9n brought the country's death toll to thirteen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: muri\u00f3 un m\u00e9dico en Neuqu\u00e9n y ya son 13 los fallecidos en el pa\u00eds|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/255691-coronavirus-murio-un-medico-en-neuquen-y-ya-son-13-los-falle|accessdate=27 March 2020|work=[[P\u00e1gina/12]]|date=27 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> In the night report, the Ministry of health raised the number of deaths to seventeen, with 101 new and reclassified cases in the City of Buenos Aires (43) and the provinces of Buenos Aires (36), Santa Fe (9), Tucum\u00e1n (6), C\u00f3rdoba (5), Neuqu\u00e9n (4), Chaco (3), Entre R\u00edos (3), R\u00edo Negro (3), Corrientes (2), Mendoza (1), Santiago del Estero (1), and Misiones (1).<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Hay 17 muertos en la Argentina y 690 infectados|url=https://tn.com.ar/salud/lo-ultimo/coronavirus-hay-16-muertos-en-la-argentina-y-690-infectados_1052691|accessdate=28 March 2020|work=[[TN (TV channel)|TN]]|date=27 March 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''28 March:''' A new death was confirmed, a 51-year-old man from Mar del Plata that returned from a trip to Spain and Egypt. The man was diagnosed a week ago and was in the [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] under [[mechanical ventilation]], but did not register any previous condition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Palavecino |first1=Dar\u00edo |title=Coronavirus en Argentina: falleci\u00f3 un hombre en Mar del Plata y ya son los 18 muertos |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-fallecio-hombre-mar-del-plata-nid2348379 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=28 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Later the Ministry of Health confirmed 55 new cases, in the City of Buenos Aires (18) and the provinces of Santa Fe (13), Buenos Aires (8), Chaco (5), Corrientes (4), Tierra del Fuego (4), Neuqu\u00e9n (2), Mendoza (1), and C\u00f3rdoba (1). Also, another death was registered of an 84-year-old woman from the City of Buenos Aires that had contact with a person that travelled to Italy. Therefore, the number of cases rose to 745 and 19 fatal victims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: hubo dos muertes, pero la cantidad de casos diarios baj\u00f3 casi la mitad |url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-reportaron-55-casos-total-infectados-elevo-745_0_FeSXcvTXv.html |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Clar\u00edn |date=28 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March:''' 75 new cases were confirmed by the Ministry of Health on the City of Buenos Aires (13) and the provinces of C\u00f3rdoba (18), Buenos Aires (16), Santa Fe (13), Chaco (4), Tierra del Fuego (4), La Pampa (2), San Juan (1), La Rioja (1), Mendoza (1), Misiones (1) and Corrientes (1). Two new deaths were confirmed, one from a 58-year-old man from the Province of Buenos Aires that had contact with another confirmed case and had a history of [[Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease|COPD]], and a 50-year-old man from Tucum\u00e1n that recently returned from Europe with his wife that was the first case on the province. To this day there were 820 confirmed cases and 21 deaths.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Argentina: confirman tres muertos m\u00e1s y 75 nuevos infectados |url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-registran-muerto-75-nuevos-casos_0_cRma6qguF.html |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Clar\u00edn |date=29 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nLater, president [[Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez]] announced that the mandatory quarantine would be extended until April 12.<ref name=\"quarantine-extension\" />\n\n'''30 March:''' Four new deaths were confirmed, two men from the Province of Buenos Aires (58 and 67 years old), a 68-year-old woman from Neuqu\u00e9n that returned from Spain and another 77-year-old woman from Tucum\u00e1n that suffered from obesity, diabetes and hypertension and have travelled to Chile and Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Argentina: Se confirmaron 4 nuevas muertes y ya son 24 en total |url=https://la100.cienradios.com/coronavirus-en-argentina-se-confirmaron-4-nuevas-muertes-y-ya-son-24-en-total/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=La 100 |date=30 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> 146 new cases were confirmed in the Province of Buenos Aires (36), the City of Buenos Aires (34), Santa Fe (21), Chaco (12), Tierra del Fuego (11), Corrientes (10), C\u00f3rdoba (8), Neuqu\u00e9n (8), Mendoza (3) y Entre R\u00edos (3), bringing the total to 966 accumulated cases and 24 deaths.<ref>{{cite news |title=Con 146 nuevos contagios en 24 horas, el coronavirus suma 966 casos en Argentina |url=https://www.perfil.com/noticias/salud/con-146-nuevos-casos-confirmados-el-coronavirus-afecta-a-966-en-argentina.phtml?rd=1&rd=1 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Perfil |date=30 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''31 March:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed 88 new cases in Santa Fe (22), the City of Buenos Aires (19), the Province of Buenos Aires (17), C\u00f3rdoba (14), Tierra del Fuego (7), Chaco (3), Mendoza (2), R\u00edo Negro (1), Corrientes (1), Misiones (1), and Tucum\u00e1n (1).<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron 88 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina, y el total de infectados asciende a 1054 |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/03/31/confirmaron-88-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-total-de-infectados-asciende-a-1054/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=31 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Three new deaths were also confirmed, three women from Chaco (63 years old), La Rioja (52) and C\u00f3rdoba (89). The number of cases now rose to 1,054 and 27 fatal victims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Argentina: murieron tres mujeres y ya son 27 los fallecidos en el pa\u00eds |url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-fallecio-mujer-chaco-muertos-ascienden-25_0_7P9Ga3DEP.html |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Clar\u00edn |date=31 March 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n'''1 April:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed 79 new cases in Chaco (12), Santa Fe (11), the City of Buenos Aires (10), Santa Cruz (10), the Province of Buenos Aires (10), Mendoza (10), C\u00f3rdoba (6), Neuqu\u00e9n (4), Salta (2), Entre R\u00edos (1), Corrientes (1), San Luis (1), and Tucum\u00e1n (1).<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron 79 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y el n\u00famero de infectados asciende a 1.133 |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/01/confirmaron-79-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-numero-de-infectados-asciende-a-1133/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=1 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Six new deaths were confirmed, a 71-year-old man from the Province of Buenos Aires, the 66-year-old Chilean consul in Santa Fe, a 55-year-old rabbi from the City of Buenos Aires, a 78-year-old man from Neuqu\u00e9n, a 73-year old from Mendoza, and a 61-year-old woman from the Province of Buenos Aires. The number of cases are 1,133 and the death toll has risen to 33.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: se registraron 33 muertes en Argentina |url=https://radiomitre.cienradios.com/coronavirus-se-registraron-33-muertes-en-argentina/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Radio Mitre |date=1 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''2 April:''' 132 new cases were confirmed in the City of Buenos Aires (24) and the provinces of Buenos Aires (36), Tierra del Fuego (24), C\u00f3rdoba (16), Santa Fe (8), Neuqu\u00e9n (4), Tucum\u00e1n (4), Chaco (3), La Rioja (3), San Luis (2), Jujuy (2), Entre R\u00edos (2), Santa Cruz (2), Santiago del Estero (1) and Corrientes (1).<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron 132 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y el n\u00famero de infectados asciende a 1.265 |url=https://www.infobae.com/politica/2020/04/02/confirmaron-132-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-numero-de-infectados-asciende-a-1265/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=2 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Also, four new deaths were registered (a 73-year-old man from Mendoza, a 61-year-old from Chaco and a 41-year-old from the Province of Buenos Aires), bringing the death toll to 37 and the number of total confirmed cases to 1,265.<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirman 37 muertos por COVID-19 en Argentina |url=https://www.a24.com/politica/confirman-37-muertos-covid19-argentina-03042020_m9G2rzN-e |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=A24 |date=2 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''3 April:''' 88 new cases were confirmed, from the City of Buenos Aires (28), and the provinces of Buenos Aires (22), C\u00f3rdoba (14), Santa Fe (8), Chaco (8), Entre R\u00edos (2), Mendoza (2), Neuqu\u00e9n (1), R\u00edo Negro (1), San Luis (1) and Tierra del Fuego (1).<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron 88 nuevos casos de coronavirus en la Argentina y el n\u00famero de infectados asciende a 1.353 |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/03/confirmaron-88-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-y-el-numero-de-infectados-asciende-a-1353/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=3 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Five new deaths were registered: two men from the Province of Buenos Aires (87 and 72 years old), a 60-year-old man from Chaco, a 76-year-old man of Spanish nationality living in Mendoza, and a 53-year-old woman from the Province of Buenos Aires. There are 1353 confirmed cases and 42 fatal victims to this day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron que ya son 42 las v\u00edctimas fatales por coronavirus en la Argentina |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/03/se-confirmo-una-nueva-muerte-por-coronavirus-y-ya-son-40-las-victimas-fatales-en-la-argentina/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=3 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''4 April:''' The Ministry of Health announced that 98 new cases were registered, from the City of Buenos Aires (34) and the Provinces of Buenos Aires (26), Chaco (8), Tierra del Fuego (8), R\u00edo Negro (5), Santa Fe (5), Neuqu\u00e9n (4), C\u00f3rdoba (3), La Rioja (2), Santa Cruz (1), Santiago del Estero (1) and Tucum\u00e1n (1). A 73-year-old man from the Province of Buenos Aires died, bringing the number of deaths to 43.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Se registraron 98 nuevos contagios y una muerte en las \u00faltimas 24 horas |url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/257558-coronavirus-se-registraron-98-nuevos-contagios-y-una-muerte- |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=P\u00e1gina 12 |date=4 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''5 April:''' On this day, 103 new cases were confirmed and the death toll rose to 48 fatal victims (two of them died after the Ministry of Health's nightly official report).<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron dos nuevos muertos por coronavirus y la cantidad de v\u00edctimas asciende a 48 |url=https://www.infobae.com/coronavirus/2020/04/05/confirmaron-dos-muertes-y-103-nuevos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-en-las-ultimas-24-horas/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=5 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''6 April:''' The Ministry of Health announced that 74 new cases were confirmed in the last 24 hours, bringing the number of total confirmed cases to 1,628. Five new deaths were reported, three men from the City of Buenos Aires, a man from the Province of Buenos Aires, and another man from Neuqu\u00e9n, making the number of deaths rise to 53. Also, it was reported that 325 people were discharged to this day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron cinco nuevas muertes y 74 casos de coronavirus en la Argentina: el total de contagiados asciende a 1.628 |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/06/confirmaron-cinco-nuevas-muertes-y-74-casos-de-coronavirus-en-la-argentina-el-total-de-contagiados-asciende-a-1628/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=6 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''7 April:''' 87 new cases and seven new deaths were reported, bringing the total number of cases to 1,715 and the number of deaths to 60.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: hay 87 nuevos caso positivos y las muertes llegan a 60 |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-nid2351871 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=7 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''8 April:''' President [[Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez]] announced that the mandatory quarantine would be extended beyond 12 April, with \"flexibilisation\" of few activities only.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Argentina: la cuarentena se extender\u00e1 hasta el jueves 23 y ser\u00e1 menos flexible de lo que se esperaba |url=https://www.clarin.com/politica/cuarentena-extendera-jueves-23-flexible-esperado_0_Oapxli-B4.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Clar\u00edn |date=7 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Later, the Ministry of Health confirmed 80 new cases and five new deaths; The number of confirmed cases has risen to 1,795 and the number of total deaths to 65, while the number of recoveries is now 358.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: se registraron 80 casos positivos nuevos y el total de muertos lleg\u00f3 a 65 |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-son-80-casos-positivos-nuevos-nid2352322 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=8 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''9 April:''' The Ministry of Health announced that 99 new cases were confirmed in the last 24 hours, bringing the number of total confirmed cases to 1,894. 14 new deaths were reported, making the number of deaths rise to 79, and the number of recoveries has risen to 365.<ref>{{cite news |title=Se registr\u00f3 el d\u00eda con m\u00e1s muertes por coronavirus en Argentina: 14 fallecidos y el total de v\u00edctimas fatales asciende a 79 |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/09/se-registro-el-dia-con-mas-muertes-por-coronavirus-en-argentina-10-fallecidos-y-el-total-de-victimas-fatales-asciende-a-79/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=9 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''10 April:''' 81 new cases and three new deaths were reported, bringing the total number of cases to 1,975 and the number of deaths to 82.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: confirmaron 81 casos y 3 nuevas muertes en las \u00faltimas 24 horas |url=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-confirmaron-81-casos-3-nuevas-muertes-ultimas-24-horas_0_tAr9vJ9CH.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=Clar\u00edn |date=10 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In the night, President Fern\u00e1ndez confirmed that the lockdown would be extended until 26 April in major cities,<ref name=\"extension26apr\" /> and that the flexibilisation of restrictions in zones with lesser risk would be analysed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: la cuarentena continuar\u00e1 hasta el 26 de abril, pero se flexibilizar\u00e1 en zonas del interior |url=https://www.clarin.com/politica/coronavirus-argentina-cuarentena-continuara-igual-grandes-ciudades-administrara-zonas-interior_0_BARh39KmC.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=Clar\u00edn |date=10 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''11 April:''' On this day, 162{{efn|Excluding five [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Falkland Islands|confirmed cases]] on the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute|claimed territory]] of the [[Falkland Islands]] included by the report of the Ministry of Health.}} new cases were confirmed by the Ministry of Health in the Argentinian territory, the highest to this date, and the death toll rose to 89 fatal victims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron seis nuevas muertes por coronavirus y 167 casos en las \u00faltimas 24 horas |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/11/confirmaron-seis-nuevas-muertes-por-coronavirus-y-167-casos-en-las-ultimas-24-horas/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=11 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''12 April:''' The Ministry of Health announced that 66 new cases were confirmed in the last 24 hours, bringing the number of total confirmed cases to 2,203. Five new deaths were reported, making the number of deaths rise to 94, and the number of recoveries has risen to 467.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Argentina: se registraron 5 nuevas muertes, y son 95 las v\u00edctimas fatales, mientras que 66 personas dieron positivo en las \u00faltimas 24 horas |url=https://www.infobae.com/coronavirus/2020/04/12/coronavirus-en-argentina-se-registraron-4-nuevas-muertes-y-son-95-las-victimas-fatales-mientras-que-66-personas-dieron-positivo-en-las-ultimas-24-horas/ |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=12 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''13 April:''' The Ministry of Health confirmed 69 new cases and three new deaths; The number of confirmed cases has risen to 2,272 and the number of total deaths to 98, while the number of recoveries is now 514.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 69 nuevos casos en Argentina |url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/259492-coronavirus-69-nuevos-casos-en-argentina |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=P\u00e1gina 12 |date=13 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''14 April:''' 160{{efn|Excluding six new [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Falkland Islands|confirmed cases]] on the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute|claimed territory]] of the [[Falkland Islands]] included by the report of the Ministry of Health.}} new cases and seven new deaths were reported, bringing the total number of cases to 2,432 and the number of deaths to 105.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: 166 nuevos casos y son 2443 en todo el pa\u00eds |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/sociedad/coronavirus-argentina-nid2354214 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |date=14 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''15 April:''' The Ministry of Health announced that 128 new cases were confirmed in the last 24 hours, bringing the number of total confirmed cases to 2,560. Seven new deaths were reported, making the number of deaths rise to 112, and the number of recoveries has risen to 595.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en la Argentina: confirmaron siete muertes y 128 casos nuevos en las \u00faltimas 24 horas |url=https://www.infobae.com/coronavirus/2020/04/15/confirmaron-siete-muertes-y-128-casos-nuevos-de-coronavirus-en-las-ultimas-24-horas-el-total-de-contagiados-asciende-a-2571/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=15 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n'''16 April:''' On this day, 98 new cases and 10 deaths were confirmed by the Ministry of Health, bringing the number of total confirmed cases to 2,658  and the death toll to 122 fatal victims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Confirmaron 10 nuevas muertes y otros 98 casos de coronavirus en Argentina: el total de infectados asciende a 2.669 |url=https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/16/confirmaron-10-nuevas-muertes-y-otros-98-casos-de-coronavirus-en-argentina-el-total-de-infectados-asciende-a-2669/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Infobae |date=16 April 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<div style=\"overflow-x:auto;>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Argentina medical cases}}\n{{clear}}\n<!--\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Provinces\n!Deaths\n!Recoveries\n|-\n|{{Flag|Buenos Aires|name=City of B