Iceman Challenge IV''']] | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Strongman Champions League#2013|2013 Latvia]] | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordSecond | [[Strongman Champions League#2013|2013 Germany]] | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | [[Strongman Champions League#2015|2015 '''SCL Iceman Challenge ''']] | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[J\u00f3n P\u00e1ll Sigmarsson Classic]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordSecond | 2010 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2012 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Iceland's Strongest Man]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordThird | 2010 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2011 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2012 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2013 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2014 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2015 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2016 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2017 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2018 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2019 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Strongest Man in Iceland]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2010 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2011 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2012 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2016 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2017 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Iceland's Strongest Viking]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2010 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2011 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2012 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[Westfjord's Viking]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFourth | 2009 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2010 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2011 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2012 | }}\n{{CompetitionRecordCompetition|[[OK Budar Strongman Championships]] }}\n{{CompetitionRecordFirst | 2010 | }}\n}}\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r met Icelandic strongman [[Magn\u00fas Ver Magn\u00fasson]] at his gym \"Jakab\u00f3l\" in 2008, and Magn\u00fas said that Haf\u00fe\u00f3r seemed a good prospect as a strongman.<ref name=\"ironmind1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/May/Magnus_Ver_Magnusson-Icelandic_Strongman_Scout.html |title=Magnus Ver Magnusson: Icelandic Strongman Scout |author=Randall J. Strossen|website=[[IronMind]] |date=29 May 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> Haf\u00fe\u00f3r won several strongman contests in Iceland in 2010 including Strongest Man in Iceland,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grindavik.is/v/5659|title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus sterkasti ma\u00f0ur \u00e1 \u00cdslandi|website=Vefs\u00ed\u00f0an Grindav\u00edkurb\u00e6jar|date=8 June 2010|accessdate=5 April 2018|language=Icelandic}}</ref> Iceland's Strongest Viking, Westfjords Viking,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vodvafikn.net/profils/64-aflraunamenn/1224-haftor-julius-bjoernsson.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706022835/http://vodvafikn.net/profils/64-aflraunamenn/1224-haftor-julius-bjoernsson.html |archive-date=6 July 2010|title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson|website=vodvafikn.net}}</ref> and five of six events at the OK Badur Strongman Championships.<ref name=ironmind>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/Aug/Hafthor_Juliusson_Bjornsson_Wins_Icelandxs_OK_Budar_Strongman_Contest.html |title=Haff\u00fe\u00f3r [sic] J\u00fal\u00edusson Bj\u00f6rnsson wins Iceland's OK Budar Strongman Contest| website=[[IronMind]] |author=Randall J. Strossen |date=10 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210205412/http://ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/Aug/Hafthor_Juliusson_Bjornsson_Wins_Icelandxs_OK_Budar_Strongman_Contest.html |archive-date= 10 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r finished in second place at the inaugural [[J\u00f3n P\u00e1ll Sigmarsson Classic]] in November 2010, behind [[Brian Shaw (strongman)|Brian Shaw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2010/Nov/Brian_Shaw_Wins_the_Inaugural_Jon_Pall_Sigmarsson_Classic_Strongman_Contest.html| title=Brian Shaw Wins the Inaugural Jon Pall Sigmarsson Classic Strongman Contest |author=Randall J. Strossen |website=[[IronMind]] | date=22 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> He won the 2011 [[Strongest Man in Iceland]] contest on 4 June 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2011/Jun/Hafthor_Julius_Bjornsson_Wins_the_Strongest_Man_in_Iceland.html|title=Hafthor Julius Bjornsson Wins the Strongest Man in Iceland|website=[[IronMind]]|author=Randall J. Strossen |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> and the 2011 [[Iceland's Strongest Man]] contest on 18 June 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2011/Jun/Hafthor_Julius_Bjornsson_Wins_Icelandxs_Strongest_Man.html|title=Hafthor Julius Bjornsson Wins Iceland's Strongest Man |website=[[IronMind]]|author=Randall J. Strossen |date=19 June 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> He placed fourth in the [[Giants Live]] Poland 2011 event on 6 August 2011.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn January 2015, at the [[World's Strongest Viking]] competition held in Norway, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r carried a {{convert|10|m|ft|adj=mid|-long}}, {{convert|650|kg|adj=mid}} log for five steps, thus breaking a 1,000-year-old record set by [[Orm Storolfsson]].<ref name=\"IBT\">{{cite web|url=http://ironmind.com/news/Hafthor-Wins-Worlds-Strongest-Viking-Sets-Sights-on-Worlds-Strongest-Man/|title=Hafthor Wins World's Strongest Viking, Sets Sights on World's Strongest Man|work=[[IronMind]] |author=Randall J. Strossen |date=1 January 2015 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===World's Strongest Man===\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r took part in [[World's Strongest Man]] after earning a wild card invitation to the [[2011 World's Strongest Man|2011]] contest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ironmind.com/ironmind/opencms/Articles/2011/Aug/Giants_Live_Poland-Radzikowskix_Jenkins_and_Baron_Make_WSM_Cut...Bjornsson_Gets_Wild_Card.html |title=Giants Live\u2013Poland: Radzikowski, Jenkins and Baron Make WSM Cut . . . Bjornsson Gets Wild Card |author=Randall J. Strossen |website=[[IronMind]] |date=8 August 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> He came in sixth overall. Taking part again in ensuing years, he placed third in 2012, 2013 and 2015. He finished runner-up in 2014 event<ref name=wp>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2014/05/19/game-of-thrones-villain-is-second-strongest-man-in-the-world/|author=Cindy Boren|title='Game of Thrones' villain is second-strongest man in the world|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> to [[\u017dydr\u016bnas Savickas]] and again in the 2016 event to [[Brian Shaw (strongman)|Brian Shaw]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2014/04/01/hafthor-julius-runner-worlds-strongest-man-comp |title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Runner up in World's Strongest Man Comp |website=[[Iceland Review]] |author=P\u00e1ll Stef\u00e1nsson |date=1 April 2014 |accessdate=7 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408130518/http://icelandreview.com/news/2014/04/01/hafthor-julius-runner-worlds-strongest-man-comp |archive-date=8 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2017, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r once again was runner up, this time to [[Eddie Hall]].<ref>{{Cite Web|url=https://barbend.com/2017-worlds-strongest-man-results/ |title=Breaking: Eddie Hall Wins 2017 World's Strongest Man in Botswana |website= BarBend|author=BarBend Team |date=27 May 2017 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> Haf\u00fe\u00f3r won the 2018 World's Strongest Man,<ref name=WSM2018a>{{cite web|title=Breaking News: Hafthor Bjornsson Wins 2018 World's Strongest Man in Manila|url=https://barbend.com/2018-worlds-strongest-man-results/|website=BarBend|author=BarBend Team|accessdate=6 May 2018|date=6 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=WSM2018b>{{cite web|title='The Mountain' Hafthor Bjornsson Crowned 2018 World's Strongest Man|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2774532-the-mountain-hafthor-bjornsson-crowned-2018-worlds-strongest-man|website=Bleacher Report|author=Tom Sunderland|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> thus becoming the first Icelander to win the title since [[Magn\u00fas Ver Magn\u00fasson]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/sports/Hafthor-Bjornsson-worlds-strongest-man-mountain.html|title =The Mountain from Game of Thrones Wins World's Strongest Man Title|website =The New York Times|first =Victor|last =Mather|date =7 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Arnold Strongman Classic ===\nOn 3 March 2018, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r broke the Elephant Bar deadlift world record with his successful {{convert|472|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} third attempt, as well as being champion of the Arnold Strongman Classic 2018. The previous Elephant Bar deadlift world record of {{convert|468|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} was set by Jerry Pritchett at the Arnold Strongman Classic 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://canoe.com/entertainment/celebrity/game-of-thrones-the-mountain-sets-new-strongman-record|title=Game of Thrones' 'The Mountain' sets new strongman record|date=7 March 2018|work=[[Canoe.com]]|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Arnold Strongman Classic - Rogue Elephant Bar Deadlift - Full Live Stream Event 4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=InSl_bG-A7w|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[Rogue Fitness]]|date=4 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r defended his title at the Arnold Strongman Classic 2019; he finished on 45 points, 4.5 points ahead of runner-up [[Martins Licis]]. He also improved on his elephant bar world record, increasing it to {{convert|474|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} with his second attempt. He tried for {{convert|501|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} in his third attempt but was unsuccessful.<ref>[https://barbend.com/hafthor-bjornsson-2019-arnold-strongman-classic/ Hafthor Bjornsson Wins 2019 Arnold Strongman Classic (Plus Final Results)] Barbend</ref><ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-04/game-of-thrones-the-mountain-breaks-deadlift-world-record/10866688 Game of Thrones star Hafthor Julius Bjornsson, aka 'The Mountain', breaks his own deadlift world record] [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]]</ref>\n\nAfter successfully defending his crown Haf\u00fe\u00f3r became only the second person to win 3 Arnold Strongman Classics in a row (2018, 2019 and 2020) after [[Zydrunas Savickas]].\n\n==Acting career==\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r was cast as Ser [[Gregor Clegane|Gregor \"The Mountain\" Clegane]] for the [[Game of Thrones (season 4)|fourth season]] of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' in August 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://winteriscoming.net/2013/08/mountain-recast/|title=Mountain Recast|author=Ours is the Fury|publisher=WinterIsComing.net|date=30 August 2013|accessdate=30 August 2013}}</ref> This was his first main acting role, and he is the third person to depict the character after [[Conan Stevens]] played the role in [[Game of Thrones (season 1)|season 1]] and [[Ian Whyte (actor)|Ian Whyte]] in [[Game of Thrones (season 2)|season 2]]. He became the first actor to portray Clegane in more than one continuous season with his appearances in seasons four through eight. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WatchersOTWall/status/510783858657071105|title=The Mountain in Belfast, and Game of Thrones filming in Split continues despite flooding |publisher=Watchers On The Wall|date=13 September 2014|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> Haf\u00fe\u00f3r was cast for the role of Mongkut in the 2017 film ''[[Kickboxer: Retaliation]].''\n\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r played the lead role in the Philadelphia Renaissance Faire during their debut season in 2015. He appeared as \"King Thor\", the leader of a Viking raiding party intent on capturing the city of Amman.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.phillymag.com/ticket/2015/04/08/game-of-throness-the-mountain-coming-to-philly-ren-faire/ |author= Dan McQuade |title=Mountain Comes to Philly Ren Faire|magazine=[[Philadelphia (magazine)|Philadelphia Magazine]]|date=8 April 2015|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n=== Family and relationships ===\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r was born in [[Reykjav\u00edk]].<ref name=\"nyt\" /> His father, Bj\u00f6rn, stands at {{height|cm=203}},<ref name=\"ironmind\" /> and his mother, Ragnhei\u00f0ur, is of similarly tall stature.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Haf\u00fe\u00f3r's grandfather, Reynir, is {{height|cm=207}}<ref name=\"ironmind\" /> and \"just as broad across the chest\". Reynir recalled in 2014 that Haf\u00fe\u00f3r worked on the family farm outside [[Reykjav\u00edk]] as a child and \"was always big, even when he wasn't tall\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|url =https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/sports/icelandic-strongman-does-heavy-lifting-on-a-second-career-as-an-actor.html|title =Icelandic Strongman Does Heavy Lifting on a Second Career as an Actor|website =[[The New York Times]]|date=1 November 2014  |first =Sam |last =Borden |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r has a daughter, Theresa L\u00edf, with former girlfriend Thelma Bj\u00f6rk Steimann.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/1sonSBgLj5/|title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson on Instagram: \"My daughter Theresa L\u00edf - beautiful design from her mother :) repost via @instarepost20 from @thelmasteimann All about the maxi dress\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://icelandmag.is/article/strongman-mountain-facing-new-serious-accusations-domestic-violence|title=Strongman \"The Mountain\" facing new serious accusations of domestic violence|work=Icelandmag|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://icelandmag.is/article/strongman-mountain-denies-accusations-domestic-violence-threatens-suing-libel|title=Strongman \"The Mountain\" denies accusations of domestic violence, threatens suing for libel|work=Icelandmag|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2018/05/08/controversial-figure-mountain-becomes-worlds-strongest-man|title=Controversial Figure \"The Mountain\" Becomes World's Strongest Man|last=\u0106iri\u0107|first=Jelena|date=8 May 2018|work=Iceland Review|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.looper.com/110519/everything-dont-know-mountain/|title=Everything you don't know about The Mountain|website=Looper.com|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2018|date=21 February 2018}}</ref> Until early 2017, he was in a relationship with Andrea Sif J\u00f3nsd\u00f3ttir whom he met at a gym. They lived together in Reykjavik.  In an online video interview by Mulligan Brothers published 21 December 2019, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r laments not having seen his daughter in three years.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hafthor Bjornsson - Story of 'The Mountain' {{!}} One Of The Most Compelling & Emotional Interviews EVER|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RQoQrqk6-Ng|language=en|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\nHafthor did some grip traning with luke stoltman and tom stoltman before icelands strongest man 2019\nSince late 2017, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r had been dating Kelsey Henson, a Canadian waitress. The two met when Haf\u00fe\u00f3r was in [[Alberta]], [[Canada]] for a strongman competition and visited the bar where Henson worked. The couple garnered much attention for the difference in their respective heights, as Henson is {{height|cm=157}}.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/These-photos-of-The-Mountain-from-Game-of-Thrones-and-his-tiny-girlfriend-have-baffled-Instagram-users/articleshow/62054121.cms|title=These photos of The Mountain from 'Game of Thrones' and his tiny girlfriend have baffled Instagram users|work=Business Insider|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.journalpost.com/enterainment/kelsey-henson-mountain-kisses/|title=Kelsey Henson, the Mountain's Girlfriend, Tells Her Fans How She Kisses Him|website=www.journalpost.com|access-date=30 September 2018|date=9 April 2018}}</ref> On 21 October 2018, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r announced on his Instagram page that he and Henson are married.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BpKmOUnC1dE|title=It is with great pleasure...|first=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r|last=Bj\u00f6rnsson|date=21 October 2018|website=Instagram|accessdate=21 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12146745|title=Enormous Game of Thrones star Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson ties the knot with girlfriend|first=Christine|last=Rendon|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=23 October 2018}}</ref>\nOn 11 April, 2020, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r announced on his Instagram page, that he and Henson were expecting their first child together. \n<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|https://www.instagram.com/p/B-z_b2HAd1i/?igshid=1bfzpenroftf5</ref>\n\n=== Tattoos ===\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r has several tattoos including those in relation to [[Norse deities]] and the [[Vikings|Viking]] culture. He also has a tattoo of [[J\u00f3n P\u00e1ll Sigmarsson]] on his calf.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a18801982/twenty-four-hours-with-the-mountain/|title=Twenty-Four Hours With The Mountain|date=2 March 2017|work=Men's Health|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Citation|last=Men's Health|title=24 Hours With The Mountain|date=20 April 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lAZobMyRy8o|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r and his former girlfriend Andrea have spoken about his occasional sleep troubles after a heavy meal due to his body weight.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn March 2017, he was diagnosed with [[Bell's palsy]].<ref>{{cite web|title='The Mountain' Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson has Bell's palsy|url=https://theconversation.com/the-mountain-haf-or-julius-bjornsson-has-bells-palsy-heres-what-it-means-75601|website=theconversation.com|date=6 April 2017 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Endorsements ==\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r is a brand ambassador for [[SodaStream]], a company involved in manufacture of a device for making carbonated water at home. He has appeared in advertisements of the brand promoting environmental awareness and collaborated in one with fellow ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' actor [[Hannah Waddingham]] (who played [[Septa Unella]]).<ref>{{Citation|last=SodaStream|title=SodaStream's Join the Revolution|date=31 January 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b5FoXLxpFPk|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Shame or Glory|title=HeavyBubbles\u2122 - Uncut|date=1 April 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_XGd8w9RhUM|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Shame or Glory|title=Shame or Glory|date=14 November 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S_EuNmQOpbw|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Icelandic Mountain Vodka ===\nIn 2016, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r co-founded the spirits brand Icelandic Mountain Vodka. The main focus of the company is a seven-time distilled Icelandic [[vodka]], as well as having a gin production.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/icelandic-mountain-vodka-commercial-game-of-thrones/1555599 |title=The Mountain's Amazing New Alcohol Is Basically A \"Game Of Thrones\" Vodka |website=[[Elite Daily]] |author=Jake Cappuccino |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Icelandic Mountain Spirits|title=Icelandic Mountain Vodka\u2122 A day with Hafthor|date=10 July 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c19HRM0x-lA|access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal records==\n===Strongman===\n''Set at competitive meets:''\n* [[Arnold Strongman Classic#Regular events|Tire deadlift]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{convert|460|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} ''raw with wrist straps''<ref name=\"Gawker\">{{cite web|url=http://gawker.com/watch-the-mountain-from-game-of-thrones-deadlift-almost-1586066070|title=Watch The Mountain from Game of Thrones Deadlift Almost 1,000 Pounds|author=Jay Hathaway|publisher=Gawker.com|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=5 June 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Deadlift]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{convert|474|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} ''Elephant bar, raw with wrist straps'' (Arnold Strongman Classic 2019, World Record)<ref name=\"Arnold 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://barbend.com/hafthor-bjornsson-474kg-elephant-bar/ |website=BarBend.com |title=Hafthor Bjornsson Deadlifts a 474kg Elephant Bar World Record (Closely Misses 501kg)|author=Jake Boly |date=1 March 2019|accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n* Log press&nbsp;\u2013 {{convert|213|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} (Europe's Strongest Man 2018) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XndyEyIfd-8|title=Europe's Strongest Man 2018 - Log Lift 213kg - Thor|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[Europe's Strongest Man]]|date=7 April 2018|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n* Log carry \u2013 [5 steps] {{convert|650|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}}<ref name=\"Viking\">{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2352774-the-mountain-from-game-of-thrones-breaks-1000-year-old-weightlifting-record|title=The Mountain from 'Game of Thrones' Breaks 1,000-Year-Old Weightlifting Record|author=Kyle Newport |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=3 February 2015| accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Keg toss]] \u2013 {{convert|7.15|m|ft|abbr=on|0}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://barbend.com/hafthor-bjornsson-strongman-keg-toss-record/ |title=Hafthor Bjornsson Breaks His Own Keg Toss World Record in Botswana |author=BarBend Team |website= BarBend.com |date=15 August 2016 |access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Keg toss]] \u2013 8 kegs in 16.35 seconds (World's Strongest Man 2014). Strongman record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://strongman.org/news/worlds-strongest-man-2014/ |title=World's Strongest Man 2014|website=Strongman.org|date=19 March 2014|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Set in the gym:''\n*[[Deadlift]] \u2013 480 kg (1,058 lb) ''Replica Elephant bar, raw with wrist straps''<ref>{{Citation|last=Hafthor Bjornsson|title=480KG/1058LBS DEADLIFT UNOFFICIAL WORLD RECORD RAW!!|date=15 February 2020|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6t3OU5rsR28|website=[[YouTube]] |access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Powerlifting===\n''Set at competitive meets:''\n*[[Squat (exercise)|Squat (with wraps)]] \u2013 {{convert|440|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} (Thor's Powerlifting Challenge 2018)<ref name=\"power\">{{cite web |title=Hafthor Bjornsson Puts Up Big Total At Powerlifting Meet |url=https://barbend.com/hafthor-bjornsson-powerlifting-meet/ |website=BarBend |author=Jake Boly | date=17 December 2018 | accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Bench press]] \u2013 {{convert|250|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} (Thor's Powerlifting Challenge 2018)<ref name=\"power\"/>\n* [[Deadlift]] \u2013 {{convert|410|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} (Thor's Powerlifting Challenge 2018)<ref name=\"power\"/>\n* Total - {{convert|1100|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} (Thor's Powerlifting Challenge 2018)<ref name=\"power\"/>\n\n''Set in the gym:''\n* [[Squat (exercise)|Squat]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{convert|440|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} ''raw''<ref name=\"Floelite\">{{cite web|url=https://www.floelite.com/articles/6034679-hafthor-bjornsson-destroys-a-440kg970lb-squat|title=Hafthor Bjornsson Destroys A 440kg/970lb Squat|author=Armen Hammer|publisher=Floelite.com|date=7 November 2017|accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Bench press]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{convert|245|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}} ''raw''<ref>{{cite web|url =https://barbend.com/thor-bjornsson-245kg-bench-press/|title =Thor Bjornsson PRs His Bench Press With 245 Kilograms, 2 Weeks Out From Powerlifting Meet|quote =245kg/539lbs bench PR on my 30th birthday!|website =BarBend|author=Nick English|date =27 November 2018|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n|''Zon 261'' (aka \"Operation Ragnarok\") \n| Big John&nbsp;\u2013 Icelandic Viking Squad\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Devilish Deeds''\n| Psycho Phil Bell\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Beast''\n| The Beast\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Kickboxer: Retaliation]]''\n| Mongkut\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Hamlet Pharon''\n| Frank\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2012\u20132019\n| ''[[The World's Strongest Man]]''\n| Himself&nbsp;\u2013 competitor\n|\n|-\n| 2014\u20132019\n| ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\n| [[Gregor Clegane]]\n| Recurring role\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[A League of Their Own (British game show)|A League of Their Own]]''\n| Himself\n| Series 9, Episode 7\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Heavy Bubbles''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Born Strong]]''\n| Himself&nbsp;\u2013 competitor\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Keith Lemon: Coming to America''\n| Himself\n| Series 1, Episode 6\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[E:60]], How the World's Strongest Man became 'The Mountain' on Game of Thrones''\n| Himself\n| Original air date; 14 April 2019\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{clear}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson}}\n* {{official|http://www.hafthorbjornsson.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=5485781}}\n* [http://basketball.eurobasket.com/player/Hafthor_Bjornsson/FSU_Selfoss/77879 \"Hafthor Bjornsson basketball profile\"]. Eurobasket.\n\n<!-- First name indexed category. -->\n{{Footer - World's Strongest Man Champions}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bjornsson, Hafthor Julius}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Icelandic strength athletes|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:Icelandic male weightlifters|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:Icelandic men's basketball players|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:Icelandic male television actors|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:\u00darvalsdeild karla basketball players|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Reykjav\u00edk|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:Brei\u00f0ablik men's basketball players|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n[[Category:KR men's basketball players|Hafthor Julius Bjornsson]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Icelandic strongman and actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Icelandic name|Haf\u00fe\u00f3r}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name         = Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson\n| image        = Bj\u00f6rnsson Arnold Classic 2017.jpg\n| image_size   = 250px\n| caption      = Haf\u00fe\u00f3r in March 2017\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|11|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Reykjav\u00edk]], [[Iceland]]\n| occupation   = Strongman, actor\n| years_active = 2010\u2013present (strongman)\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Kelsey Henson|2018}}\n| height = 205 cm\n| weight = 200 kg\n| website      = {{url|hafthorbjornsson.com}}\n| module       =\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n|embed=yes\n| name = Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson\n| image =\n| position = [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| league = Icelandic Basketball League\n| team =\n| number =\n| nationality =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| highschool =\n| college =\n| draft_year =\n| career_start = 2004\n| career_end = 2008\n| years1 = 2004\u20132005\n| team1 = [[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]]\n| years2 = 2005\u20132006\n| team2 = [[FSu Selfoss basketball|FSu]]\n| years3 = 2006\u20132007\n| team3 = [[KR (basketball club)|KR]]\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008\n| team4 = [[FSu Selfoss basketball|FSu]]\n| highlights =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson''' ({{IPA-is|\u02c8haf\u03b8our \u02c8ju\u02d0lij\u028fs \u02c8pj\u0153r\u0325s\u0254\u02d0n|lang|Is-Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson.ogg}}; often [[transliteration|transliterated]] as '''Hafthor'''; born 26 November 1988) is an Icelandic professional strongman and actor. He is the first person to have won the [[Arnold Strongman Classic]], [[Europe's Strongest Man]] and [[World's Strongest Man]] in the same calendar year.<ref name=WSM2018a/><ref name=WSM2018b/> He played [[Gregor Clegane|Gregor \"The Mountain\" Clegane]] in the HBO series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' for five seasons. He also is a former professional basketball player.\n\nBorn in [[Reykjav\u00edk]], Haf\u00fe\u00f3r began his basketball career in 2004 with [[1. deild karla (basketball)|Division I]] team [[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]], moving to [[FSu Selfoss basketball|FSu]] in 2005. He transferred to [[\u00darvalsdeild karla (basketball)|Premier League]] side [[KR (basketball club)|KR]] in 2006 before returning to FSu in 2007. He helped FSu to promotion from Division I to the Premier League but his career was cut short in 2008 due to a recurrent ankle injury. He subsequently began his strongman career.\n\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r won the [[Strongest Man in Iceland]] event in 2010, and won [[Iceland's Strongest Man]] in 2011. He won Europe's Strongest Man in 2014, a feat he repeated in 2015, 2017, 2018, and 2019. He won silver at the 2017 Arnold Strongman Classic, improving to gold in 2018, 2019 and 2020. He competed in his first World's Strongest Man in 2011, placing sixth. He won three bronze and three silver medals in his next six attempts before being crowned champion in 2018.\n\n==Basketball career==\nHaf\u00fe\u00f3r began his athletic career as a [[basketball]] player. At {{height|meters=2.06}},<ref name=r1>{{cite web|title=Hafthor Bjornsson|url=http://www.strongman.org/athletes/hafthor-bjornsson/|website=www.strongman.org|publisher=Strongman|accessdate=18 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611184904/http://www.strongman.org/athletes/hafthor-bjornsson/|archive-date=11 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> he started his senior team career with Division I club [[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]] in 2004, playing as a [[center (basketball)|center]]. In 2005 he joined [[FSu Selfoss basketball|FSu Selfoss]], also in the Icelandic Division I. After 10 games it was discovered that he had been playing with a broken bone in his ankle and would require surgery. After recovering from surgery, Haf\u00fe\u00f3r moved to [[\u00darvalsdeild karla (basketball)|\u00darvalsdeild]] powerhouse [[KR (basketball club)|KR]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kr.is/karfa/hafthor-bjornsson-genginn-til-lids-vid-kr/|  title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r Bj\u00f6rnsson genginn til li\u00f0s vi\u00f0 KR |author=K\u00f6rfuknattleiksdeild |language=Icelandic |date= 11 July 2006 |accessdate= 4 March 2018}}</ref> He missed most of the 2006\u20132007 season after a screw in his ankle shattered and had to be fixed by another surgery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kr.is/karfa/hafthor-julius-bjornsson-leikur-ekki-meira-a-thessari-leiktid |title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson leikur ekki meira \u00e1 \u00feessari leikt\u00ed\u00f0 |language=Icelandic|author=Drengjaflokkur, K\u00f6rfuknattleiksdeild |date=12 November 2006 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2007\u20132008 season, he moved back to play for FSu Selfoss. He averaged 6.7 points per game,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gamli.kki.is/mot/1500002686_FSU_________.htm |title=FSu 2007-2008 statistics  |language=Icelandic |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> helping the team achieve promotion to the \u00darvalsdeild,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mbl.is/sport/korfubolti/2008/04/02/fsu_i_urvalsdeildina_i_korfu_karla/ |title=FSu \u00ed \u00farvalsdeildina \u00ed k\u00f6rfu karla |newspaper =[[Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0]] |language=Icelandic| date=2 April 2008|accessdate= 4 March 2018}}</ref> but the troublesome ankle forced him to retire from basketball after the season, at the age of 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hafthorbjornsson.com/about/ |title=About Haf\u00fe\u00f3r |website= hafthorbjornsson.com |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dv.is/folk/2017/4/11/hafthor-julius-ofvirki-skagastrakurinn-sem-breyttist-i-vodvafjall/| title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus: Ofvirki Skagastr\u00e1kurinn sem breyttist \u00ed v\u00f6\u00f0vafjall| author=Editorial(DV) |language=Icelandic |publisher=[[DV (newspaper)|DV]] |date=11 April 2017 |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2006 Haf\u00fe\u00f3r played 32 games for the [[Iceland men's national basketball team|Icelandic junior national basketball teams]].<ref name=kki.is>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kki.is/landslid/karlar/leikjafjoldi/unglinga-og-drengja/ |title=Landsli\u00f0 unglinga- og drengja |work=[[Icelandic Basketball Federation]]|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> In 2006 he played 8 games with Iceland's U-18 national team in Division A of the [[2006 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|U18 European Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/compID_8aYeHlfuGF-mF5IqO8aFH1.season_2006.roundID_4888.teamID_300.playerID_43824.html |title=FIBA Europe - Hafthor Bjornsson |work=[[FIBA Europe]] |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Strongman career==\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson\n| image = File:Hafth\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson Scottish Stone Put.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| caption = At the 2015 Caledonian Club Highland Games\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| known = \n| occupation = [[Strongman (strength athlete)|Strongman]]\n| sport = \n| height = 206 cm<ref name=bio>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/athletes/hafthor-bjornsson/ |title=Haf\u00fe\u00f3r Bj\u00f6rnsson |website=theworldsstrongestman.com |accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|180-200|kg|lb|0}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/game-of-thrones-star-named-2018-worlds-strongest-man|title='Game of Thrones' star named 2018 World's Strongest Man |website=[[Fox News]] |author=Zoe Szathmary |date=7 May 2018 |accessdate= 16 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=r1/> \n| show-medals = yes\n| pb = '''Deadlift''': {{convert|474|kg|1}} raw (2019, '''WR''')\n| medaltemplates =